{"title_page": "Krishnadasi", "text_new": "{{Use Indian English|date=August 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2015}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = Krishnadasi <br> \u0b95\u0bbf\u0bb0\u0bc1\u0bb7\u0bcd\u0ba3\u0ba4\u0bbe\u0b9a\u0bbf\n| image                    = \n| caption                  = Cover photo for ''Krishnadasi''\n| genre                    = Soap opera\n| creator                  = \n| based_on                 = [[Devadasi]] practice and Krishnadasi novel by [[Indra Soundar Rajan]]\n| writer                   = [[Indra Soundar Rajan]]\n| director                 = [[Prabhoo Nepaul]]\n| starring                 = [[Gemini Ganesan]] <br> [[Nalini (actress)|Nalini]] <br> \n[[Nagesh]] <br> [[Vietnam Veedu Sundaram]] <br> [[Ranjitha]] <br>   Suja Raghuram <br> [[Aravind Akash]]\n| country                  = [[Tamil Nadu]]\n| language                 = [[Tamil language|Tamil]]\n| num_episodes             = 359\n| list_episodes            = \n| producer                 = [[Prabhoo Nepaul]]\n| company                  = Prabhoo Nepaul Telefilms\n| theme_music_composer     = [[D. Imman]]\n| opentheme                = \"Sigaram Parthai\"<br>(vocals)<br>[[Nithyasree Mahadevan]]<br>\n[[D. Imman]]<br>Kadhal Mathi (lyrics)\n| location                 = [[Tamil Nadu]]\n| cinematography           = \n| editing                  = \n| camera                   = [[Multi-camera]]\n| runtime                  = Approx. 20-22 minutes per \nepisode\n| channel                  = \n| first_aired              = {{start date|df=yes|2000|02|14|}}\n| last_aired               = {{End date|df=yes|2002|10|25|}}\n| status                   = \n| preceded_by              = \n| followed_by              = [[Alaigal]]\n| related                  = [[Krishnadasi (2016 TV series)|Krishnadasi]]\n| production_website       = \n| image_alt                = \n| num_seasons              = 1\n| network                  = [[Sun TV (India)|Sun TV]]<br>[[Raj TV]]\n| first_run                = \n| released                 = \n}}\n\n'''''Krishnadasi''''' ({{lang-ta|\u0b95\u0bbf\u0bb0\u0bc1\u0bb7\u0bcd\u0ba3\u0ba4\u0bbe\u0b9a\u0bbf}}) is a [[Tamil language|Tamil]] language soap opera aired on [[Sun TV (India)|Sun TV]]. It aired from 14 February 2000 to 25 October 2002 at 7:30 PM every Monday to Friday. The show stars veteran actors [[Gemini Ganesan]] and [[Nagesh]] (guest appearance only) alongside [[Nalini (actress)|Nalini]], [[Vietnam Veedu Sundaram]], [[Ranjitha]], [[Aravind Akash]] and [[Suja Raghuram]]. The show was produced by [[Prabhoo Nepaul]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindu.com/2001/01/04/stories/13040784.htm |title=Calling the shots, daringly |publisher=The Hindu |date=2001-01-04 |accessdate=2016-12-01}}</ref> It is based on the novel written by [[Indra Soundar Rajan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/report/tv-south-tamil-indra-soundarrajan-on-yamirukka-bayamaen/20100305.htm |title='I now know that there is a God' - Rediff.com Movies |publisher=Rediff.com |date= |accessdate=2016-12-01}}</ref> The title track was composed by [[D. Imman]] and sung by [[Nithyasree Mahadevan]]. Prabhoo Nepaul was the first Producer/Director to introduce Music Director D. Imman into the film and TV industry. It was Producer Prabhoo Nepaul who moved D. Imman's career from a musician to giving him the opportunity and chance of being a Music Director.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newindianexpress.com/entertainment/tamil/article59868.ece |title=I prefer melody to pacy songs: Imman |publisher=The New Indian Express |date= |accessdate=2016-12-01}}</ref>\n\n==Remarks==\n* Krishnadasi marked the debut of the actor [[Gemini Ganesan]] in Television and his last performance in a character.\n* Krishnadasi also marked the re-entry of actress [[Nalini (actress)|Nalini]] into the media after a 14-year hiatus she took after getting married.\n* Krishnadasi title sequence is the first song composed by the now famous music director [[D. Imman]].\n\n==Cast==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Actor !! Character Name !! Character Description\n|-\n| [[Ranjitha]]|| '''Krishnaveni'''|| a [[devadasi|dasi]] by birth, Meenatchi's mother and Manonmani's daughter - keeping the information about Meenatchi's father a secret for many years for reasons only known to her. Gowri's best friend.\n|-\n| [[Nalini (actress)|Nalini]]|| '''Manonmani'''|| a dasi by birth, Krishnaveni's mother and Meenatchi's grandmother.\n|-\n| [[Gemini Ganesan]]|| '''Rudramuthi Sastri'''|| Sawaminatha Sastri, and Gowri's father.\n|-\n| Suja Raghuram|| '''Meenaatchi'''||a dasi by birth, Krishnaveni's daughter and Manonmani's granddaughter.\n|-\n| [[Vietnam Veedu Sundaram]]|| '''Saama'''|| a procurer.\n|-\n| Rajasekhar || '''Swaminatha Sastri'''(Deetchadhar)|| Rudhramurthi Sastri's son - father to six children, five daughters and one son.\n|-\n| Vijayalakshmi || '''Santhanalakshmi'''|| Swaminatha Sastri's wife - mother to six children, five daughters and one son.\n|-\n| [[Aravind Akash]]- Credited as Arvinder Singh || '''Sunderesan'''|| Swaminatha Sastri's sixth child and only son.\n|-\n| [[Anju (actress)|Anju]]|| '''Lecturer Kalyani'''|| Santhanalaksmi's sister. She became a widow on the same day she got married and remained a widow.\n|-\n| \"Kalaimamani\" Naanjil Nalini|| '''Pachaiamma'''|| village midwife, extorts Manonnmani to safeguard a secret of hers.\n|-\n| Menaka || '''Gayathri'''|| Swaminatha Sastri's fifth child and youngest daughter. \n|-\n| Manjari- Credited as Vinothini || '''Gowri'''/Gloria(after marriage)|| Rudhramurthi Sastri's daughter, married a man from a different religion against the wishes of her family. Krishnaveni's best friend.\n|-\n| David Ramesh|| '''David'''|| Gowri's husband, Rudhramurthi Sastri's son-in-law.\n|-\n| [[Raja Ravindra]]|| '''Muthukumarasaamy'''|| A brother figure to Krishnaveni and her well-wisher.\n|-\n| K.Manogar|| '''Godhandam'''|| Swaminatha Sastri's fourth son-in-law.\n|-\n| --|| '''Visaalaatchi'''|| Swaminatha Sastri\u2019s third daughter.\n|-\n|-\n| Shobana|| '''Sunandha'''|| Swaminatha Sastri\u2019s first daughter. Lives in Mumbai. Tries to marry her daughter to her brother Sunderesan.\n|-\n|-\n| Shanthi Ganesh|| '''Sulochana'''|| Swaminatha Sastri\u2019s second daughter. Lives in Delhi. Tries to marry her daughter to her brother Sunderesan.\n|-\n|-\n| --|| '''Sowmya'''|| Sugandha's daughter. Tries to marry Sunderesan.\n|-\n|-\n| --|| '''Maya'''|| Sulochana's daughter. Tries to marry Sunderesan.\n|-\n| --|| '''Kokila'''(Koki)|| Swaminatha Sastri\u2019s fourth daughter.\n|-\n| Rindhya || '''Indrani'''|| Meenaatchi\u2019s friend from college.\n|}\n\n==Plot==\nThis serial revolved around the [[Devadasi]] practice that prevailed in [[Tamil Nadu]] almost a few years after [[India|India's]] independence and how the dasi women are treated by the society. The story followed the rivalry between Rudramuthi Sastri, a very powerful Brahman in that village and his family and Manonmani, the dasi of the village and her family in the small hamlet of Kandhanallur on the banks of the river [[Kaveri]].\n\nManonmani, a dasi comes back to her ancestral village of '''Kandhanallur''' with her daughter, Krishnaveni after 15 years of exile from the village where she, her daughter and baby granddaughter, Meenaatchi, were exiled by the village's people. As soon as she arrives, she goes to meet Rudhramoorthi Sastri and his son Saminatha Sastri and vows that she will wreak havoc in their perfect lives like they wrecked hers 15 years ago.\n\nMeanwhile,  Saminatha Sastri's son, Sunderesan falls in love with Meenaatchi while they are studying at the college. Krishnaveni never revealed who was Meenatchi's father to anyone for reasons only known to her but Meenaatchi is determined to find out the truth. Pachiamma, the village midwife extorts Manonmani to safeguard a secret known only to them.\n\nGowri, Rudhramoorthi Sastri's daughter married a Christian man, David and because of that, her mother committed suicide. They have a son, Kirubakaran. Her family never forgave her and cut all ties with her. She is suffering from cancer now.\n\nWhat is the reason for enmity between Manonmani and Rudhramoorthy Sastri? Why was Manonmani's family exiled from the village in the first place? Did Manonmani wreak havoc in Rudhramoorthi Sastri's family? Who is Meenaatchi's father and why is Krishnaveni keeping this a secret? What is the secret between Manonmani and Pachaiamma? What is the fate of the relationship between Sunderesan and Meenaatchi?  These are the questions that are answered in the course of this serial with lots of twists and turns.\n\n==Remake==\nKrishnadasi was remade in [[Hindi]] under the same title, [[Krishnadasi (2016 TV series)|Krishnadasi]], starring [[Shravan Reddy]] and [[Sana Amin Sheikh]] on [[Colours (TV channel)|Colors]] with significant changes in the story.\n\n==YouTube release==\n\nThe episodes of Krishnadasi are being officially released by the production house in their KPTV YouTube channel in the second half of 2018, more than 18 years after the premiere of episode 1 of Krishnadasi on Sun TV in the year 2000. The uploading of the episodes was stopped after 127 episodes for some unknown reasons.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of programs broadcast by Sun TV]]\n* [[List of TV shows aired on Sun TV (India)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/user/VisionTimeTamizh Vision Time on YouTube]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20141007220928/http://www.suntvnetwork.in/tv-channel-details.aspx?Channelid=1&channelname=SUN%20TV&LanguageID=1&Type=q Official website] {{in lang|en}}\n* [https://www.youtube.com/suntv Sun TV on YouTube]\n* [http://www.suntv.in/ Sun TV Network] {{in lang|en}}\n* [http://www.sun.in Sun Group] {{in lang|en}}\n\n{{Sun TV shows}}\n\n[[Category:Sun TV television series]]\n[[Category:Tamil-language television soap operas]]\n[[Category:Tamil Nadu drama television series]]\n[[Category:2000 Tamil-language television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2002 Tamil-language television series endings]]\n[[Category:Tamil-language television programs]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Indian English|date=August 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2015}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = Krishnadasi <br> \u0b95\u0bbf\u0bb0\u0bc1\u0bb7\u0bcd\u0ba3\u0ba4\u0bbe\u0b9a\u0bbf\n| image                    = \n| caption                  = Cover photo for ''Krishnadasi''\n| genre                    = Soap opera\n| creator                  = \n| based_on                 = [[Devadasi]] practice and Krishnadasi novel by [[Indra Soundar Rajan]]\n| writer                   = [[Indra Soundar Rajan]]\n| director                 = [[Prabhoo Nepaul]]\n| starring                 = [[Gemini Ganesan]] <br> [[Nalini (actress)|Nalini]] <br> \n[[Nagesh]] <br> [[Vietnam Veedu Sundaram]] <br> [[Ranjitha]] <br>   Suja Raghuram <br> [[Aravind Akash]]\n| country                  = [[Tamil Nadu]]\n| language                 = [[Tamil language|Tamil]]\n| num_episodes             = 359\n| list_episodes            = \n| producer                 = [[Prabhoo Nepaul]]\n| company                  = Prabhoo Nepaul Telefilms\n| theme_music_composer     = [[D. Imman]]\n| opentheme                = \"Sigaram Parthai\"<br>(vocals)<br>[[Nithyasree Mahadevan]]<br>\n[[D. Imman]]<br>Kadhal Mathi (lyrics)\n| location                 = [[Tamil Nadu]]\n| cinematography           = \n| editing                  = \n| camera                   = [[Multi-camera]]\n| runtime                  = Approx. 20-22 minutes per \nepisode\n| channel                  = \n| first_aired              = {{start date|df=yes|2000|02|14|}}\n| last_aired               = {{End date|df=yes|2002|10|25|}}\n| status                   = \n| preceded_by              = \n| followed_by              = Indira\n| related                  = [[Krishnadasi (2016 TV series)|Krishnadasi]]\n| production_website       = \n| image_alt                = \n| num_seasons              = 1\n| network                  = [[Sun TV (India)|Sun TV]]<br>[[Raj TV]]\n| first_run                = \n| released                 = \n}}\n\n'''''Krishnadasi''''' ({{lang-ta|\u0b95\u0bbf\u0bb0\u0bc1\u0bb7\u0bcd\u0ba3\u0ba4\u0bbe\u0b9a\u0bbf}}) is a [[Tamil language|Tamil]] language soap opera aired on [[Sun TV (India)|Sun TV]]. It aired from 14 February 2000 to 25 October 2002 at 7:30 PM every Monday to Friday. The show stars veteran actors [[Gemini Ganesan]] and [[Nagesh]] (guest appearance only) alongside [[Nalini (actress)|Nalini]], [[Vietnam Veedu Sundaram]], [[Ranjitha]], [[Aravind Akash]] and [[Suja Raghuram]]. The show was produced by [[Prabhoo Nepaul]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hindu.com/2001/01/04/stories/13040784.htm |title=Calling the shots, daringly |publisher=The Hindu |date=2001-01-04 |accessdate=2016-12-01}}</ref> It is based on the novel written by [[Indra Soundar Rajan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/report/tv-south-tamil-indra-soundarrajan-on-yamirukka-bayamaen/20100305.htm |title='I now know that there is a God' - Rediff.com Movies |publisher=Rediff.com |date= |accessdate=2016-12-01}}</ref> The title track was composed by [[D. Imman]] and sung by [[Nithyasree Mahadevan]]. Prabhoo Nepaul was the first Producer/Director to introduce Music Director D. Imman into the film and TV industry. It was Producer Prabhoo Nepaul who moved D. Imman's career from a musician to giving him the opportunity and chance of being a Music Director.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newindianexpress.com/entertainment/tamil/article59868.ece |title=I prefer melody to pacy songs: Imman |publisher=The New Indian Express |date= |accessdate=2016-12-01}}</ref>\n\n==Remarks==\n* Krishnadasi marked the debut of the actor [[Gemini Ganesan]] in Television and his last performance in a character.\n* Krishnadasi also marked the re-entry of actress [[Nalini (actress)|Nalini]] into the media after a 14-year hiatus she took after getting married.\n* Krishnadasi title sequence is the first song composed by the now famous music director [[D. Imman]].\n\n==Cast==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Actor !! Character Name !! Character Description\n|-\n| [[Ranjitha]]|| '''Krishnaveni'''|| a [[devadasi|dasi]] by birth, Meenatchi's mother and Manonmani's daughter - keeping the information about Meenatchi's father a secret for many years for reasons only known to her. Gowri's best friend.\n|-\n| [[Nalini (actress)|Nalini]]|| '''Manonmani'''|| a dasi by birth, Krishnaveni's mother and Meenatchi's grandmother.\n|-\n| [[Gemini Ganesan]]|| '''Rudramuthi Sastri'''|| Sawaminatha Sastri, and Gowri's father.\n|-\n| Suja Raghuram|| '''Meenaatchi'''||a dasi by birth, Krishnaveni's daughter and Manonmani's granddaughter.\n|-\n| [[Vietnam Veedu Sundaram]]|| '''Saama'''|| a procurer.\n|-\n| Rajasekhar || '''Swaminatha Sastri'''(Deetchadhar)|| Rudhramurthi Sastri's son - father to six children, five daughters and one son.\n|-\n| Vijayalakshmi || '''Santhanalakshmi'''|| Swaminatha Sastri's wife - mother to six children, five daughters and one son.\n|-\n| [[Aravind Akash]]- Credited as Arvinder Singh || '''Sunderesan'''|| Swaminatha Sastri's sixth child and only son.\n|-\n| [[Anju (actress)|Anju]]|| '''Lecturer Kalyani'''|| Santhanalaksmi's sister. She became a widow on the same day she got married and remained a widow.\n|-\n| \"Kalaimamani\" Naanjil Nalini|| '''Pachaiamma'''|| village midwife, extorts Manonnmani to safeguard a secret of hers.\n|-\n| Menaka || '''Gayathri'''|| Swaminatha Sastri's fifth child and youngest daughter. \n|-\n| Manjari- Credited as Vinothini || '''Gowri'''/Gloria(after marriage)|| Rudhramurthi Sastri's daughter, married a man from a different religion against the wishes of her family. Krishnaveni's best friend.\n|-\n| David Ramesh|| '''David'''|| Gowri's husband, Rudhramurthi Sastri's son-in-law.\n|-\n| [[Raja Ravindra]]|| '''Muthukumarasaamy'''|| A brother figure to Krishnaveni and her well-wisher.\n|-\n| K.Manogar|| '''Godhandam'''|| Swaminatha Sastri's fourth son-in-law.\n|-\n| --|| '''Visaalaatchi'''|| Swaminatha Sastri\u2019s third daughter.\n|-\n|-\n| Shobana|| '''Sunandha'''|| Swaminatha Sastri\u2019s first daughter. Lives in Mumbai. Tries to marry her daughter to her brother Sunderesan.\n|-\n|-\n| Shanthi Ganesh|| '''Sulochana'''|| Swaminatha Sastri\u2019s second daughter. Lives in Delhi. Tries to marry her daughter to her brother Sunderesan.\n|-\n|-\n| --|| '''Sowmya'''|| Sugandha's daughter. Tries to marry Sunderesan.\n|-\n|-\n| --|| '''Maya'''|| Sulochana's daughter. Tries to marry Sunderesan.\n|-\n| --|| '''Kokila'''(Koki)|| Swaminatha Sastri\u2019s fourth daughter.\n|-\n| Rindhya || '''Indrani'''|| Meenaatchi\u2019s friend from college.\n|}\n\n==Plot==\nThis serial revolved around the [[Devadasi]] practice that prevailed in [[Tamil Nadu]] almost a few years after [[India|India's]] independence and how the dasi women are treated by the society. The story followed the rivalry between Rudramuthi Sastri, a very powerful Brahman in that village and his family and Manonmani, the dasi of the village and her family in the small hamlet of Kandhanallur on the banks of the river [[Kaveri]].\n\nManonmani, a dasi comes back to her ancestral village of '''Kandhanallur''' with her daughter, Krishnaveni after 15 years of exile from the village where she, her daughter and baby granddaughter, Meenaatchi, were exiled by the village's people. As soon as she arrives, she goes to meet Rudhramoorthi Sastri and his son Saminatha Sastri and vows that she will wreak havoc in their perfect lives like they wrecked hers 15 years ago.\n\nMeanwhile,  Saminatha Sastri's son, Sunderesan falls in love with Meenaatchi while they are studying at the college. Krishnaveni never revealed who was Meenatchi's father to anyone for reasons only known to her but Meenaatchi is determined to find out the truth. Pachiamma, the village midwife extorts Manonmani to safeguard a secret known only to them.\n\nGowri, Rudhramoorthi Sastri's daughter married a Christian man, David and because of that, her mother committed suicide. They have a son, Kirubakaran. Her family never forgave her and cut all ties with her. She is suffering from cancer now.\n\nWhat is the reason for enmity between Manonmani and Rudhramoorthy Sastri? Why was Manonmani's family exiled from the village in the first place? Did Manonmani wreak havoc in Rudhramoorthi Sastri's family? Who is Meenaatchi's father and why is Krishnaveni keeping this a secret? What is the secret between Manonmani and Pachaiamma? What is the fate of the relationship between Sunderesan and Meenaatchi?  These are the questions that are answered in the course of this serial with lots of twists and turns.\n\n==Remake==\nKrishnadasi was remade in [[Hindi]] under the same title, [[Krishnadasi (2016 TV series)|Krishnadasi]], starring [[Shravan Reddy]] and [[Sana Amin Sheikh]] on [[Colours (TV channel)|Colors]] with significant changes in the story.\n\n==YouTube release==\n\nThe episodes of Krishnadasi are being officially released by the production house in their KPTV YouTube channel in the second half of 2018, more than 18 years after the premiere of episode 1 of Krishnadasi on Sun TV in the year 2000. The uploading of the episodes was stopped after 127 episodes for some unknown reasons.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of programs broadcast by Sun TV]]\n* [[List of TV shows aired on Sun TV (India)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/user/VisionTimeTamizh Vision Time on YouTube]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20141007220928/http://www.suntvnetwork.in/tv-channel-details.aspx?Channelid=1&channelname=SUN%20TV&LanguageID=1&Type=q Official website] {{in lang|en}}\n* [https://www.youtube.com/suntv Sun TV on YouTube]\n* [http://www.suntv.in/ Sun TV Network] {{in lang|en}}\n* [http://www.sun.in Sun Group] {{in lang|en}}\n\n{{Sun TV shows}}\n\n[[Category:Sun TV television series]]\n[[Category:Tamil-language television soap operas]]\n[[Category:Tamil Nadu drama television series]]\n[[Category:2000 Tamil-language television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2002 Tamil-language television series endings]]\n[[Category:Tamil-language television programs]]\n", "name_user": "Akiran267", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Krishnadasi"}
{"title_page": "Bhandup", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2018}}\n{{more citations needed|date=August 2012}}\n\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Bhandup\n| other_name                      = Bhandupeshwar\n| settlement_type                 = Suburban\n| image_skyline                   = \n| image_alt                       = \n| image_caption                   = \n| nickname                        = \n| map_alt                         = \n| map_caption                     = \n| pushpin_map                     = Mumbai\n| pushpin_label_position          = \n| pushpin_map_alt                 = \n| pushpin_map_caption             = \n| coordinates                     = {{coord|19.14|N|72.93|E|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = {{flag | India}}\n| subdivision_type1               = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_name1               = [[Maharashtra]]\n| subdivision_type2               = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Mumbai Suburban district|Mumbai Suburban]]\n| subdivision_type3               = Metro (Ward) s \"ward\"\n| subdivision_name3               = \n| subdivision_type4               = [[Talukas of Maharashtra|Taluka/Tehsil]]\n| subdivision_name4               = [[Kurla]]\n| established_title               = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date                = 1803\n| founder                         = \n| named_for                       = \n| government_type                 = \n| governing_body                  = \n| leader_title1                   = [[Maharashtra Legislative Assembly|M.L.A]]\n| leader_name1                    = [[Ramesh Korgaonkar]] <br /> [[Shiv Sena]] (since 2019)\n| leader_title2                   = [[Parliament of India|M.P.]]\n| leader_name2                    = [[Manoj Kotak]] <br /> [[BJP]] (since 2019)\n| unit_pref                       = Metric\n| area_footnotes                  = \n| area_rank                       = \n| area_total_km2                  = \n| elevation_footnotes             = \n| elevation_m                     = 5.205\n| population_total                = 6,91,227\n| population_as_of                = 2001 Census\n| population_rank                 = \n| population_density_km2          = auto\n| population_demonym              = Bhandupkar\n| population_footnotes            = \n| demographics_type1              = Languages\n| demographics1_title1            = Official\n| demographics1_info1             = [[Marathi language|Marathi]]\n| timezone1                       = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1                     = +5:30\n| postal_code_type                = [[Postal Index Number|PIN]]\n| postal_code                     = 400078 (West) and 400042 (East)\n| blank1_name_sec1                = [[Lok Sabha]] constituency\n| blank1_info_sec1                = [[Mumbai North East (Lok Sabha constituency)|Mumbai North East]]\n| blank2_name_sec1                = [[Vidhan Sabha]] constituency\n| blank2_info_sec1                = [[Bhandup West (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Bhandup West]]\n| registration_plate              = MH-03\n| website                         = https://mumbaisuburban.gov.in/\n| footnotes                       = \n| official_name                   = \n}}\n'''Bhandup''' is a suburban community within the Municipal Corporation of [[Mumbai]], in the state of [[Maharashtra]], [[India]]. The name ''Bhandup'' is derived from ''Bhandupeshwar'', one of the names of the [[Hinduism|Hindu]] god [[Shiva]]. An old temple dedicated to Lord Shiva, the Bhandupeshwar Mahadev Mandir, is located in Bhandup. Sonapur signal is north lead line on L.B.S. Marg and south is dockyard colony.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Ganpati Visarjan - Bhandup west.jpg|thumb|left|2016 Ganpati Visarjan ([[Ganesh Chaturthi]]) - Bhandup west]]\nBhandup is one of the oldest suburbs in Mumbai.{{citation needed|date=December 2018}} It is home to Shivaji Talao, or Shivaji Lake, named after the [[Maratha]] ruler, [[Chhatrapati Shivaji]]. Devotees of [[Ganapati]] immerse idols of the elephant god Ganesh at the lake during the months of August through September, as well as in Bhandupeshwar Kundh in Bhandup Village East near the Eastern Express Highway.{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}\n\nThe earliest records of Bhandup come from 1803, and show the contemporary Bhandup [[Estate (house)|estate]] to comprise Bhandup, [[Nahur]] and [[Kanjur Marg]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pb8IAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA44-IA1|title=Gazetteer of the Bombay Presidency: Tha'na. Places of Interest.|last=|first=|publisher=Government Central Press|year=1882|isbn=|volume=Vol. XIV|location=Bombay|pages=44\u201345}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Silaharas]], also known as [[Shilahara]], was a mixture of people of [[Dravidian peoples|Dravidian]] ancestry and the [[Kayastha]] Prabhus from [[Konkan]]. The [[Silaharas]] promoted socio-economic progress in the 11th century around Bombay. To control the regions in Bombay and Thane, the built the ''Rajapatha'', passing from the north of Bhandup, following the current Bombay-Thane road.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/risebombayaretr00edwagoog|title=The Rise of Bombay, A Retrospect|last=Edwardes|first=S. M.|publisher=Government of Bombay|year=1902|isbn=|location=Bombay|pages=[https://archive.org/details/risebombayaretr00edwagoog/page/n114 17]}}</ref>\n\nHistorical records indicate that the distillery at Bhandup was one of the two biggest sources of [[liquor]] in the [[Bombay Presidency]], the other being the [[Uran]] distillery.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JAobAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA455|title=General Report on the Administration of the Bombay Presidency, For the Year 1873-74|last=|first=|publisher=Government of Bombay|year=1875|isbn=|location=Bombay|pages=455\u2013456}}</ref>\n\nBhandup was also one of the first [[railway]] stations in India. The first train ran between [[Bori Bunder]] and [[Thane]] on 16 April 1853 with 400 passengers aboard 14 railway carriages, at 3:35 pm. It is said that the idea to connect Bombay with Thane and [[Kalyan, India|Kalyan]] occurred to Mr. George Clark, the Chief Engineer of the Bombay Government, on a visit to Bhandup in 1843.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.asiatradehub.com/India/railways.asp |title=Indian Railways-Introduction |access-date=2008-10-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081016092740/http://www.asiatradehub.com/India/railways.asp |archive-date=2008-10-16 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.irfca.org/~mrinal/irhistory2.html|title=Development of Railways in India|website=Indian Railways Fan Club|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180315181011/http://www.irfca.org/~mrinal/irhistory2.html|archive-date=2018-03-15|url-status=dead|access-date=2019-04-14}}</ref>\n\nHowever, Bhandup was not a part of Bombay until 1950, when the boundaries of the Bombay municipal corporation were extended up to [[Andheri]] on the western side and Bhandup on the eastern side.{{Citation needed|date=April 2019}}\n\n==Demographics==\nBhandup falls within the S-ward, as defined by the [[Municipal Corporation of Greater Mumbai]]. The population of Bhandup has risen exponentially in the last twenty years.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://mmrda.maharashtra.gov.in/documents/10180/6867434/Population+and+Employment+Profile.pdf|title=Population and Employment Profile of Mumbai Metropolitan Region|last=Pendharkar|first=S. P.|date=2003-09-01|website=Mumbai Metropolitan Region Development Authority|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190414190143/https://mmrda.maharashtra.gov.in/documents/10180/6867434/Population+and+Employment+Profile.pdf|archive-date=2019-04-14|url-status=live|access-date=2019-04-14}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\"\n|-\n! Census Year\n! Population\n! Density per square km\n! % change in population from previous year\n! Sex ratio (females/1000 males)\n|-\n| 1981\n| 2,97,108\n| 7860\n| NA\n| 740\n|-\n| 1991\n| 5,68,028\n| 15,027\n| 91%\n| 813\n|-\n| 2001\n| 6,91,227\n| 10,800\n| 21%\n| 823\n|}\n*''The discordance between population and density could be due to re-drawing of ward boundaries''\n\nThe majority of residents of Bhandup are [[Hindus]] by religion. The dominant language is [[Marathi language|Marathi]]. Although a large percentage of the residents are natives of Maharashtra, in the last few decades, there has been a huge influx of non-native residents into Bhandup, reflecting the trend witnessed for Mumbai as a whole.{{Citation needed|date=April 2019}}\n\n[[File:... near Bhandup Pumping Station (8213582822).jpg|thumb|near Bhandup Pumping Station]]\n\n==Economy==\n===Industry===\nAccording to the 2001 census, there were 12,380 industrial establishments in Bhandup (S-Ward), providing employment to 36,921 residents of Bhandup.<ref name=\":0\" /> The rest of the employed populace are employed outside the limits of the S-ward.\n\nOne of the first industries to start in this area was [[Crompton Greaves]] in 1937,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.maharashtra.gov.in/english/gazetteer/greater_bombay/industries.html|title=Greater Bombay District: Industries|last=Rairikar|first=B. R.|last2=Chaudhari|first2=Shri K. K.|website=Maharashtra State Gazetteers|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110809033942/http://www.maharashtra.gov.in/english/gazetteer/greater_bombay/industries.html|archive-date=2011-08-09|url-status=dead|access-date=2019-04-14}}</ref> currently in Kanjur Marg. Currently, almost all of the industries in Bhandup are in Bhandup West, including [[CEAT Tyres]], [[Asian Paints Ltd]], [[BASF]], and the Indian Smelting And Refining Company Limited. Apart from these big companies, there are several small-scale manufacturing units all over Bhandup West.\n\nThe presence of a large number of industries, coupled with large traffic flows throughout the day, led to Bhandup's air is one of the worst in Mumbai in 1999.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/res/web/pIe/ie/daily/19991029/ige29049.html|title=Fretting about fumes|last=Nagaraj|first=Anuradha|date=1999-10-29|work=[[The Indian Express]]|access-date=2019-04-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100830002755/http://www.indianexpress.com/res/web/pIe/ie/daily/19991029/ige29049.html|archive-date=2010-08-30|url-status=dead}}</ref> However, several of the polluting industries have moved out of Mumbai since, leading to slightly better air quality.\n\n[[File:Pink visitors - Flamingos in Mumbai.jpg|thumb|left]]\nBhandup has Asia's biggest [[Water sources of Mumbai|water filtration plant]]. The eastern sections of Kanjurmarg and Nahur blend into Bhandup without clear demarcation.\n\n===Retail===\nIn recent years, several [[shopping mall|mall]] construction projects have been initiated in Bhandup. One reason for Bhandup being a prime location for malls is its proximity to affluent areas like [[Powai]] and [[Mulund]]. In the past few years, several industries in Bhandup have shifted or started shifting out of Mumbai, rendering vast tracts of land vacant. These land-plots are being used for the construction of huge residential complexes, in turn, providing the customer base for these malls.{{Citation needed|date=April 2019}}\n\nDreams the Mall, being developed by Satra Properties, is one of the biggest malls in Bhandup. It is located close to Bhandup Railway Station. Neptune Magnet Mall is a shopping mall that is part of a satellite township, Living Point, comprising six towers of 22 stories each being developed by Neptune group.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/india-business/metro-buys-retail-space-in-mumbai/articleshow/1565137.cms|title=Metro buys retail space in Mumbai|date=2007-02-06|work=The Times Of India|accessdate=2008-10-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190414190815/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/india-business/Metro-buys-retail-space-in-Mumbai/articleshow/1565137.cms|archive-date=14 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Some of the other malls in the area include the Leo Mall and a shopping space being developed by HBS Centrix.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://archive.mid-day.com/lifestyle/2008/jul/240708hp4.htm|title=Bhandup (West) gets a makeover|last=Banerjee|first=Urmimala|date=2008-07-24|work=[[Mid Day]]|accessdate=2008-10-21|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190414190946/https://archive.mid-day.com/lifestyle/2008/jul/240708hp4.htm|archivedate=2019-04-14|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Transport==\nBhandup is connected with the rest of the city through the road network. The arterial road of Bhandup West is the [[Agra]] Road i.e. L.B.S. Marg, while Bhandup East is flanked by the Eastern Express [[highway]]. Four buses (numbers 453, 545 and 603), however, pass through Bhandup East, as the area is relatively sparsely populated. There is also a special bus service in the mornings for female commuters, going from Bhandup to Andheri. There is also a special State Transport Bus service in the morning which run between Bhandup and CWC (Navi Mumbai) and Navi Mumbai Municipal Transport Corporation runs a bus (route no 144) through Bhandup East which plies between Andheri East and Airoli.{{Citation needed|date=April 2019}}\n\nBhandup is also a [[Bhandup railway station|railway station]] on the Central Line of the Mumbai Suburban Railway network,{{Citation needed|date=April 2019}} between KanjurMarg and Nahur.{{Citation needed|date=April 2019}}\n\n==Schools==\nThere are over 35 schools in Bhandup. Most of these schools are affiliated with the [[Maharashtra State Board of Secondary and Higher Secondary Education]].{{Citation needed|date=April 2019}}\n\n* [[NES High School|NES High School and Junior College]]\n* [[Pawar Public School]], L.B.S. Marg, Bhandup (W)\n* Adarsh Vidyalay, Bhandup East (Marathi medium)\n* Ahilya Vidyalaya (Jamil Nagar)\n* Ahilya Vidyalaya (Utkarsh Nagar)\n* B.E.S English High School, Next to Railway station, Bhandup (East)\n* B.P.E.S. High School, Pratap Nagar, Bhandup (W)\n* Cosmos English High School & Jr. College Bhandup (West)\n* Gurunanak English High School \n* I D U B S High School and Jr. College Bhandup (W) \n* IES School, Bhandup East (English/Marathi medium)\n* Navjeevan Vidyamandir & Jr. College\n* New English School Dockyard Colony Kanjur West\n* Pragatik Vidyalaya school Tembipada gavdevi Road Bhandup West.\n* R.S.S Vidya Mandir English/Hindi Bhandup west\n* Parag vidyalaya, Chatrapati shivaji maharaj talav, Bhandup West, Mumbai - 78.\n* Sahyadri Vidyamandir, Shivaji Talav, Bhandup West, Mumbai-78.\n* Shree Saraswati Vidyamandir Bhandup (West)\n* St. Francis Xavier's High School Bhandup (East)\n* St. Xavier's High School & Jr. College Bhandup (West)\n* [[Yashwant Chandaji Sawant Vidyamandir]], Utkarsh Nagar, Bhandup (West)\n\n===Colleges===\nBhandup has four major accredited colleges, out of which two are in Bhandup (East) and two in Bhandup (West). All of them are affiliated to the [[University of Mumbai]].{{Citation needed|date=April 2019}} The breakup is as follows:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\"\n|-\n! Name of college Vidyadhiraja High School & Jr College\n! Location Tata Nagar, Bhandup(East)\n! NAAC accreditation status\n! Class levels Junior College\n|-\n| [[NES Ratnam College Of Arts, Science & Commerce]]\n| N.E.S. Marg, Bhandup (West)\n| A<ref name=\"Sencol\">[http://naacindia.org/Colleges.asp?state=14# NAAC-Maharashtra institutions]</ref>\n| Junior college to Postgraduate\n|-\n| V. K. Krishna Menon College of Commerce and Economics & Science\n| Bhandup (East)\n| B<ref name=Sencol/>\n| Junior college to Postgraduate\n|-\n| Ramanand Arya D. A. V. College, Station Road\n| Datar Colony, Bhandup (East)\n| A<ref name=Sencol/>\n| Junior college to Bachelors\n|-\n| Jijamata Junior College, Maharashtra Nagar\n| Bhandup (West)\n| B<ref name=Sencol/>\n| Junior college to Bachelors\n|-\n| Shri Ram College of Commerce, Subhash Nagar\n|Bhandup (West)\n| B<ref name=Sencol/>\n| Junior college to Postgraduate\n|} Mount Merry English High school Tulshetpada Bhandup West\n\n==Sports==\n\n===Football===\nBhandup has several [[Association football|Football]] clubs which are members of the [[Mumbai District Football Association]] (MDFA), including the Sunday Boys Football Club, the GKW Rangers, Ushanagar Youth CluB, DATAR CHAMP'S Football Club (DC), Samarth Garden Football Club (S.G.F.C), UshaComplex Football club (U.C.F.C). And Gunners Football Club and GN Boys and also Satya Vijay Football Club (SVFC).{{Citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\nBhandup also has its own football association called the Bhandup Suburb Football Association (BSFA).{{Citation needed|date=April 2019}}\n\n===Cricket===\nBhandup has several cricket clubs.\n\n==Social organisations==\nThere are several social organizations in Bhandup of which Sarvajanik Pooja Samiti Bhandup village east, founded in 1946, is the oldest, followed by [[Adrash Sports Club]] (1956), followed by [[Vijay Krida Mandal]], Shree Saibhajan Sanskrutik Mandal (Bhandup), Vikas Mandal, Sai Vihar, [[BKWSU|Prajapita Brahma Kumaris Ishwariya Vishwa Vidyalaya]], [[Jeevan Vidya Mission]] and the Rotary Club of Mumbai Bhandup.{{Citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\n==Notable people from Bhandup==\n<!-- ONLY ADD A PERSON TO THIS LIST IF THEY ALREADY HAVE AN ARTICLE IN THE ENGLISH WIKIPEDIA -->\n* [[Dhananjay Mahadik]] - Indian National Hockey Player\n* [[Jemimah Rodrigues]] - Indian Women's Cricket Teams Youngest Player\n* [[Sanjay Raut]] -[[Saamna]] Editor and [[Shiv Sena]] leader\n* [[Sanjay Dina Patil]] - ex- Member of Parliament-North-East Mumbai and NCP [[Nationalist Congress Party]]\n* [[Om Puri]] Bollywood Actor used to stay here before getting into Bollywood\n* [[Rupali Repale]] - long-distance swimmer \n<!-- ONLY ADD A PERSON TO THIS LIST IF THEY ALREADY HAVE AN ARTICLE IN THE ENGLISH WIKIPEDIA -->\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Mumbai metropolitan area}}\n\n[[Category:Suburbs of Mumbai]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2018}}\n{{more citations needed|date=August 2012}}\n\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Bhandup\n| other_name                      = Bhandupeshwar\n| settlement_type                 = Suburban\n| image_skyline                   = \n| image_alt                       = \n| image_caption                   = \n| nickname                        = \n| map_alt                         = \n| map_caption                     = \n| pushpin_map                     = Mumbai\n| pushpin_label_position          = \n| pushpin_map_alt                 = \n| pushpin_map_caption             = \n| coordinates                     = {{coord|19.14|N|72.93|E|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = {{flag | India}}\n| subdivision_type1               = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_name1               = [[Maharashtra]]\n| subdivision_type2               = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Mumbai Suburban district|Mumbai Suburban]]\n| subdivision_type3               = Metro (Ward) s \"ward\"\n| subdivision_name3               = \n| subdivision_type4               = [[Talukas of Maharashtra|Taluka/Tehsil]]\n| subdivision_name4               = [[Kurla]]\n| established_title               = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date                = 1803\n| founder                         = \n| named_for                       = \n| government_type                 = \n| governing_body                  = \n| leader_title1                   = [[Maharashtra Legislative Assembly|M.L.A]]\n| leader_name1                    = [[Ramesh Korgaonkar]] <br /> [[Shiv Sena]] (since 2019)\n| leader_title2                   = [[Parliament of India|M.P.]]\n| leader_name2                    = [[Manoj Kotak]] <br /> [[BJP]] (since 2019)\n| unit_pref                       = Metric\n| area_footnotes                  = \n| area_rank                       = \n| area_total_km2                  = \n| elevation_footnotes             = \n| elevation_m                     = 5.205\n| population_total                = 6,91,227\n| population_as_of                = 2001 Census\n| population_rank                 = \n| population_density_km2          = auto\n| population_demonym              = Bhandupkar\n| population_footnotes            = \n| demographics_type1              = Languages\n| demographics1_title1            = Official\n| demographics1_info1             = [[Marathi language|Marathi]]\n| timezone1                       = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1                     = +5:30\n| postal_code_type                = [[Postal Index Number|PIN]]\n| postal_code                     = 400078 (West) and 400042 (East)\n| blank1_name_sec1                = [[Lok Sabha]] constituency\n| blank1_info_sec1                = [[Mumbai North East (Lok Sabha constituency)|Mumbai North East]]\n| blank2_name_sec1                = [[Vidhan Sabha]] constituency\n| blank2_info_sec1                = [[Bhandup West (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Bhandup West]]\n| registration_plate              = MH-03\n| website                         = https://mumbaisuburban.gov.in/\n| footnotes                       = \n| official_name                   = \n}}\n'''Bhandup''' is a suburban community within the Municipal Corporation of [[Mumbai]], in the state of [[Maharashtra]], [[India]]. The name ''Bhandup'' is derived from ''Bhandupeshwar'', one of the names of the [[Hinduism|Hindu]] god [[Lord Shiva]]. An old temple dedicated to Lord Shiva, the Bhandupeshwar Mahadev Mandir, is located in Bhandup. Sonapur signal is north lead line on L.B.S. Marg and south is dockyard colony.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Ganpati Visarjan - Bhandup west.jpg|thumb|left|2016 Ganpati Visarjan ([[Ganesh Chaturthi]]) - Bhandup west]]\nBhandup is one of the oldest suburbs in Mumbai.{{citation needed|date=December 2018}} It is home to Shivaji Talao, or Shivaji Lake, named after the [[Maratha]] ruler, [[Chhatrapati Shivaji]]. Devotees of [[Ganapati]] immerse idols of the elephant god Ganesh at the lake during the months of August through September, as well as in Bhandupeshwar Kundh in Bhandup Village East near the Eastern Express Highway.{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}\n\nThe earliest records of Bhandup come from 1803, and show the contemporary Bhandup [[Estate (house)|estate]] to comprise Bhandup, [[Nahur]] and [[Kanjur Marg]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pb8IAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA44-IA1|title=Gazetteer of the Bombay Presidency: Tha'na. Places of Interest.|last=|first=|publisher=Government Central Press|year=1882|isbn=|volume=Vol. XIV|location=Bombay|pages=44\u201345}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Silaharas]], also known as [[Shilahara]], was a mixture of people of [[Dravidian peoples|Dravidian]] ancestry and the [[Kayastha]] Prabhus from [[Konkan]]. The [[Silaharas]] promoted socio-economic progress in the 11th century around Bombay. To control the regions in Bombay and Thane, the built the ''Rajapatha'', passing from the north of Bhandup, following the current Bombay-Thane road.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/risebombayaretr00edwagoog|title=The Rise of Bombay, A Retrospect|last=Edwardes|first=S. M.|publisher=Government of Bombay|year=1902|isbn=|location=Bombay|pages=[https://archive.org/details/risebombayaretr00edwagoog/page/n114 17]}}</ref>\n\nHistorical records indicate that the distillery at Bhandup was one of the two biggest sources of [[liquor]] in the [[Bombay Presidency]], the other being the [[Uran]] distillery.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JAobAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA455|title=General Report on the Administration of the Bombay Presidency, For the Year 1873-74|last=|first=|publisher=Government of Bombay|year=1875|isbn=|location=Bombay|pages=455\u2013456}}</ref>\n\nBhandup was also one of the first [[railway]] stations in India. The first train ran between [[Bori Bunder]] and [[Thane]] on 16 April 1853 with 400 passengers aboard 14 railway carriages, at 3:35 pm. It is said that the idea to connect Bombay with Thane and [[Kalyan, India|Kalyan]] occurred to Mr. George Clark, the Chief Engineer of the Bombay Government, on a visit to Bhandup in 1843.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.asiatradehub.com/India/railways.asp |title=Indian Railways-Introduction |access-date=2008-10-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081016092740/http://www.asiatradehub.com/India/railways.asp |archive-date=2008-10-16 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.irfca.org/~mrinal/irhistory2.html|title=Development of Railways in India|website=Indian Railways Fan Club|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180315181011/http://www.irfca.org/~mrinal/irhistory2.html|archive-date=2018-03-15|url-status=dead|access-date=2019-04-14}}</ref>\n\nHowever, Bhandup was not a part of Bombay until 1950, when the boundaries of the Bombay municipal corporation were extended up to [[Andheri]] on the western side and Bhandup on the eastern side.{{Citation needed|date=April 2019}}\n\n==Demographics==\nBhandup falls within the S-ward, as defined by the [[Municipal Corporation of Greater Mumbai]]. The population of Bhandup has risen exponentially in the last twenty years.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://mmrda.maharashtra.gov.in/documents/10180/6867434/Population+and+Employment+Profile.pdf|title=Population and Employment Profile of Mumbai Metropolitan Region|last=Pendharkar|first=S. P.|date=2003-09-01|website=Mumbai Metropolitan Region Development Authority|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190414190143/https://mmrda.maharashtra.gov.in/documents/10180/6867434/Population+and+Employment+Profile.pdf|archive-date=2019-04-14|url-status=live|access-date=2019-04-14}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\"\n|-\n! Census Year\n! Population\n! Density per square km\n! % change in population from previous year\n! Sex ratio (females/1000 males)\n|-\n| 1981\n| 2,97,108\n| 7860\n| NA\n| 740\n|-\n| 1991\n| 5,68,028\n| 15,027\n| 91%\n| 813\n|-\n| 2001\n| 6,91,227\n| 10,800\n| 21%\n| 823\n|}\n*''The discordance between population and density could be due to re-drawing of ward boundaries''\n\nThe majority of residents of Bhandup are [[Hindus]] by religion. The dominant language is [[Marathi language|Marathi]]. Although a large percentage of the residents are natives of Maharashtra, in the last few decades, there has been a huge influx of non-native residents into Bhandup, reflecting the trend witnessed for Mumbai as a whole.{{Citation needed|date=April 2019}}\n\n[[File:... near Bhandup Pumping Station (8213582822).jpg|thumb|near Bhandup Pumping Station]]\n\n==Economy==\n===Industry===\nAccording to the 2001 census, there were 12,380 industrial establishments in Bhandup (S-Ward), providing employment to 36,921 residents of Bhandup.<ref name=\":0\" /> The rest of the employed populace are employed outside the limits of the S-ward.\n\nOne of the first industries to start in this area was [[Crompton Greaves]] in 1937,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.maharashtra.gov.in/english/gazetteer/greater_bombay/industries.html|title=Greater Bombay District: Industries|last=Rairikar|first=B. R.|last2=Chaudhari|first2=Shri K. K.|website=Maharashtra State Gazetteers|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110809033942/http://www.maharashtra.gov.in/english/gazetteer/greater_bombay/industries.html|archive-date=2011-08-09|url-status=dead|access-date=2019-04-14}}</ref> currently in Kanjur Marg. Currently, almost all of the industries in Bhandup are in Bhandup West, including [[CEAT Tyres]], [[Asian Paints Ltd]], [[BASF]], and the Indian Smelting And Refining Company Limited. Apart from these big companies, there are several small-scale manufacturing units all over Bhandup West.\n\nThe presence of a large number of industries, coupled with large traffic flows throughout the day, led to Bhandup's air is one of the worst in Mumbai in 1999.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/res/web/pIe/ie/daily/19991029/ige29049.html|title=Fretting about fumes|last=Nagaraj|first=Anuradha|date=1999-10-29|work=[[The Indian Express]]|access-date=2019-04-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100830002755/http://www.indianexpress.com/res/web/pIe/ie/daily/19991029/ige29049.html|archive-date=2010-08-30|url-status=dead}}</ref> However, several of the polluting industries have moved out of Mumbai since, leading to slightly better air quality.\n\n[[File:Pink visitors - Flamingos in Mumbai.jpg|thumb|left]]\nBhandup has Asia's biggest [[Water sources of Mumbai|water filtration plant]]. The eastern sections of Kanjurmarg and Nahur blend into Bhandup without clear demarcation.\n\n===Retail===\nIn recent years, several [[shopping mall|mall]] construction projects have been initiated in Bhandup. One reason for Bhandup being a prime location for malls is its proximity to affluent areas like [[Powai]] and [[Mulund]]. In the past few years, several industries in Bhandup have shifted or started shifting out of Mumbai, rendering vast tracts of land vacant. These land-plots are being used for the construction of huge residential complexes, in turn, providing the customer base for these malls.{{Citation needed|date=April 2019}}\n\nDreams the Mall, being developed by Satra Properties, is one of the biggest malls in Bhandup. It is located close to Bhandup Railway Station. Neptune Magnet Mall is a shopping mall that is part of a satellite township, Living Point, comprising six towers of 22 stories each being developed by Neptune group.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/india-business/metro-buys-retail-space-in-mumbai/articleshow/1565137.cms|title=Metro buys retail space in Mumbai|date=2007-02-06|work=The Times Of India|accessdate=2008-10-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190414190815/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/india-business/Metro-buys-retail-space-in-Mumbai/articleshow/1565137.cms|archive-date=14 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Some of the other malls in the area include the Leo Mall and a shopping space being developed by HBS Centrix.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://archive.mid-day.com/lifestyle/2008/jul/240708hp4.htm|title=Bhandup (West) gets a makeover|last=Banerjee|first=Urmimala|date=2008-07-24|work=[[Mid Day]]|accessdate=2008-10-21|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190414190946/https://archive.mid-day.com/lifestyle/2008/jul/240708hp4.htm|archivedate=2019-04-14|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Transport==\nBhandup is connected with the rest of the city through the road network. The arterial road of Bhandup West is the [[Agra]] Road i.e. L.B.S. Marg, while Bhandup East is flanked by the Eastern Express [[highway]]. Four buses (numbers 453, 545 and 603), however, pass through Bhandup East, as the area is relatively sparsely populated. There is also a special bus service in the mornings for female commuters, going from Bhandup to Andheri. There is also a special State Transport Bus service in the morning which run between Bhandup and CWC (Navi Mumbai) and Navi Mumbai Municipal Transport Corporation runs a bus (route no 144) through Bhandup East which plies between Andheri East and Airoli.{{Citation needed|date=April 2019}}\n\nBhandup is also a [[Bhandup railway station|railway station]] on the Central Line of the Mumbai Suburban Railway network,{{Citation needed|date=April 2019}} between KanjurMarg and Nahur.{{Citation needed|date=April 2019}}\n\n==Schools==\nThere are over 35 schools in Bhandup. Most of these schools are affiliated with the [[Maharashtra State Board of Secondary and Higher Secondary Education]].{{Citation needed|date=April 2019}}\n\n* [[NES High School|NES High School and Junior College]]\n* [[Pawar Public School]], L.B.S. Marg, Bhandup (W)\n* Adarsh Vidyalay, Bhandup East (Marathi medium)\n* Ahilya Vidyalaya (Jamil Nagar)\n* Ahilya Vidyalaya (Utkarsh Nagar)\n* B.E.S English High School, Next to Railway station, Bhandup (East)\n* B.P.E.S. High School, Pratap Nagar, Bhandup (W)\n* Cosmos English High School & Jr. College Bhandup (West)\n* Gurunanak English High School \n* I D U B S High School and Jr. College Bhandup (W) \n* IES School, Bhandup East (English/Marathi medium)\n* Navjeevan Vidyamandir & Jr. College\n* New English School Dockyard Colony Kanjur West\n* Pragatik Vidyalaya school Tembipada gavdevi Road Bhandup West.\n* R.S.S Vidya Mandir English/Hindi Bhandup west\n* Parag vidyalaya, Chatrapati shivaji maharaj talav, Bhandup West, Mumbai - 78.\n* Sahyadri Vidyamandir, Shivaji Talav, Bhandup West, Mumbai-78.\n* Shree Saraswati Vidyamandir Bhandup (West)\n* St. Francis Xavier's High School Bhandup (East)\n* St. Xavier's High School & Jr. College Bhandup (West)\n* [[Yashwant Chandaji Sawant Vidyamandir]], Utkarsh Nagar, Bhandup (West)\n\n===Colleges===\nBhandup has four major accredited colleges, out of which two are in Bhandup (East) and two in Bhandup (West). All of them are affiliated to the [[University of Mumbai]].{{Citation needed|date=April 2019}} The breakup is as follows:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\"\n|-\n! Name of college Vidyadhiraja High School & Jr College\n! Location Tata Nagar, Bhandup(East)\n! NAAC accreditation status\n! Class levels Junior College\n|-\n| [[NES Ratnam College Of Arts, Science & Commerce]]\n| N.E.S. Marg, Bhandup (West)\n| A<ref name=\"Sencol\">[http://naacindia.org/Colleges.asp?state=14# NAAC-Maharashtra institutions]</ref>\n| Junior college to Postgraduate\n|-\n| V. K. Krishna Menon College of Commerce and Economics & Science\n| Bhandup (East)\n| B<ref name=Sencol/>\n| Junior college to Postgraduate\n|-\n| Ramanand Arya D. A. V. College, Station Road\n| Datar Colony, Bhandup (East)\n| A<ref name=Sencol/>\n| Junior college to Bachelors\n|-\n| Jijamata Junior College, Maharashtra Nagar\n| Bhandup (West)\n| B<ref name=Sencol/>\n| Junior college to Bachelors\n|-\n| Shri Ram College of Commerce, Subhash Nagar\n|Bhandup (West)\n| B<ref name=Sencol/>\n| Junior college to Postgraduate\n|} Mount Merry English High school Tulshetpada Bhandup West\n\n==Sports==\n\n===Football===\nBhandup has several [[Association football|Football]] clubs which are members of the [[Mumbai District Football Association]] (MDFA), including the Sunday Boys Football Club, the GKW Rangers, Ushanagar Youth CluB, DATAR CHAMP'S Football Club (DC), Samarth Garden Football Club (S.G.F.C), UshaComplex Football club (U.C.F.C). And Gunners Football Club and GN Boys and also Satya Vijay Football Club (SVFC).{{Citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\nBhandup also has its own football association called the Bhandup Suburb Football Association (BSFA).{{Citation needed|date=April 2019}}\n\n===Cricket===\nBhandup has several cricket clubs.\n\n==Social organisations==\nThere are several social organizations in Bhandup of which Sarvajanik Pooja Samiti Bhandup village east, founded in 1946, is the oldest, followed by [[Adrash Sports Club]] (1956), followed by [[Vijay Krida Mandal]], Shree Saibhajan Sanskrutik Mandal (Bhandup), Vikas Mandal, Sai Vihar, [[BKWSU|Prajapita Brahma Kumaris Ishwariya Vishwa Vidyalaya]], [[Jeevan Vidya Mission]] and the Rotary Club of Mumbai Bhandup.{{Citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\n==Notable people from Bhandup==\n<!-- ONLY ADD A PERSON TO THIS LIST IF THEY ALREADY HAVE AN ARTICLE IN THE ENGLISH WIKIPEDIA -->\n* [[Dhananjay Mahadik]] - Indian National Hockey Player\n* [[Jemimah Rodrigues]] - Indian Women's Cricket Teams Youngest Player\n* [[Sanjay Raut]] -[[Saamna]] Editor and [[Shiv Sena]] leader\n* [[Sanjay Dina Patil]] - ex- Member of Parliament-North-East Mumbai and NCP [[Nationalist Congress Party]]\n* [[Om Puri]] Bollywood Actor used to stay here before getting into Bollywood\n* [[Rupali Repale]] - long-distance swimmer \n<!-- ONLY ADD A PERSON TO THIS LIST IF THEY ALREADY HAVE AN ARTICLE IN THE ENGLISH WIKIPEDIA -->\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Mumbai metropolitan area}}\n\n[[Category: Suburbs of Mumbai]]\n", "name_user": "Titodutta", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bhandup"}
