{"title_page": "Monrovia Transit Authority", "text_new": "The '''Monrovia Transit Authority''' ('''MTA''') is a [[public ownership|publicly owned]] company started 1979 in [[Monrovia]], [[Liberia]], to provide timetabled bus services in the capital city. Operations ceased prior to the war. The MTA owns and runs a depot outside of Monrovia in [[Gardnersville]]. The general manager of the MTA is [[Obedia Tarla]].\n\nAs a result of the [[First Liberian Civil War|Liberian civil war]], the premises of the MTA were completely vandalized, and sat desolate and dormant for over 20 years. In 2007 the transit system in the country was resuscitated.<ref>http://mirror.unhabitat.org/downloads/docs/8858_49014_4%20Senegal%20MTA%20Presentation.pdf</ref>\n\n==National Transit Authority==\n[[File:A National Transit Authority bus on Broad Street in Monrovia.jpg|thumb|A National Transit Authority bus on Broad Street in Monrovia]]\n\nIn 2009, the National Transit Authority (NTA) was established to which the Monrovia Transit Authority became a subsidiary.<ref>http://mot.gov.lr/doc/Cap_4.pdf</ref> The NTA will be responsible\nfor passenger transport services throughout Liberia.<ref>http://www.nta.com.lr/2content.php?sub=178&related=1&third=178&pg=sp</ref>\n\nIn October, 2011 the Government of India donated 25 [[Ashok Leyland]] Falcon buses.<ref>http://allafrica.com/stories/201412100493.html</ref>  This donation was soon followed by the purchase of additional 8 new buses.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Companies of Liberia]]\n[[Category:Transport in Liberia]]\n[[Category:Monrovia]]\n\n{{Liberia-stub}}\n", "text_old": "The '''Monrovia Transit Authority''' ('''MTA''') is a [[public ownership|publicly owned]] company started 1979 in [[Monrovia]], [[Liberia]], to provide timetabled bus services in the capital city. Operations ceased prior to the war. The MTA owns and runs a depot outside of Monrovia in [[Gardnersville]]. The general manager of the MTA is [[Obedia Tarla]].\n\nAs a result of the [[Liberian civil war]], the premises of the MTA were completely vandalized, and sat desolate and dormant for over 20 years. In 2007 the transit system in the country was resuscitated.<ref>http://mirror.unhabitat.org/downloads/docs/8858_49014_4%20Senegal%20MTA%20Presentation.pdf</ref>\n\n==National Transit Authority==\n[[File:A National Transit Authority bus on Broad Street in Monrovia.jpg|thumb|A National Transit Authority bus on Broad Street in Monrovia]]\n\nIn 2009, the National Transit Authority (NTA) was established to which the Monrovia Transit Authority became a subsidiary.<ref>http://mot.gov.lr/doc/Cap_4.pdf</ref> The NTA will be responsible\nfor passenger transport services throughout Liberia.<ref>http://www.nta.com.lr/2content.php?sub=178&related=1&third=178&pg=sp</ref>\n\nIn October, 2011 the Government of India donated 25 [[Ashok Leyland]] Falcon buses.<ref>http://allafrica.com/stories/201412100493.html</ref>  This donation was soon followed by the purchase of additional 8 new buses.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Companies of Liberia]]\n[[Category:Transport in Liberia]]\n[[Category:Monrovia]]\n\n{{Liberia-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toLiberian Civil War(link changed toFirst Liberian Civil War) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monrovia_Transit_Authority"}
{"title_page": "Leo Varadkar", "text_new": "{{pp-vandalism|small=yes}}\n{{redirect|Varadkar|the surname|Varadkar (surname)}}\n{{short description|Irish politician; Taoiseach (Prime Minister) of Ireland, current Minister for Defence, and leader of the Fine Gael party}}\n{{Use Irish English|date=June 2018}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name          = Leo Varadkar\n|honorific-suffix = [[Teachta D\u00e1la|TD]]\n|image         = Leo Varadkar October 2019.jpg\n|caption       = Varadkar in 2019\n|order         = 14th\n|office        = Taoiseach\n|president     = [[Michael D. Higgins]]\n|1blankname    = [[T\u00e1naiste]]\n|1namedata     = [[Frances Fitzgerald (politician)|Frances Fitzgerald]]<br>[[Simon Coveney]]\n|term_start    = 14 June 2017\n|term_end      = \n|predecessor   = [[Enda Kenny]]\n|successor     =\n|office1       = [[Leader of Fine Gael]]\n|deputy1       = Simon Coveney\n|term_start1   = 2 June 2017\n|term_end1     =\n|predecessor1  = Enda Kenny\n|successor1    =\n|office2       = [[Minister for Defence (Ireland)|Minister for Defence]]\n|term_start2   = 14 June 2017\n|term_end2     =\n|predecessor2  = Enda Kenny\n|successor2    =\n|office3       = [[Minister for Employment Affairs and Social Protection|Minister for Social Protection]]\n|taoiseach3    = Enda Kenny\n|term_start3   = 6 May 2016\n|term_end3     = 14 June 2017\n|predecessor3  = [[Joan Burton]]\n|successor3    = [[Regina Doherty]]\n|office4       = [[Minister for Health (Ireland)|Minister for Health]]\n|taoiseach4    = Enda Kenny\n|term_start4   = 11 July 2014\n|term_end4     = 6 May 2016\n|predecessor4  = [[James Reilly (Irish politician)|James Reilly]]\n|successor4    = [[Simon Harris (politician)|Simon Harris]]\n|office5       = [[Minister for Transport, Tourism and Sport]]\n|taoiseach5    = Enda Kenny\n|term_start5   = 9 March 2011\n|term_end5     = 11 July 2014\n|predecessor5  = [[Pat Carey]]\n|successor5    = [[Paschal Donohoe]]\n|office6       = [[Teachta D\u00e1la]]\n|term_start6   = [[2007 Irish general election|June 2007]]\n|term_end6     =\n|constituency6 = [[Dublin West (D\u00e1il constituency)|Dublin West]]\n|birth_name    = Leo Eric Varadkar\n|birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1979|1|18|df=y}}\n|birth_place   = [[Rotunda Hospital]], [[Dublin]], Ireland\n|death_date    = \n|death_place   =\n|nationality   = [[Irish people|Irish]]\n|party         = [[Fine Gael]]\n|partner       = Matthew Barrett {{small|(2015\u2013present)}}\n|children      =\n|parents       = {{Unbulleted list|Ashok Varadkar|Miriam Varadkar}}\n|education     = [[The King's Hospital]]\n|alma_mater    = [[Trinity College Dublin]]\n|signature     =\n|website       = {{url|taoiseach.gov.ie|Official website}}<br>{{url|leovaradkar.ie|Constituency website}}\n|}}\n'''Leo Eric Varadkar''' ({{IPAc-en|v|\u0259|\u02c8|r|\u00e6|d|k|\u0259r}} {{respell|v\u0259|RAD|k\u0259r}}; born 18 January 1979) is an Irish [[Fine Gael]] politician and [[physician]]. He has served as the [[Leader of Fine Gael]], and as [[Taoiseach]] and [[Minister for Defence (Ireland)|Minister for Defence]] in the [[Government of Ireland]], since June 2017. Following the [[2020 Irish general election]] in which Fine Gael were returned as the third largest party behind [[Fianna F\u00e1il]] and [[Sinn F\u00e9in]], Varadkar resigned but remains in office as caretaker Taoiseach until a successor is appointed. He has also been a [[Teachta D\u00e1la]] (TD) for the [[Dublin West (D\u00e1il constituency)|Dublin West]] constituency since [[2007 Irish general election|2007]].\n\nVaradkar was born in [[Dublin]] and studied medicine at [[Trinity College Dublin]]. He spent several years as a non-consultant hospital doctor, eventually qualifying as a [[general practitioner]] in 2010. In 2004, he joined Fine Gael and became a member of [[Fingal County Council]] and later served as Deputy Mayor. He was elected to [[D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann]] for the first time in 2007. \n\nDuring the 2015 [[2015 Irish constitutional referendums|same-sex marriage referendum]], Varadkar [[Coming out|came out]] as gay, becoming the first Irish Minister to do so.<ref>{{cite news|last=Armstrong |first=Kathy |url=http://www.independent.ie/irish-news/politics/significant-step-for-equality-the-world-reacts-to-leo-varadkar-becoming-the-new-fine-gael-leader-35782985.html |title='Significant step for equality'- the world reacts to Leo Varadkar becoming the new Fine Gael leader |work=[[Irish Independent]] |publisher=[[Independent News & Media]] |location=[[Dublin]] |issn=0021-1222 |date=2 June 2017 |access-date=25 August 2018}}</ref> He is Ireland's first, and the world's fourth, [[List of the first LGBT holders of political offices|openly gay head of government]] in modern times,<ref>{{Cite news|last= Kwak |first=Bethia |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/feature/nbc-out/ireland-appears-set-elect-first-openly-gay-prime-minister-n765426|title=Ireland appears set to elect first openly gay prime minister|work=[[NBC News]]|date=27 May 2017 |access-date=13 November 2017|language=en-US |quote=If elected, Varadkar would only be the fourth openly gay world leader in modern history. The others include [[Prime Minister of Luxembourg]], [[Xavier Bettel]], former [[Prime Minister of Belgium]], [[Elio Di Rupo]], and former [[Prime Minister of Iceland]], [[J\u00f3hanna Sigur\u00f0ard\u00f3ttir]].}}</ref> and first Taoiseach of [[India]]n heritage.  ''[[The Economist]]'' says of him: \"Not since the days of [[\u00c9amon de Valera]] has Ireland had a leader as globally recognisable as Leo Varadkar.\"<ref>The Economist, \"The rise of Sinn Fein, an Irish party that once espoused violence,\" February 6, 2020 [https://www.economist.com/europe/2020/02/06/the-rise-of-sinn-fein-an-irish-party-that-once-espoused-violence]</ref>\n\nHe later served in the [[Enda Kenny|Kenny Government]], as [[Minister for Employment Affairs and Social Protection|Minister for Social Protection]] from 2016 to 2017, [[Minister for Health (Ireland)|Minister for Health]] from 2014 to 2016 and [[Minister for Transport, Tourism and Sport]] from 2011 to 2014.<ref name=RTE2017-06-08a>{{cite news|title=More 'disappointments than appointments' over cabinet selection \u2013 Varadkar|url=https://www.rte.ie/news/politics/2017/0608/881166-leo-varadkar/ |access-date=10 June 2017|publisher=[[RT\u00c9 News]]|date=8 June 2017|quote=Mr Varadkar, who is on course to be elected taoiseach in the D\u00e1il next Wednesday, ... He described his meetings with Fianna F\u00e1il and Independents yesterday as \"fruitful\".}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2017, Kenny announced that he would resign as Taoiseach and Fine Gael Leader. Varadkar stood in the [[2017 Fine Gael leadership election|leadership election]] to replace him; although more party members voted for his opponent, [[Simon Coveney]], he won by a significant margin among members of the [[Oireachtas]], and was elected leader on 2 June. 12 days later, he was appointed Taoiseach, and at 38 years old became the youngest person to hold the office.<ref>{{Cite news|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/leo-varadkar-born-to-an-indian-father-a-historic-gay-pm-for-ireland/story-Nyxchjg1avrV5hqUQPe3qJ.html|title=Leo Varadkar: Born to an Indian father, a historic gay PM for Ireland|last=|first=|date=3 June 2017|work=[[Hindustan Times]]|location=[[New Delhi]] |publisher=[[HT Media]] |access-date=13 November 2017 |agency=[[Agence France-Presse]] |issn=0972-0243}}</ref> \n\n==Early life==\nBorn on 18 January 1979, in the [[Rotunda Hospital]], [[Dublin]], Varadkar is the third child and only son of Ashok and Miriam (n\u00e9e Howell) Varadkar. His father was born in Bombay (now [[Mumbai]]), [[India]], and moved to the [[United Kingdom]] in the 1960s, to work as a doctor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/world/varad-village-in-maharashtra-rejoices-as-leo-varadkar-is-set-to-be-irish-pm-4687123/|title=Varad village in Maharashtra rejoices as Leo Varadkar is set to be Irish PM|date=3 June 2017|publisher=IndianExpress.com}}</ref> His mother, born in [[Dungarvan]], [[County Waterford]], met her future husband while working as a nurse in [[Slough]].<ref>{{Cite news| last=McDonald |first=Henry |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/jun/02/leo-varadkar-becomes-irelands-prime-minister-elect |title=Leo Varadkar, gay son of Indian immigrant, to be next Irish PM |date=2 June 2017 |work=[[The Guardian]] |location=[[London]] |publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]] |access-date=13 November 2017 |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> They married in the UK, early in 1971,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=LpXrN9C1aygapjYzkUf0Og&scan=1|title=Index entry|accessdate=16 February 2018|work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}}</ref> then lived in [[Leicester]], where the eldest of their three children, Sophie, was born. The family moved to India, before settling in Dublin in 1973, where their second child, Sonia, was born.\n\nThough Varadkar was born to a [[Hindu]] father and a [[Catholic]] mother, his parents made the decision to raise him in the Catholic faith.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bielenberg |first1=Kim |title=Why Leo, the petulant political puppy, is still happily wagging his tail |url=http://www.independent.ie/lifestyle/why-leo-the-petulant-political-puppy-is-still-happily-wagging-his-tail-26739416.html |access-date=3 June 2017 |work=[[Irish Independent]] |publisher=[[Independent News & Media]] |issn=0021-1222 |date=4 June 2011 |quote=His father is Hindu and his mother Catholic. When they got married in church they had to get special permission and agree to bring up the children as Catholic. Varadkar once said: \"They deliberately decided that if we were to be brought up in a Western country that we would be brought up in the culture of our country. I think it's a sensible thing.\"}}</ref> He was educated at the St Francis Xavier National School, [[Blanchardstown]]. His second-level education took place at [[The King's Hospital]] in [[Palmerstown]], a boarding school run by the [[Church of Ireland]].\n\nDuring his secondary schooling, he joined [[Young Fine Gael]]. He was admitted to [[Trinity College Dublin]] (TCD), where he briefly studied law. He later switched to medicine. At TCD he was active in the university's Young Fine Gael branch and served as Vice-President of the [[Youth of the European People's Party]], the youth wing of the [[European People's Party]], of which [[Fine Gael]] is a member.<ref>{{cite news |last=McGee |first=Harry |url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/weekend/2010/1120/1224283746408.html |title=The Saturday Interview |work=[[The Irish Times]] |location=[[Dublin]] |issn=1393-3515 |date=20 November 2010 |access-date=25 August 2018}}</ref> Varadkar was selected for the Washington Ireland Program for Service and Leadership (WIP), a prestigious half-year personal and professional development program in [[Washington, D.C.]], for students from Ireland.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tcd.ie/news_events/articles/first-trinity-graduate-elected-taoiseach/|title=First Trinity Graduate elected Taoiseach|date=13 June 2017|website=Trinity News and Events}}</ref>\n\nHe graduated from the [[School of Medicine (Trinity College Dublin)]] in 2003, after he completed his internship at KEM Hospital in Mumbai.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/world/irelands-new-prime-minister-leo-varadkar-is-a-real-global-indian-says-family-back-home-3512287.html|title=Ireland\u2019s new Prime Minister Leo Varadkar is a 'real global Indian', says family back home - Firstpost|website=www.firstpost.com|access-date=18 June 2018}}</ref> He then spent several years working as a junior doctor in [[St. James's Hospital]] and [[Connolly Hospital]], before qualifying as a [[general practitioner]] in 2010.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/Leo-Varadkar|title=Leo Varadkar {{!}} Biography & Facts|work=Encyclopedia Britannica|access-date=13 November 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Early political career==\n===Fingal County Council (2003\u20132007)===\nVaradkar was twenty years old and a second-year medical student when he unsuccessfully contested the [[1999 Irish local elections|1999 local elections]] in the [[Mulhuddart]] electoral area. Varadkar was co-opted to [[Fingal County Council]] in 2003, for the [[Castleknock]] local electoral area, as a replacement for [[Sheila Terry (politician)|Sheila Terry]]. At the [[2004 Irish local elections|2004 local elections]], he received the highest first-preference vote in the country with 4,894 votes and was elected on the first count.<ref name=elecs_irl>{{cite web|url=http://www.electionsireland.org/candidate.cfm?ID=321|title=Leo Varadkar|publisher=ElectionsIreland.org |accessdate=8 September 2009}}</ref>\n\n===D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann (2007\u2013present)===\nVaradkar was elected to [[D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann]] at the [[2007 Irish general election|2007 general election]].<ref name=oireachtas_db>{{cite web|url=https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/members/member/Leo-Varadkar.D.2007-06-14/|title=Leo Varadkar|work=Oireachtas Members Database|accessdate=8 September 2009}}</ref> Then [[List of Irish Leaders of the Opposition|Leader of the Opposition]], [[Enda Kenny]], appointed him to the [[Fine Gael Front Bench|Front Bench]] as Spokesperson for [[Minister for Business, Enterprise and Innovation|Enterprise, Trade and Employment]] until a 2010 reshuffle, when he became [[Minister for Communications, Climate Action and Environment|Spokesperson on Communications, Energy and Natural Resources]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bardon|first1=Sarah|title=Profile: Leo Varadkar (FG)|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/oireachtas/profile-leo-varadkar-fg-1.2552227|accessdate=3 June 2017|work=The Irish Times|date=3 June 2017}}</ref> At the [[2011 Irish general election|2011 general election]], Varadkar was re-elected to D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann, with 8,359 first-preference votes (a 19.7% share of the poll in a four-seat constituency).<ref name=elecs_irl/>\n\n==Government minister==\n===Minister for Transport, Tourism, and Sport (2011\u20132014)===\nWhen Fine Gael formed a coalition government with the [[Labour Party (Ireland)|Labour Party]], Varadkar was appointed [[Minister for Transport, Tourism and Sport]] on 9 March 2011.<ref name=\"RT\u00c9\">{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2011/0309/finance-business.html|title=Noonan named as new Finance Minister|publisher=[[RT\u00c9 News]]|date=9 March 2011}}</ref> This was considered a surprise appointment, as Varadkar was not known as a sports lover. He said that while he knew \"a lot of facts&nbsp;... I don't play the sports.\"<ref name=\"'True blue' Varadkar red card flag\">{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/national-news/true-blue-varadkar-gets-red-card-as-dail-officials-flag-problem-2877295.html|work=[[Irish Independent]]|title='True blue' Varadkar gets red card as D\u00e1il officials flag problem|date=15 September 2011|first=Fionnan|last=Sheahan}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2011, Varadkar suggested Ireland was \"very unlikely\" to resume borrowing in 2012 and might need a [[Post-2008 Irish economic downturn#EU-IMF intervention|second bailout]], causing jitters on international markets about Ireland's credibility.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/opinion/2011/0601/1224298206616.html|work=[[The Irish Times]]|title=To borrow a phrase, Minister|date=1 June 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052702303657404576354983728036512|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|title=Bond Auctions Test Contagion Fears|date=30 May 2011|first1=Emese|last1=Bartha|first2=Eamon|last2=Quinn}}</ref> Many of his cabinet colleagues frowned on Varadkar's forthrightness, as did the [[European Central Bank]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/frontpage/2011/0531/1224298146011.html|work=[[The Irish Times]]|title=Cabinet colleagues angered at Varadkar bailout view|date=31 May 2011|first1=Stephen|last1=Collins|first2=Arthur|last2=Beesley}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/business/irish/trichet-talks-verbal-discipline-after-leos-gaffe-2671031.html|work=[[Irish Independent]]|title=Trichet talks 'verbal discipline' after Leo's gaffe|date=10 June 2011|first=Laura|last=Noonan}}</ref> [[Taoiseach]] [[Enda Kenny]] repeated the line of the [[Government of Ireland]], that the State would not require a further [[EU]]-[[IMF]] bailout, and said he had warned all Ministers against publicly disparaging the economy.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/breaking/2011/0531/breaking3.html|work=[[The Irish Times]]|title=State 'won't require' second bailout|date=31 May 2011|first1=Michael|last1=O'Regan|first2=Marie|last2=O'Halloran}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/national-news/kenny-lays-down-law-to-ministers-after-varadkars-gaffe-on-bailout-2662634.html|work=[[Irish Independent]]|title=Kenny lays down law to ministers after Varadkar's gaffe on bailout|date=1 June 2011|first1=Fionnan|last1=Sheahan|first2=Colm|last2=Kelpie}}</ref> Varadkar said that reaction to the story was hyped up but that he was not misquoted.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2011/0602/economy.html|title=Bailout comments were 'hyped up' \u2013 Varadkar|publisher=[[RT\u00c9 News]]|date=2 June 2011}}</ref> The ''[[Evening Herald]]'' repeatedly described Varadkar as gaffe prone.<ref>{{cite news |last=Doyle |first=Kevin |url=http://www.herald.ie/national-news/new-gaffe-is-just-one-of-a-growing-list-2661193.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120925120923/http://www.herald.ie/news/new-gaffe-is-just-one-of-a-growing-list-2661193.html |archive-date=25 September 2012 |newspaper=[[Evening Herald]] |location=[[Dublin]] |publisher=[[Independent News & Media]] |issn=0791-6892 |title=New gaffe is just one of a growing list |date=30 May 2011 |access-date=26 August 2018 |quote=He spent years tongue-lashing Calamity Coughlin for her gaffes, but now Leo Varadkar is building up a bit of a reputation himself. The Fine Gael 'Young Turk' has a growing list of slip-ups, with the latest being the most serious.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Lynch |first=Andrew |url=http://www.herald.ie/opinion/leo-wont-become-king-of-the-political-jungle-with-his-roaring-gaffes-1470085.html |newspaper=[[Evening Herald]] |location=[[Dublin]] |publisher=[[Independent News & Media]] |issn=0791-6892 |title=Leo won't become king of the political jungle with his roaring gaffes |date=5 September 2008 |access-date=26 August 2018 | quote=In a week where the Government should have been feeling the heat over its economic woes, Varadkar has landed himself in hot water with his suggestion that unemployed immigrants should be offered six months' worth of dole money in return for going back to their own countries.}}</ref>\n\n===Minister for Health (2014\u20132016)===\n[[File:Minister_Varadkar_and_Joan_Burton_open_AMA_unit_at_Connolly_Hospital,_July2014.jpg|left|thumb|Health Minister Varadkar with T\u00e1naiste [[Joan Burton]] at the opening of a unit at [[Connolly Hospital]], [[Blanchardstown]], July 2014]]\nIn the cabinet reshuffle of July 2014, Varadkar replaced [[James Reilly (Irish politician)|James Reilly]] as [[Minister for Health (Ireland)|Minister for Health]].<ref name=RT>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2014/0711/629951-cabinet/|title=Taoiseach announces new Cabinet|date=11 July 2014|publisher=[[RT\u00c9 News]]|accessdate=11 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/leo-varadkar-to-replace-reilly-as-minister-for-health-1.1862975|title=Leo Varadkar to replace Reilly as Minister for Health|first=Fiach|last=Kelly|date=11 July 2014|work=The Irish Times|accessdate=11 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nHe was returned to the D\u00e1il at the [[2016 Irish general election|2016 general election]]. He retained the health portfolio in an acting capacity until May that year, due to [[2016 Irish government formation|the delay in government formation]]. In one of his final acts as Minister for Health, Varadkar cut \u20ac12&nbsp;million from the \u20ac35&nbsp;million allocated to that year's budget for mental health care, telling the D\u00e1il that the cuts were \"necessary as the funding could be better used elsewhere.\"<ref>{{cite news|first=Michael|last=McKeowen |date=27 April 2016 |title=Varadkar: 'Mental health funding cuts were not supposed to happen but they are necessary as the funding could be better used elsewhere' |url=https://theliberal.ie/varadkar-mental-health-funding-cuts-were-not-supposed-to-happen-but-they-are-necessary-as-the-funding-could-be-better-used-elsewhere/ <!-- Now excluded from Web archiving at the Wayback Machine. --> |work=The Liberal |location=Ireland |access-date=16 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Minister for Social Protection (2016\u20132017)===\nOn 6 May 2016, after government formation talks had concluded, Taoiseach Enda Kenny appointed Varadkar as [[Minister for Employment Affairs and Social Protection|Minister for Social Protection]].<ref>[http://www.irishmirror.ie/news/irish-news/politics/leo-varadkar-insists-new-ministry-7920880 Leo Varadkar insists new ministry is not a demotion] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160508114336/http://www.irishmirror.ie/news/irish-news/politics/leo-varadkar-insists-new-ministry-7920880 |date=8 May 2016 }}, ''[[Irish Mirror]]'', 7 May 2016</ref> During his time in the ministry, he launched a campaign against welfare fraud.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dublinlive.ie/news/dublin-news/department-social-protection-earns-300m-13171066|title=The Government saved THIS much investigating dole fraud in Dublin|last=McDermott|first=Stephen|date=11 June 2017|work=dublinlive|access-date=13 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n==14th Taoiseach (2017\u2013present)==\n===2017===\n{{See also|2017 Fine Gael leadership election|Government of the 32nd D\u00e1il#31st Government of Ireland}}\n{{Wikinews|Leo Varadkar becomes first openly gay elected Taoiseach of Ireland, succeeds Enda Kenny}}\nOn 2 June 2017, Varadkar was [[2017 Fine Gael leadership election|elected leader of Fine Gael]], defeating [[Simon Coveney]].<ref name=RTE2017-06-02a>{{cite news|title=Varadkar 'delighted and humbled' by election result|url=https://www.rte.ie/news/2017/0602/879755-fine-gael-leadership/|accessdate=2 June 2017|work=RT\u00c9.ie|date=2 June 2017}}</ref> Although Coveney had the support of more Fine Gael members than Varadkar, the electoral college system more strongly weighted the votes of the party's parliamentarians, with these strongly backing Varadkar.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/FineGael/status/870693601834958848|title=Results of the combined votes cast by the Electoral College. #FGLE17|website=Twitter|date=2 June 2017|accessdate=2 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nLike Enda Kenny, Varadkar relied upon the support of Independents and the abstention of [[Fianna F\u00e1il]] TDs to support his premiership. On 14 June 2017, he was appointed Taoiseach in a 57\u201350 vote with 47 abstentions.<ref name=\"BBC_elect\">{{cite news|title=Leo Varadkar elected as Republic of Ireland's taoiseach|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-40266513|accessdate=14 June 2017|work=BBC News|date=14 June 2017}}</ref> He became Ireland's first openly gay Taoiseach, as well as the youngest.{{refn|The [[Irish heads of government since 1919#List of office-holders|List of Irish heads of government since 1919]] shows that two Irish heads of government since 1919, [[\u00c9amon de Valera]] (born 14 October 1882, and aged 36 on 1 April 1919) and [[Michael Collins (Irish Leader)|Michael Collins]] (born 16 October 1890, and aged 31 on 16 January 1922), have been younger than Varadkar (born 18 January 1979, and aged 38 on 14 June 2017). But both were before [[Taoiseach#History|the title ''Taoiseach'' was adopted]] under the [[Constitution of Ireland|1937 Constitution]], and indeed before [[Republic of Ireland#Revolution and steps to independence|the state came into internationally recognized existence on 6 December 1922]].|name=YoungerHeadsOfGovernment01|group=nb}} He is not, however, the youngest head of an Irish government; both [[\u00c9amon de Valera]] and [[Michael Collins (Irish Leader)|Michael Collins]] were younger on assuming their respective offices in revolutionary governments prior to the establishment of the state. He is also the first head of government who is of half-Indian descent.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/jun/02/leo-varadkar-becomes-irelands-prime-minister-elect|title=Leo Varadkar, gay son of Indian immigrant, to be next Irish PM|date=3 June 2017|publisher=The Guardian|last1=McDonald|first1=Henry|accessdate=3 June 2017}}</ref> It was also the first time that [[Taoiseach#List of office-holders|one Fine Gael Taoiseach was succeeded by another]].{{refn|The [[Irish heads of government since 1919#List of office-holders|List of Irish heads of government since 1919]] shows that by the end of August 1922, two heads of government from the Pro-Treaty Sinn F\u00e9in party had died in office: [[Arthur Griffith]] (who died on 12 August 1922) and [[Michael Collins (Irish Leader)|Michael Collins]] (who died on 22 August 1922). They were succeeded by [[W. T. Cosgrave]] of the same Pro-Treaty Sinn F\u00e9in faction, which, after being known as [[Cumann na nGaedheal]] from 1923 to 1933, merged with two smaller parties in 1933 to form Fine Gael, which was soon led by Cosgrave from 1934 to 1944. But that was before [[Taoiseach#History|the title ''Taoiseach'' was adopted]] under the [[Constitution of Ireland|1937 Constitution]], before the name \"Fine Gael\" [[History of Fine Gael#Origins|was adopted in 1933]], and indeed before [[Republic of Ireland#Revolution and steps to independence|the state came into internationally recognized existence on 6 December 1922]].|name=FGsucceedsFG01|group=nb}}\n\nOne of Varadkar's first acts as Taoiseach was to announce a [[Thirty-sixth Amendment of the Constitution Bill 2018 (Ireland)|referendum on abortion for 2018]]. He said that the government would also lay out a road map for achieving a low carbon economy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/oireachtas/abortion-referendum-to-be-held-next-year-varadkar-says-1.3119981|title=Abortion referendum to be held next year, Varadkar says|work=Irish Times}}</ref>\n\nHis government nearly collapsed as a result of the [[Garda whistleblower scandal]] and [[T\u00e1naiste]] (Deputy Prime Minister) [[Frances Fitzgerald (politician)|Frances Fitzgerald]]'s role in it. [[Fianna F\u00e1il]], the main opposition party, who were in a confidence-and-supply agreement with Fine Gael, threatened a motion of no confidence in the T\u00e1naiste. This action would have collapsed the government and caused a general election. Despite days of gridlock, the crisis was averted, after Fitzgerald resigned from the cabinet to prevent the election, which most of the country did not want due to the possibility of it jeopardising the Irish position in [[Brexit negotiations]]. Shortly after this, Varadkar appointed former leadership rival and [[Minister for Foreign Affairs and Trade]] Simon Coveney as T\u00e1naiste, [[Heather Humphreys]] as [[Minister for Business, Enterprise and Innovation]] and [[Josepha Madigan]] as [[Minister for Culture, Heritage and the Gaeltacht]], in a small reshuffle of the cabinet.\n\nShortly after the Fitzgerald crisis, an impasse was reached in the [[Brexit]] talks, as leader of the [[Democratic Unionist Party|DUP]] [[Arlene Foster]] objected to a deal agreed to by Varadkar, [[British Prime Minister]] [[Theresa May]] and [[President of the European Commission]], [[Jean-Claude Juncker]].{{Citation needed|date=May 2018}} This prevented an agreement from being reached as the deadline approached. Varadkar stated he was 'surprised' and 'disappointed' the UK couldn't reach a deal. However, later in the week a consensus deal was finalised. Varadkar stated he had received guarantees from the UK there would be no hard border between [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]] and [[Northern Ireland]]. He later said he and his cabinet had 'achieved all we set out to achieve' during the talks before quoting former British Prime Minister [[Winston Churchill]], by saying 'This is not the end, this is the end of the beginning\". An ''[[The Irish Times|Irish Times]]'' poll taken during these days showed Varadkar with a 53% approval rating, the highest for any Taoiseach since 2011, and showed Fine Gael with an eleven-point lead over Fianna F\u00e1il. Government satisfaction was also at 41%, the highest in almost 10 years.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/fine-gael-support-surges-on-back-of-brexit-row-1.3318116|title=Fine Gael support surges on back of Brexit row|work=The Irish Times|accessdate=20 January 2018}}</ref> ''Irish Times'' columnist Pat Leahy claimed Varadkar had ended 2017 'on a high' and IrishCentral called it the Taoiseach's 'finest hour'.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/opinion/pat-leahy-varadkar-ends-2017-on-a-high-thanks-to-brexit-talks-1.3320611?mode=sample&auth-failed=1&pw-origin=https://www.irishtimes.com/opinion/pat-leahy-varadkar-ends-2017-on-a-high-thanks-to-brexit-talks-1.3320611|title=Pat Leahy: Varadkar ends 2017 on a high thanks to Brexit talks|website=Irishtimes.com|accessdate=20 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.irishcentral.com/opinion/others/british-contempt-for-ireland-shows-over-brexit-but-irish-leader-varadkar-has-his-finest-hour|title=Finest hour for Taoiseach Varadkar over Brexit border issue|date=9 December 2017|website=Irishcentral.com|accessdate=20 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2018===\nIn January 2018, his opinion poll approval ratings reached 60%, a ten-year high for any Taoiseach.<ref>{{ cite news |title=Leo Varadkar\u2019s popularity rating grows to Bertie Ahern proportions |author= Loscher, Damian |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/leo-varadkar-s-popularity-rating-grows-to-bertie-ahern-proportions-1.3367359|newspaper=Irish Times |date=25 January 2018 |accessdate=30 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2018, he announced that the [[Thirty-sixth Amendment of the Constitution Bill 2018 (Ireland)|referendum]] to repeal Ireland's [[Eighth Amendment of the Constitution of Ireland|8th Amendment]] which prevented any liberalisation of restrictive abortion laws would take place in May. If passed, it would allow the government to introduce new legislation. It was proposed that women would be allowed unrestricted access to abortion up until 12 weeks, with exceptions if the mother's life is in danger up until six months. Varadkar said he would campaign for liberalising the laws, saying his mind was changed by difficult cases during his tenure as [[Minister for Health (Ireland)|Minister for Health]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Leo Varadkar reveals abortion referendum will be held in May |last1= Murray |first1= Shona |last2= Doyle |first2= Kevin |url=https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/politics/leo-varadkar-reveals-abortion-referendum-will-be-held-in-may-36543756.html |work=Independent.ie |date=29 January 2018 |accessdate=30 January 2018|quote=\u201cAs minister for health I became convinced that abortion had no place in the constitution\u201d said Mr Varadkar. Of the most compelling cases was that of \u201cMiss Y\u201d a migrant woman was turned away from an English port when she went to the UK for an abortion. \u201cShe went on hunger strike and became suicidal\u201d said the Taoiseach.}}</ref> The referendum was passed by a 2:1 majority.\n\n===2019===\n[[File:President Trump Meets with the Taoiseach of Ireland (48012258958).jpg|thumb|Varadkar and [[US President]] [[Donald Trump]] in Shannon, Ireland in June 2019]]\nOn 24 January 2019, Varadkar said in an interview with [[Euronews]] he was standing firm on the [[Irish backstop]] and called Brexit an act of self-harm that was not fully thought through. He also said the technology promised by the Brexiteers to solve the Northern Ireland border issue \"doesn't yet exist\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/leo-varakar-brexit-was-not-fully-thought-through/|title=Leo Varadkar: Brexit was \u2018not fully thought through\u2019|first1=James|last1=R|first2=|last2=erson|date=24 January 2019|website=POLITICO|accessdate=6 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nVaradkar stated he will refuse to ratify the [[European Union\u2013Mercosur free trade agreement|EU\u2013Mercosur free trade agreement]] unless [[Brazil]] commits to protecting the environment.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-49450495|title=Amazon fires: France and Ireland threaten to block EU trade deal|date=23 August 2019|work=[[BBC]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Amazon fires spark European rift at G7 over Mercosur trade deal |url=https://www.dw.com/en/amazon-fires-spark-european-rift-at-g7-over-mercosur-trade-deal/a-50154578 |work=Deutsche Welle |date=24 August 2019}}</ref> The fear is that the deal could lead to more deforestation of the [[Amazon rainforest]] as it expands market access to Brazilian beef.<ref>{{cite web |title=We must not barter the Amazon rainforest for burgers and steaks |url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/commentisfree/2019/jul/02/barter-amazon-rainforest-burgers-steaks-brazil|author=Watts, Jonathan|work=The Guardian | date=2 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n===2020===\n{{redirect|A Ministerial Broadcast by An Taoiseach Leo Varadkar, TD|further details on how COVID-19 impacted the country|2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Republic of Ireland}}\nOn 14 January 2020, Varadkar called for a dissolution of the D\u00e1il, which was granted by President [[Michael D. Higgins]], and scheduled [[2020 Irish general election|the next election]] for 8 February.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://president.ie/en/diary/details/president-signs-warrant-for-the-dissolution-of-the-32nd-dail |title=President signs warrant for the dissolution of the 32nd D\u00e1il |date=14 January 2020 |access-date=22 January 2020 |website=[[President of Ireland]]}}</ref> Fine Gael lost 12 seats in the election, falling to third place behind [[Fianna F\u00e1il]] and [[Sinn F\u00e9in]]. Varadkar ruled out any possibility of a Fine Gael-Sinn F\u00e9in coalition during the election campaign, though a \"grand coalition\" of Fianna F\u00e1il and Fine Gael was floated as a possibility.<ref name=carroll9feb>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/09/sinn-fein-to-try-to-form-ruling-coalition-after-irish-election-success|title=Sinn F\u00e9in to try to form ruling coalition after Irish election success|first=Rory|last=Carroll|work=The Guardian|date=9 February 2020}}</ref> However, on 12 February, Varadkar conceded that Fine Gael had lost the election and that he was very likely to become the next [[Leader of the Opposition (Ireland)|Opposition Leader]]. Varadkar added that Fine Gael was \"willing to step back\" to allow Sinn F\u00e9in, as the winner of the popular vote, to have the first opportunity to form a government.<ref>{{cite web|last=Goodbody|first=Will|url=https://www.rte.ie/news/ireland/2020/0212/1114778-varadkar-election/|title=Varadkar says Sinn F\u00e9in must now build a coalition|website=[[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann|RTE.ie]]|date=12 February 2020|accessdate=12 February 2020}}</ref> On 20 February, Varadkar offered his resignation to President Higgins at [[\u00c1ras an Uachtar\u00e1in]], remaining, however, as Taoiseach in a caretaker capacity until [[2020 Irish government formation|the formation of a new government]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rte.ie/news/politics/2020/0221/1116630-dail-taoiseach/|title=Taoiseach to continue in caretaker capacity amid D\u00e1il deadlock|first=M\u00edche\u00e1l|last=Lehane|date=21 February 2020|accessdate=21 February 2020|website=[[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann|RTE.ie]]}}</ref> \n\nDuring this period, the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Republic of Ireland|COVID-19 pandemic]] arrived in Ireland. While in Washington ahead of [[Saint Patrick's Day]], Varadkar announced measures intended to stop COVID-19 spreading, including the closure of all schools, universities and childcare facilities from the following day, as well as the closure of all cultural institutions and the cancellation of \"all indoor mass gatherings of more than 100 people and outdoor mass gatherings of more than 500 people\".<ref>https://merrionstreet.ie/en/News-Room/News/Statement_by_An_Taoiseach_Leo_Varadkar_On_measures_to_tackle_Covid-19_Washington_12_March_2020.html</ref> After returning home early, Varadkar addressed the nation on Saint Patrick's night during ''A Ministerial Broadcast by An Taoiseach Leo Varadkar, TD'', introducing television viewers to the concept of \"[[Cocooning (behaviour)|cocooning]]\", i.e. \"At a certain point\u2026 we will advise the elderly and people who have a long-term illness to stay at home for several weeks\".<ref>https://www.thejournal.ie/leo-varadkar-white-house-st-patricks-day-5036232-Mar2020/</ref><ref>https://www.independent.ie/world-news/coronavirus/short-us-trip-for-varadkar-as-washington-mayor-declares-state-of-emergency-over-coronavirus-spread-39038043.html</ref><ref>https://merrionstreet.ie/en/News-Room/Speeches/Address_by_An_Taoiseach_Leo_Varadkar_17th_March.html</ref> The speech was the most watched television event in Irish history, surpassing the previous record held by ''[[The Late Late Toy Show]]'' by an additional total of about 25% and was widely distributed globally.<ref>https://www.independent.ie/entertainment/television/tv-news/leos-speech-sets-new-tv-record-as-16-million-tune-in-39057364.html</ref><ref>https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/politics/behind-the-lines-the-who-how-and-why-that-created-leo-varadkars-historic-speech-39057126.html</ref> It was also plagiarised by [[Peter Bellew]], the chief operating officer at British low-cost airline group [[EasyJet]].<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/business/2020/mar/21/easyjet-sorry-as-staff-motivation-video-copies-leo-varadkar</ref>\n\nIn response to a March 2020 [[Health Service Executive]] appeal to healthcare professionals, Varadkar rejoined the medical register and offered to work as a doctor one day each week.<ref name=\"guardian-5apr2020\">{{cite news |last1=Carroll |first1=Rory |title=Irish taoiseach Leo Varadkar to work a day a week as a doctor |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/05/irish-taoiseach-leo-varadkar-to-work-a-day-a-week-as-a-doctor |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nVaradkar is the first Irish government leader of Indian origin and has visited India on a number of occasions. He completed his medical internship at [[King Edward Memorial Hospital and Seth Gordhandas Sunderdas Medical College|KEM Hospital]] in his father's childhood city of [[Mumbai]].\n\nDuring an interview on [[RT\u00c9 Radio]] on 18 January 2015 (his 36th birthday), Varadkar spoke publicly for the first time about being gay: \"it's not something that defines me. I'm not a half-Indian politician, or a doctor politician or a gay politician for that matter. It's just part of who I am, it doesn't define me, it is part of my character I suppose\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/leo-varadkar-i-am-a-gay-man-minister-says-1.2070189|title=Leo Varadkar: 'I am a gay man', Minister says|work=The Irish Times|date=18 January 2015|accessdate=18 January 2015}}</ref> Varadkar was a prominent advocate of the [[Thirty-fourth Amendment of the Constitution of Ireland|same-sex marriage referendum]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/leo-varadkar-i-wanted-to-be-an-equal-citizen-and-today-i-am-1.2223688|title=Leo Varadkar: 'I wanted to be an equal citizen . . . and today I am'|work=The Irish Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.independent.ie/irish-news/referendum/10-factors-behind-the-yes-sides-victory-31247192.html|title=10 factors behind the 'Yes' side's victory|author=Nial O'Connor|work=The Irish Independent|date=23 May 2015}}</ref> His partner, Matthew Barrett, is a doctor at [[Mater Misericordiae University Hospital]].<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.independent.ie/irish-news/meet-the-dashing-doctor-boyfriend-supporting-leo-varadkar-in-his-fine-gael-leadership-bid-35469585.html | accessdate = 29 May 2017 | date = 21 February 2017 | work = The Independent | title = Meet the dashing doctor boyfriend supporting Leo Varadkar in his Fine Gael leadership bid }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | work = The Irish Times | url = https://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/fine-gael-leadership-race-leo-varadkar-1.3086625 | accessdate = 29 May 2017 | title = Fine Gael leadership race: Leo Varadkar | date= 17 May 2017 | first = Sarah | last = Barton}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2019, to mark the [[Stonewall 50 \u2013 WorldPride NYC 2019|50th anniversary]] of the [[Stonewall riots]], an event widely considered a watershed moment in the modern [[LGBT rights movement|LGBTQ rights movement]], ''[[Queerty]]'' named him one of the ''Pride50'' \"trailblazing individuals who actively ensure society remains moving towards [[LGBT equality|equality]], acceptance and dignity for all [[queer]] people\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.queerty.com/pride50|title=Queerty Pride50 2019 Honorees|website=Queerty|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-18}}</ref>\n\nVaradkar completed a course in professional Irish, and devised an [[Irish language]] form for his surname, Leo de Varad.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/heritage/maith-an-fear-taoiseach-awarded-certificate-for-irish-language-course-1.3214781?mode=amp|title=Maith an fear: Taoiseach awarded certificate for Irish language course|website=www.irishtimes.com|access-date=2019-06-15}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of LGBT heads of government]]\n\n==Notes==\n<references group=\"nb\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commonscat}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*{{Official website|leovaradkar.ie}}\n*[http://www.finegael.ie/our-people/ministers/leo-varadkar/ Leo Varadkar's page on the Fine Gael website]\n\n{{s-start}} \n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[Pat Carey]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Minister for Transport, Tourism and Sport]]\n       |years  = 2011\u20132014}}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[Paschal Donohoe]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before = [[James Reilly (Irish politician)|James Reilly]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Minister for Health (Ireland)|Minister for Health]]\n       |years  = 2014\u20132016}}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[Simon Harris (politician)|Simon Harris]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before = [[Joan Burton]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Minister for Employment Affairs and Social Protection|Minister for Social Protection]]\n       |years  = 2016\u20132017}}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[Regina Doherty]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before = [[Enda Kenny]]|rows = 2}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Taoiseach]]\n       |years  = 2017\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc|rows   = 2}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Minister for Defence (Ireland)|Minister for Defence]]\n       |years  = 2017\u2013present}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[Enda Kenny]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Leader of Fine Gael]]\n       |years  = 2017\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Navboxes|title=Leo Varadkar navigational boxes|list1=\n{{Heads of government of Ireland}}\n{{European Council}}\n{{Current Government of Ireland}}\n{{Current TDs}}\n{{29th Government of Ireland}}\n{{30th Government of Ireland}}\n{{Ministers for Health of Ireland}}\n{{Ministers for Transport of Ireland}}\n{{Ministers for Social Affairs of Ireland}}\n{{Ministers for Defence of Ireland}}\n{{Fine Gael}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Varadkar, Leo}}\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Trinity College Dublin]]\n[[Category:Fine Gael TDs]]\n[[Category:Gay politicians]]\n[[Category:Irish people of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:LGBT conservatism]]\n[[Category:LGBT heads of government]]\n[[Category:LGBT history in Ireland]]\n[[Category:LGBT legislators]]\n[[Category:LGBT politicians from Ireland]]\n[[Category:LGBT rights activists from Ireland]]\n[[Category:Local councillors in Fingal]]\n[[Category:Members of the 30th D\u00e1il]]\n[[Category:Members of the 31st D\u00e1il]]\n[[Category:Members of the 32nd D\u00e1il]]\n[[Category:Members of the 33rd D\u00e1il]]\n[[Category:Ministers for Defence (Ireland)]]\n[[Category:Ministers for Health (Ireland)]]\n[[Category:Ministers for Social Affairs (Ireland)]]\n[[Category:Ministers for Transport (Ireland)]]\n[[Category:People educated at The King's Hospital]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Fingal]]\n[[Category:Politicians of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:Taoisigh]]\n[[Category:21st-century Irish medical doctors]]\n[[Category:Young Fine Gael]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-vandalism|small=yes}}\n{{redirect|Varadkar|the surname|Varadkar (surname)}}\n{{short description|Irish politician; Taoiseach (Prime Minister) of Ireland, current Minister for Defence, and leader of the Fine Gael party}}\n{{Use Irish English|date=June 2018}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name          = Leo Varadkar\n|honorific-suffix = [[Teachta D\u00e1la|TD]]\n|image         = Leo Varadkar October 2019.jpg\n|caption       = Varadkar in 2019\n|order         = 14th\n|office        = Taoiseach\n|president     = [[Michael D. Higgins]]\n|1blankname    = [[T\u00e1naiste]]\n|1namedata     = [[Frances Fitzgerald (politician)|Frances Fitzgerald]]<br>[[Simon Coveney]]\n|term_start    = 14 June 2017\n|term_end      = \n|predecessor   = [[Enda Kenny]]\n|successor     =\n|office1       = [[Leader of Fine Gael]]\n|deputy1       = Simon Coveney\n|term_start1   = 2 June 2017\n|term_end1     =\n|predecessor1  = Enda Kenny\n|successor1    =\n|office2       = [[Minister for Defence (Ireland)|Minister for Defence]]\n|term_start2   = 14 June 2017\n|term_end2     =\n|predecessor2  = Enda Kenny\n|successor2    =\n|office3       = [[Minister for Employment Affairs and Social Protection|Minister for Social Protection]]\n|taoiseach3    = Enda Kenny\n|term_start3   = 6 May 2016\n|term_end3     = 14 June 2017\n|predecessor3  = [[Joan Burton]]\n|successor3    = [[Regina Doherty]]\n|office4       = [[Minister for Health (Ireland)|Minister for Health]]\n|taoiseach4    = Enda Kenny\n|term_start4   = 11 July 2014\n|term_end4     = 6 May 2016\n|predecessor4  = [[James Reilly (Irish politician)|James Reilly]]\n|successor4    = [[Simon Harris (politician)|Simon Harris]]\n|office5       = [[Minister for Transport, Tourism and Sport]]\n|taoiseach5    = Enda Kenny\n|term_start5   = 9 March 2011\n|term_end5     = 11 July 2014\n|predecessor5  = [[Pat Carey]]\n|successor5    = [[Paschal Donohoe]]\n|office6       = [[Teachta D\u00e1la]]\n|term_start6   = [[2007 Irish general election|June 2007]]\n|term_end6     =\n|constituency6 = [[Dublin West (D\u00e1il constituency)|Dublin West]]\n|birth_name    = Leo Eric Varadkar\n|birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1979|1|18|df=y}}\n|birth_place   = [[Rotunda Hospital]], [[Dublin]], Ireland\n|death_date    = \n|death_place   =\n|nationality   = [[Irish people|Irish]]\n|party         = [[Fine Gael]]\n|partner       = Matthew Barrett {{small|(2015\u2013present)}}\n|children      =\n|parents       = {{Unbulleted list|Ashok Varadkar|Miriam Varadkar}}\n|education     = [[The King's Hospital]]\n|alma_mater    = [[Trinity College Dublin]]\n|signature     =\n|website       = {{url|taoiseach.gov.ie|Official website}}<br>{{url|leovaradkar.ie|Constituency website}}\n|}}\n'''Leo Eric Varadkar''' ({{IPAc-en|v|\u0259|\u02c8|r|\u00e6|d|k|\u0259r}} {{respell|v\u0259|RAD|k\u0259r}}; born 18 January 1979) is an Irish [[Fine Gael]] politician and [[physician]]. He has served as the [[Leader of Fine Gael]], and as [[Taoiseach]] and [[Minister for Defence (Ireland)|Minister for Defence]] in the [[Government of Ireland]], since June 2017. Following the [[2020 Irish general election]] in which Fine Gael were returned as the third largest party behind [[Fianna F\u00e1il]] and [[Sinn F\u00e9in]], Varadkar resigned but remains in office as caretaker Taoiseach until a successor is appointed. He has also been a [[Teachta D\u00e1la]] (TD) for the [[Dublin West (D\u00e1il constituency)|Dublin West]] constituency since [[2007 Irish general election|2007]].\n\nVaradkar was born in [[Dublin]] and studied medicine at [[Trinity College Dublin]]. He spent several years as a non-consultant hospital doctor, eventually qualifying as a [[general practitioner]] in 2010. In 2004, he joined Fine Gael and became a member of [[Fingal County Council]] and later served as Deputy Mayor. He was elected to [[D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann]] for the first time in 2007. \n\nDuring the 2015 [[2015 Irish constitutional referendums|same-sex marriage referendum]], Varadkar [[Coming out|came out]] as gay, becoming the first Irish Minister to do so.<ref>{{cite news|last=Armstrong |first=Kathy |url=http://www.independent.ie/irish-news/politics/significant-step-for-equality-the-world-reacts-to-leo-varadkar-becoming-the-new-fine-gael-leader-35782985.html |title='Significant step for equality'- the world reacts to Leo Varadkar becoming the new Fine Gael leader |work=[[Irish Independent]] |publisher=[[Independent News & Media]] |location=[[Dublin]] |issn=0021-1222 |date=2 June 2017 |access-date=25 August 2018}}</ref> He is Ireland's first, and the world's fourth, [[List of the first LGBT holders of political offices|openly gay head of government]] in modern times,<ref>{{Cite news|last= Kwak |first=Bethia |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/feature/nbc-out/ireland-appears-set-elect-first-openly-gay-prime-minister-n765426|title=Ireland appears set to elect first openly gay prime minister|work=[[NBC News]]|date=27 May 2017 |access-date=13 November 2017|language=en-US |quote=If elected, Varadkar would only be the fourth openly gay world leader in modern history. The others include [[Prime Minister of Luxembourg]], [[Xavier Bettel]], former [[Prime Minister of Belgium]], [[Elio Di Rupo]], and former [[Prime Minister of Iceland]], [[J\u00f3hanna Sigur\u00f0ard\u00f3ttir]].}}</ref> and first Taoiseach of [[India]]n heritage.  ''[[The Economist]]'' says of him: \"Not since the days of [[\u00c9amon de Valera]] has Ireland had a leader as globally recognisable as Leo Varadkar.\"<ref>The Economist, \"The rise of Sinn Fein, an Irish party that once espoused violence,\" February 6, 2020 [https://www.economist.com/europe/2020/02/06/the-rise-of-sinn-fein-an-irish-party-that-once-espoused-violence]</ref>\n\nHe later served in the [[Enda Kenny|Kenny Government]], as [[Minister for Employment Affairs and Social Protection|Minister for Social Protection]] from 2016 to 2017, [[Minister for Health (Ireland)|Minister for Health]] from 2014 to 2016 and [[Minister for Transport, Tourism and Sport]] from 2011 to 2014.<ref name=RTE2017-06-08a>{{cite news|title=More 'disappointments than appointments' over cabinet selection \u2013 Varadkar|url=https://www.rte.ie/news/politics/2017/0608/881166-leo-varadkar/ |access-date=10 June 2017|publisher=[[RT\u00c9 News]]|date=8 June 2017|quote=Mr Varadkar, who is on course to be elected taoiseach in the D\u00e1il next Wednesday, ... He described his meetings with Fianna F\u00e1il and Independents yesterday as \"fruitful\".}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2017, Kenny announced that he would resign as Taoiseach and Fine Gael Leader. Varadkar stood in the [[2017 Fine Gael leadership election|leadership election]] to replace him; although more party members voted for his opponent, [[Simon Coveney]], he won by a significant margin among members of the [[Oireachtas]], and was elected leader on 2 June. 12 days later, he was appointed Taoiseach, and at 38 years old became the youngest person to hold the office.<ref>{{Cite news|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/leo-varadkar-born-to-an-indian-father-a-historic-gay-pm-for-ireland/story-Nyxchjg1avrV5hqUQPe3qJ.html|title=Leo Varadkar: Born to an Indian father, a historic gay PM for Ireland|last=|first=|date=3 June 2017|work=[[Hindustan Times]]|location=[[New Delhi]] |publisher=[[HT Media]] |access-date=13 November 2017 |agency=[[Agence France-Presse]] |issn=0972-0243}}</ref> \n\n==Early life==\nBorn on 18 January 1979, in the [[Rotunda Hospital]], [[Dublin]], Varadkar is the third child and only son of Ashok and Miriam (n\u00e9e Howell) Varadkar. His father was born in Bombay (now [[Mumbai]]), [[India]], and moved to the [[United Kingdom]] in the 1960s, to work as a doctor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/world/varad-village-in-maharashtra-rejoices-as-leo-varadkar-is-set-to-be-irish-pm-4687123/|title=Varad village in Maharashtra rejoices as Leo Varadkar is set to be Irish PM|date=3 June 2017|publisher=IndianExpress.com}}</ref> His mother, born in [[Dungarvan]], [[County Waterford]], met her future husband while working as a nurse in [[Slough]].<ref>{{Cite news| last=McDonald |first=Henry |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/jun/02/leo-varadkar-becomes-irelands-prime-minister-elect |title=Leo Varadkar, gay son of Indian immigrant, to be next Irish PM |date=2 June 2017 |work=[[The Guardian]] |location=[[London]] |publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]] |access-date=13 November 2017 |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> They married in the UK, early in 1971,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=LpXrN9C1aygapjYzkUf0Og&scan=1|title=Index entry|accessdate=16 February 2018|work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}}</ref> then lived in [[Leicester]], where the eldest of their three children, Sophie, was born. The family moved to India, before settling in Dublin in 1973, where their second child, Sonia, was born.\n\nThough Varadkar had been born to a [[Hindu]] father and a [[Catholic]] mother, his parents made the decision to raise him in the Catholic faith.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bielenberg |first1=Kim |title=Why Leo, the petulant political puppy, is still happily wagging his tail |url=http://www.independent.ie/lifestyle/why-leo-the-petulant-political-puppy-is-still-happily-wagging-his-tail-26739416.html |access-date=3 June 2017 |work=[[Irish Independent]] |publisher=[[Independent News & Media]] |issn=0021-1222 |date=4 June 2011 |quote=His father is Hindu and his mother Catholic. When they got married in church they had to get special permission and agree to bring up the children as Catholic. Varadkar once said: \"They deliberately decided that if we were to be brought up in a Western country that we would be brought up in the culture of our country. I think it's a sensible thing.\"}}</ref> He was educated at the St Francis Xavier National School, [[Blanchardstown]]. His second-level education took place at [[The King's Hospital]] in [[Palmerstown]], a boarding school run by the [[Church of Ireland]].\n\nDuring his secondary schooling, he joined [[Young Fine Gael]]. He was admitted to [[Trinity College Dublin]] (TCD), where he briefly studied law. He later switched to medicine. At TCD he was active in the university's Young Fine Gael branch and served as Vice-President of the [[Youth of the European People's Party]], the youth wing of the [[European People's Party]], of which [[Fine Gael]] is a member.<ref>{{cite news |last=McGee |first=Harry |url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/weekend/2010/1120/1224283746408.html |title=The Saturday Interview |work=[[The Irish Times]] |location=[[Dublin]] |issn=1393-3515 |date=20 November 2010 |access-date=25 August 2018}}</ref> Varadkar was selected for the Washington Ireland Program for Service and Leadership (WIP), a prestigious half-year personal and professional development program in [[Washington, D.C.]], for students from Ireland.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tcd.ie/news_events/articles/first-trinity-graduate-elected-taoiseach/|title=First Trinity Graduate elected Taoiseach|date=13 June 2017|website=Trinity News and Events}}</ref>\n\nHe graduated from the [[School of Medicine (Trinity College Dublin)]] in 2003, after he completed his internship at KEM Hospital in Mumbai.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/world/irelands-new-prime-minister-leo-varadkar-is-a-real-global-indian-says-family-back-home-3512287.html|title=Ireland\u2019s new Prime Minister Leo Varadkar is a 'real global Indian', says family back home - Firstpost|website=www.firstpost.com|access-date=18 June 2018}}</ref> He then spent several years working as a junior doctor in [[St. James's Hospital]] and [[Connolly Hospital]], before qualifying as a [[general practitioner]] in 2010.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/Leo-Varadkar|title=Leo Varadkar {{!}} Biography & Facts|work=Encyclopedia Britannica|access-date=13 November 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Early political career==\n===Fingal County Council (2003\u20132007)===\nVaradkar was twenty years old and a second-year medical student when he unsuccessfully contested the [[1999 Irish local elections|1999 local elections]] in the [[Mulhuddart]] electoral area. Varadkar was co-opted to [[Fingal County Council]] in 2003, for the [[Castleknock]] local electoral area, as a replacement for [[Sheila Terry (politician)|Sheila Terry]]. At the [[2004 Irish local elections|2004 local elections]], he received the highest first-preference vote in the country with 4,894 votes and was elected on the first count.<ref name=elecs_irl>{{cite web|url=http://www.electionsireland.org/candidate.cfm?ID=321|title=Leo Varadkar|publisher=ElectionsIreland.org |accessdate=8 September 2009}}</ref>\n\n===D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann (2007\u2013present)===\nVaradkar was elected to [[D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann]] at the [[2007 Irish general election|2007 general election]].<ref name=oireachtas_db>{{cite web|url=https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/members/member/Leo-Varadkar.D.2007-06-14/|title=Leo Varadkar|work=Oireachtas Members Database|accessdate=8 September 2009}}</ref> Then [[List of Irish Leaders of the Opposition|Leader of the Opposition]], [[Enda Kenny]], appointed him to the [[Fine Gael Front Bench|Front Bench]] as Spokesperson for [[Minister for Business, Enterprise and Innovation|Enterprise, Trade and Employment]] until a 2010 reshuffle, when he became [[Minister for Communications, Climate Action and Environment|Spokesperson on Communications, Energy and Natural Resources]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bardon|first1=Sarah|title=Profile: Leo Varadkar (FG)|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/oireachtas/profile-leo-varadkar-fg-1.2552227|accessdate=3 June 2017|work=The Irish Times|date=3 June 2017}}</ref> At the [[2011 Irish general election|2011 general election]], Varadkar was re-elected to D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann, with 8,359 first-preference votes (a 19.7% share of the poll in a four-seat constituency).<ref name=elecs_irl/>\n\n==Government minister==\n===Minister for Transport, Tourism, and Sport (2011\u20132014)===\nWhen Fine Gael formed a coalition government with the [[Labour Party (Ireland)|Labour Party]], Varadkar was appointed [[Minister for Transport, Tourism and Sport]] on 9 March 2011.<ref name=\"RT\u00c9\">{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2011/0309/finance-business.html|title=Noonan named as new Finance Minister|publisher=[[RT\u00c9 News]]|date=9 March 2011}}</ref> This was considered a surprise appointment, as Varadkar was not known as a sports lover. He said that while he knew \"a lot of facts&nbsp;... I don't play the sports.\"<ref name=\"'True blue' Varadkar red card flag\">{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/national-news/true-blue-varadkar-gets-red-card-as-dail-officials-flag-problem-2877295.html|work=[[Irish Independent]]|title='True blue' Varadkar gets red card as D\u00e1il officials flag problem|date=15 September 2011|first=Fionnan|last=Sheahan}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2011, Varadkar suggested Ireland was \"very unlikely\" to resume borrowing in 2012 and might need a [[Post-2008 Irish economic downturn#EU-IMF intervention|second bailout]], causing jitters on international markets about Ireland's credibility.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/opinion/2011/0601/1224298206616.html|work=[[The Irish Times]]|title=To borrow a phrase, Minister|date=1 June 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052702303657404576354983728036512|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|title=Bond Auctions Test Contagion Fears|date=30 May 2011|first1=Emese|last1=Bartha|first2=Eamon|last2=Quinn}}</ref> Many of his cabinet colleagues frowned on Varadkar's forthrightness, as did the [[European Central Bank]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/frontpage/2011/0531/1224298146011.html|work=[[The Irish Times]]|title=Cabinet colleagues angered at Varadkar bailout view|date=31 May 2011|first1=Stephen|last1=Collins|first2=Arthur|last2=Beesley}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/business/irish/trichet-talks-verbal-discipline-after-leos-gaffe-2671031.html|work=[[Irish Independent]]|title=Trichet talks 'verbal discipline' after Leo's gaffe|date=10 June 2011|first=Laura|last=Noonan}}</ref> [[Taoiseach]] [[Enda Kenny]] repeated the line of the [[Government of Ireland]], that the State would not require a further [[EU]]-[[IMF]] bailout, and said he had warned all Ministers against publicly disparaging the economy.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/breaking/2011/0531/breaking3.html|work=[[The Irish Times]]|title=State 'won't require' second bailout|date=31 May 2011|first1=Michael|last1=O'Regan|first2=Marie|last2=O'Halloran}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/national-news/kenny-lays-down-law-to-ministers-after-varadkars-gaffe-on-bailout-2662634.html|work=[[Irish Independent]]|title=Kenny lays down law to ministers after Varadkar's gaffe on bailout|date=1 June 2011|first1=Fionnan|last1=Sheahan|first2=Colm|last2=Kelpie}}</ref> Varadkar said that reaction to the story was hyped up but that he was not misquoted.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2011/0602/economy.html|title=Bailout comments were 'hyped up' \u2013 Varadkar|publisher=[[RT\u00c9 News]]|date=2 June 2011}}</ref> The ''[[Evening Herald]]'' repeatedly described Varadkar as gaffe prone.<ref>{{cite news |last=Doyle |first=Kevin |url=http://www.herald.ie/national-news/new-gaffe-is-just-one-of-a-growing-list-2661193.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120925120923/http://www.herald.ie/news/new-gaffe-is-just-one-of-a-growing-list-2661193.html |archive-date=25 September 2012 |newspaper=[[Evening Herald]] |location=[[Dublin]] |publisher=[[Independent News & Media]] |issn=0791-6892 |title=New gaffe is just one of a growing list |date=30 May 2011 |access-date=26 August 2018 |quote=He spent years tongue-lashing Calamity Coughlin for her gaffes, but now Leo Varadkar is building up a bit of a reputation himself. The Fine Gael 'Young Turk' has a growing list of slip-ups, with the latest being the most serious.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Lynch |first=Andrew |url=http://www.herald.ie/opinion/leo-wont-become-king-of-the-political-jungle-with-his-roaring-gaffes-1470085.html |newspaper=[[Evening Herald]] |location=[[Dublin]] |publisher=[[Independent News & Media]] |issn=0791-6892 |title=Leo won't become king of the political jungle with his roaring gaffes |date=5 September 2008 |access-date=26 August 2018 | quote=In a week where the Government should have been feeling the heat over its economic woes, Varadkar has landed himself in hot water with his suggestion that unemployed immigrants should be offered six months' worth of dole money in return for going back to their own countries.}}</ref>\n\n===Minister for Health (2014\u20132016)===\n[[File:Minister_Varadkar_and_Joan_Burton_open_AMA_unit_at_Connolly_Hospital,_July2014.jpg|left|thumb|Health Minister Varadkar with T\u00e1naiste [[Joan Burton]] at the opening of a unit at [[Connolly Hospital]], [[Blanchardstown]], July 2014]]\nIn the cabinet reshuffle of July 2014, Varadkar replaced [[James Reilly (Irish politician)|James Reilly]] as [[Minister for Health (Ireland)|Minister for Health]].<ref name=RT>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2014/0711/629951-cabinet/|title=Taoiseach announces new Cabinet|date=11 July 2014|publisher=[[RT\u00c9 News]]|accessdate=11 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/leo-varadkar-to-replace-reilly-as-minister-for-health-1.1862975|title=Leo Varadkar to replace Reilly as Minister for Health|first=Fiach|last=Kelly|date=11 July 2014|work=The Irish Times|accessdate=11 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nHe was returned to the D\u00e1il at the [[2016 Irish general election|2016 general election]]. He retained the health portfolio in an acting capacity until May that year, due to [[2016 Irish government formation|the delay in government formation]]. In one of his final acts as Minister for Health, Varadkar cut \u20ac12&nbsp;million from the \u20ac35&nbsp;million allocated to that year's budget for mental health care, telling the D\u00e1il that the cuts were \"necessary as the funding could be better used elsewhere.\"<ref>{{cite news|first=Michael|last=McKeowen |date=27 April 2016 |title=Varadkar: 'Mental health funding cuts were not supposed to happen but they are necessary as the funding could be better used elsewhere' |url=https://theliberal.ie/varadkar-mental-health-funding-cuts-were-not-supposed-to-happen-but-they-are-necessary-as-the-funding-could-be-better-used-elsewhere/ <!-- Now excluded from Web archiving at the Wayback Machine. --> |work=The Liberal |location=Ireland |access-date=16 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Minister for Social Protection (2016\u20132017)===\nOn 6 May 2016, after government formation talks had concluded, Taoiseach Enda Kenny appointed Varadkar as [[Minister for Employment Affairs and Social Protection|Minister for Social Protection]].<ref>[http://www.irishmirror.ie/news/irish-news/politics/leo-varadkar-insists-new-ministry-7920880 Leo Varadkar insists new ministry is not a demotion] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160508114336/http://www.irishmirror.ie/news/irish-news/politics/leo-varadkar-insists-new-ministry-7920880 |date=8 May 2016 }}, ''[[Irish Mirror]]'', 7 May 2016</ref> During his time in the ministry, he launched a campaign against welfare fraud.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dublinlive.ie/news/dublin-news/department-social-protection-earns-300m-13171066|title=The Government saved THIS much investigating dole fraud in Dublin|last=McDermott|first=Stephen|date=11 June 2017|work=dublinlive|access-date=13 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n==14th Taoiseach (2017\u2013present)==\n===2017===\n{{See also|2017 Fine Gael leadership election|Government of the 32nd D\u00e1il#31st Government of Ireland}}\n{{Wikinews|Leo Varadkar becomes first openly gay elected Taoiseach of Ireland, succeeds Enda Kenny}}\nOn 2 June 2017, Varadkar was [[2017 Fine Gael leadership election|elected leader of Fine Gael]], defeating [[Simon Coveney]].<ref name=RTE2017-06-02a>{{cite news|title=Varadkar 'delighted and humbled' by election result|url=https://www.rte.ie/news/2017/0602/879755-fine-gael-leadership/|accessdate=2 June 2017|work=RT\u00c9.ie|date=2 June 2017}}</ref> Although Coveney had the support of more Fine Gael members than Varadkar, the electoral college system more strongly weighted the votes of the party's parliamentarians, with these strongly backing Varadkar.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/FineGael/status/870693601834958848|title=Results of the combined votes cast by the Electoral College. #FGLE17|website=Twitter|date=2 June 2017|accessdate=2 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nLike Enda Kenny, Varadkar relied upon the support of Independents and the abstention of [[Fianna F\u00e1il]] TDs to support his premiership. On 14 June 2017, he was appointed Taoiseach in a 57\u201350 vote with 47 abstentions.<ref name=\"BBC_elect\">{{cite news|title=Leo Varadkar elected as Republic of Ireland's taoiseach|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-40266513|accessdate=14 June 2017|work=BBC News|date=14 June 2017}}</ref> He became Ireland's first openly gay Taoiseach, as well as the youngest.{{refn|The [[Irish heads of government since 1919#List of office-holders|List of Irish heads of government since 1919]] shows that two Irish heads of government since 1919, [[\u00c9amon de Valera]] (born 14 October 1882, and aged 36 on 1 April 1919) and [[Michael Collins (Irish Leader)|Michael Collins]] (born 16 October 1890, and aged 31 on 16 January 1922), have been younger than Varadkar (born 18 January 1979, and aged 38 on 14 June 2017). But both were before [[Taoiseach#History|the title ''Taoiseach'' was adopted]] under the [[Constitution of Ireland|1937 Constitution]], and indeed before [[Republic of Ireland#Revolution and steps to independence|the state came into internationally recognized existence on 6 December 1922]].|name=YoungerHeadsOfGovernment01|group=nb}} He is not, however, the youngest head of an Irish government; both [[\u00c9amon de Valera]] and [[Michael Collins (Irish Leader)|Michael Collins]] were younger on assuming their respective offices in revolutionary governments prior to the establishment of the state. He is also the first head of government who is of half-Indian descent.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/jun/02/leo-varadkar-becomes-irelands-prime-minister-elect|title=Leo Varadkar, gay son of Indian immigrant, to be next Irish PM|date=3 June 2017|publisher=The Guardian|last1=McDonald|first1=Henry|accessdate=3 June 2017}}</ref> It was also the first time that [[Taoiseach#List of office-holders|one Fine Gael Taoiseach was succeeded by another]].{{refn|The [[Irish heads of government since 1919#List of office-holders|List of Irish heads of government since 1919]] shows that by the end of August 1922, two heads of government from the Pro-Treaty Sinn F\u00e9in party had died in office: [[Arthur Griffith]] (who died on 12 August 1922) and [[Michael Collins (Irish Leader)|Michael Collins]] (who died on 22 August 1922). They were succeeded by [[W. T. Cosgrave]] of the same Pro-Treaty Sinn F\u00e9in faction, which, after being known as [[Cumann na nGaedheal]] from 1923 to 1933, merged with two smaller parties in 1933 to form Fine Gael, which was soon led by Cosgrave from 1934 to 1944. But that was before [[Taoiseach#History|the title ''Taoiseach'' was adopted]] under the [[Constitution of Ireland|1937 Constitution]], before the name \"Fine Gael\" [[History of Fine Gael#Origins|was adopted in 1933]], and indeed before [[Republic of Ireland#Revolution and steps to independence|the state came into internationally recognized existence on 6 December 1922]].|name=FGsucceedsFG01|group=nb}}\n\nOne of Varadkar's first acts as Taoiseach was to announce a [[Thirty-sixth Amendment of the Constitution Bill 2018 (Ireland)|referendum on abortion for 2018]]. He said that the government would also lay out a road map for achieving a low carbon economy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/oireachtas/abortion-referendum-to-be-held-next-year-varadkar-says-1.3119981|title=Abortion referendum to be held next year, Varadkar says|work=Irish Times}}</ref>\n\nHis government nearly collapsed as a result of the [[Garda whistleblower scandal]] and [[T\u00e1naiste]] (Deputy Prime Minister) [[Frances Fitzgerald (politician)|Frances Fitzgerald]]'s role in it. [[Fianna F\u00e1il]], the main opposition party, who were in a confidence-and-supply agreement with Fine Gael, threatened a motion of no confidence in the T\u00e1naiste. This action would have collapsed the government and caused a general election. Despite days of gridlock, the crisis was averted, after Fitzgerald resigned from the cabinet to prevent the election, which most of the country did not want due to the possibility of it jeopardising the Irish position in [[Brexit negotiations]]. Shortly after this, Varadkar appointed former leadership rival and [[Minister for Foreign Affairs and Trade]] Simon Coveney as T\u00e1naiste, [[Heather Humphreys]] as [[Minister for Business, Enterprise and Innovation]] and [[Josepha Madigan]] as [[Minister for Culture, Heritage and the Gaeltacht]], in a small reshuffle of the cabinet.\n\nShortly after the Fitzgerald crisis, an impasse was reached in the [[Brexit]] talks, as leader of the [[Democratic Unionist Party|DUP]] [[Arlene Foster]] objected to a deal agreed to by Varadkar, [[British Prime Minister]] [[Theresa May]] and [[President of the European Commission]], [[Jean-Claude Juncker]].{{Citation needed|date=May 2018}} This prevented an agreement from being reached as the deadline approached. Varadkar stated he was 'surprised' and 'disappointed' the UK couldn't reach a deal. However, later in the week a consensus deal was finalised. Varadkar stated he had received guarantees from the UK there would be no hard border between [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]] and [[Northern Ireland]]. He later said he and his cabinet had 'achieved all we set out to achieve' during the talks before quoting former British Prime Minister [[Winston Churchill]], by saying 'This is not the end, this is the end of the beginning\". An ''[[The Irish Times|Irish Times]]'' poll taken during these days showed Varadkar with a 53% approval rating, the highest for any Taoiseach since 2011, and showed Fine Gael with an eleven-point lead over Fianna F\u00e1il. Government satisfaction was also at 41%, the highest in almost 10 years.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/fine-gael-support-surges-on-back-of-brexit-row-1.3318116|title=Fine Gael support surges on back of Brexit row|work=The Irish Times|accessdate=20 January 2018}}</ref> ''Irish Times'' columnist Pat Leahy claimed Varadkar had ended 2017 'on a high' and IrishCentral called it the Taoiseach's 'finest hour'.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/opinion/pat-leahy-varadkar-ends-2017-on-a-high-thanks-to-brexit-talks-1.3320611?mode=sample&auth-failed=1&pw-origin=https://www.irishtimes.com/opinion/pat-leahy-varadkar-ends-2017-on-a-high-thanks-to-brexit-talks-1.3320611|title=Pat Leahy: Varadkar ends 2017 on a high thanks to Brexit talks|website=Irishtimes.com|accessdate=20 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.irishcentral.com/opinion/others/british-contempt-for-ireland-shows-over-brexit-but-irish-leader-varadkar-has-his-finest-hour|title=Finest hour for Taoiseach Varadkar over Brexit border issue|date=9 December 2017|website=Irishcentral.com|accessdate=20 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2018===\nIn January 2018, his opinion poll approval ratings reached 60%, a ten-year high for any Taoiseach.<ref>{{ cite news |title=Leo Varadkar\u2019s popularity rating grows to Bertie Ahern proportions |author= Loscher, Damian |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/leo-varadkar-s-popularity-rating-grows-to-bertie-ahern-proportions-1.3367359|newspaper=Irish Times |date=25 January 2018 |accessdate=30 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2018, he announced that the [[Thirty-sixth Amendment of the Constitution Bill 2018 (Ireland)|referendum]] to repeal Ireland's [[Eighth Amendment of the Constitution of Ireland|8th Amendment]] which prevented any liberalisation of restrictive abortion laws would take place in May. If passed, it would allow the government to introduce new legislation. It was proposed that women would be allowed unrestricted access to abortion up until 12 weeks, with exceptions if the mother's life is in danger up until six months. Varadkar said he would campaign for liberalising the laws, saying his mind was changed by difficult cases during his tenure as [[Minister for Health (Ireland)|Minister for Health]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Leo Varadkar reveals abortion referendum will be held in May |last1= Murray |first1= Shona |last2= Doyle |first2= Kevin |url=https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/politics/leo-varadkar-reveals-abortion-referendum-will-be-held-in-may-36543756.html |work=Independent.ie |date=29 January 2018 |accessdate=30 January 2018|quote=\u201cAs minister for health I became convinced that abortion had no place in the constitution\u201d said Mr Varadkar. Of the most compelling cases was that of \u201cMiss Y\u201d a migrant woman was turned away from an English port when she went to the UK for an abortion. \u201cShe went on hunger strike and became suicidal\u201d said the Taoiseach.}}</ref> The referendum was passed by a 2:1 majority.\n\n===2019===\n[[File:President Trump Meets with the Taoiseach of Ireland (48012258958).jpg|thumb|Varadkar and [[US President]] [[Donald Trump]] in Shannon, Ireland in June 2019]]\nOn 24 January 2019, Varadkar said in an interview with [[Euronews]] he was standing firm on the [[Irish backstop]] and called Brexit an act of self-harm that was not fully thought through. He also said the technology promised by the Brexiteers to solve the Northern Ireland border issue \"doesn't yet exist\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/leo-varakar-brexit-was-not-fully-thought-through/|title=Leo Varadkar: Brexit was \u2018not fully thought through\u2019|first1=James|last1=R|first2=|last2=erson|date=24 January 2019|website=POLITICO|accessdate=6 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nVaradkar stated he will refuse to ratify the [[European Union\u2013Mercosur free trade agreement|EU\u2013Mercosur free trade agreement]] unless [[Brazil]] commits to protecting the environment.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-49450495|title=Amazon fires: France and Ireland threaten to block EU trade deal|date=23 August 2019|work=[[BBC]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Amazon fires spark European rift at G7 over Mercosur trade deal |url=https://www.dw.com/en/amazon-fires-spark-european-rift-at-g7-over-mercosur-trade-deal/a-50154578 |work=Deutsche Welle |date=24 August 2019}}</ref> The fear is that the deal could lead to more deforestation of the [[Amazon rainforest]] as it expands market access to Brazilian beef.<ref>{{cite web |title=We must not barter the Amazon rainforest for burgers and steaks |url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/commentisfree/2019/jul/02/barter-amazon-rainforest-burgers-steaks-brazil|author=Watts, Jonathan|work=The Guardian | date=2 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n===2020===\n{{redirect|A Ministerial Broadcast by An Taoiseach Leo Varadkar, TD|further details on how COVID-19 impacted the country|2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Republic of Ireland}}\nOn 14 January 2020, Varadkar called for a dissolution of the D\u00e1il, which was granted by President [[Michael D. Higgins]], and scheduled [[2020 Irish general election|the next election]] for 8 February.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://president.ie/en/diary/details/president-signs-warrant-for-the-dissolution-of-the-32nd-dail |title=President signs warrant for the dissolution of the 32nd D\u00e1il |date=14 January 2020 |access-date=22 January 2020 |website=[[President of Ireland]]}}</ref> Fine Gael lost 12 seats in the election, falling to third place behind [[Fianna F\u00e1il]] and [[Sinn F\u00e9in]]. Varadkar ruled out any possibility of a Fine Gael-Sinn F\u00e9in coalition during the election campaign, though a \"grand coalition\" of Fianna F\u00e1il and Fine Gael was floated as a possibility.<ref name=carroll9feb>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/09/sinn-fein-to-try-to-form-ruling-coalition-after-irish-election-success|title=Sinn F\u00e9in to try to form ruling coalition after Irish election success|first=Rory|last=Carroll|work=The Guardian|date=9 February 2020}}</ref> However, on 12 February, Varadkar conceded that Fine Gael had lost the election and that he was very likely to become the next [[Leader of the Opposition (Ireland)|Opposition Leader]]. Varadkar added that Fine Gael was \"willing to step back\" to allow Sinn F\u00e9in, as the winner of the popular vote, to have the first opportunity to form a government.<ref>{{cite web|last=Goodbody|first=Will|url=https://www.rte.ie/news/ireland/2020/0212/1114778-varadkar-election/|title=Varadkar says Sinn F\u00e9in must now build a coalition|website=[[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann|RTE.ie]]|date=12 February 2020|accessdate=12 February 2020}}</ref> On 20 February, Varadkar offered his resignation to President Higgins at [[\u00c1ras an Uachtar\u00e1in]], remaining, however, as Taoiseach in a caretaker capacity until [[2020 Irish government formation|the formation of a new government]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rte.ie/news/politics/2020/0221/1116630-dail-taoiseach/|title=Taoiseach to continue in caretaker capacity amid D\u00e1il deadlock|first=M\u00edche\u00e1l|last=Lehane|date=21 February 2020|accessdate=21 February 2020|website=[[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann|RTE.ie]]}}</ref> \n\nDuring this period, the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Republic of Ireland|COVID-19 pandemic]] arrived in Ireland. While in Washington ahead of [[Saint Patrick's Day]], Varadkar announced measures intended to stop COVID-19 spreading, including the closure of all schools, universities and childcare facilities from the following day, as well as the closure of all cultural institutions and the cancellation of \"all indoor mass gatherings of more than 100 people and outdoor mass gatherings of more than 500 people\".<ref>https://merrionstreet.ie/en/News-Room/News/Statement_by_An_Taoiseach_Leo_Varadkar_On_measures_to_tackle_Covid-19_Washington_12_March_2020.html</ref> After returning home early, Varadkar addressed the nation on Saint Patrick's night during ''A Ministerial Broadcast by An Taoiseach Leo Varadkar, TD'', introducing television viewers to the concept of \"[[Cocooning (behaviour)|cocooning]]\", i.e. \"At a certain point\u2026 we will advise the elderly and people who have a long-term illness to stay at home for several weeks\".<ref>https://www.thejournal.ie/leo-varadkar-white-house-st-patricks-day-5036232-Mar2020/</ref><ref>https://www.independent.ie/world-news/coronavirus/short-us-trip-for-varadkar-as-washington-mayor-declares-state-of-emergency-over-coronavirus-spread-39038043.html</ref><ref>https://merrionstreet.ie/en/News-Room/Speeches/Address_by_An_Taoiseach_Leo_Varadkar_17th_March.html</ref> The speech was the most watched television event in Irish history, surpassing the previous record held by ''[[The Late Late Toy Show]]'' by an additional total of about 25% and was widely distributed globally.<ref>https://www.independent.ie/entertainment/television/tv-news/leos-speech-sets-new-tv-record-as-16-million-tune-in-39057364.html</ref><ref>https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/politics/behind-the-lines-the-who-how-and-why-that-created-leo-varadkars-historic-speech-39057126.html</ref> It was also plagiarised by [[Peter Bellew]], the chief operating officer at British low-cost airline group [[EasyJet]].<ref>https://www.theguardian.com/business/2020/mar/21/easyjet-sorry-as-staff-motivation-video-copies-leo-varadkar</ref>\n\nIn response to a March 2020 [[Health Service Executive]] appeal to healthcare professionals, Varadkar rejoined the medical register and offered to work as a doctor one day each week.<ref name=\"guardian-5apr2020\">{{cite news |last1=Carroll |first1=Rory |title=Irish taoiseach Leo Varadkar to work a day a week as a doctor |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/05/irish-taoiseach-leo-varadkar-to-work-a-day-a-week-as-a-doctor |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nVaradkar is the first Irish government leader of Indian origin and has visited India on a number of occasions. He completed his medical internship at [[King Edward Memorial Hospital and Seth Gordhandas Sunderdas Medical College|KEM Hospital]] in his father's childhood city of [[Mumbai]].\n\nDuring an interview on [[RT\u00c9 Radio]] on 18 January 2015 (his 36th birthday), Varadkar spoke publicly for the first time about being gay: \"it's not something that defines me. I'm not a half-Indian politician, or a doctor politician or a gay politician for that matter. It's just part of who I am, it doesn't define me, it is part of my character I suppose\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/leo-varadkar-i-am-a-gay-man-minister-says-1.2070189|title=Leo Varadkar: 'I am a gay man', Minister says|work=The Irish Times|date=18 January 2015|accessdate=18 January 2015}}</ref> Varadkar was a prominent advocate of the [[Thirty-fourth Amendment of the Constitution of Ireland|same-sex marriage referendum]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/leo-varadkar-i-wanted-to-be-an-equal-citizen-and-today-i-am-1.2223688|title=Leo Varadkar: 'I wanted to be an equal citizen . . . and today I am'|work=The Irish Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.independent.ie/irish-news/referendum/10-factors-behind-the-yes-sides-victory-31247192.html|title=10 factors behind the 'Yes' side's victory|author=Nial O'Connor|work=The Irish Independent|date=23 May 2015}}</ref> His partner, Matthew Barrett, is a doctor at [[Mater Misericordiae University Hospital]].<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.independent.ie/irish-news/meet-the-dashing-doctor-boyfriend-supporting-leo-varadkar-in-his-fine-gael-leadership-bid-35469585.html | accessdate = 29 May 2017 | date = 21 February 2017 | work = The Independent | title = Meet the dashing doctor boyfriend supporting Leo Varadkar in his Fine Gael leadership bid }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | work = The Irish Times | url = https://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/fine-gael-leadership-race-leo-varadkar-1.3086625 | accessdate = 29 May 2017 | title = Fine Gael leadership race: Leo Varadkar | date= 17 May 2017 | first = Sarah | last = Barton}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2019, to mark the [[Stonewall 50 \u2013 WorldPride NYC 2019|50th anniversary]] of the [[Stonewall riots]], an event widely considered a watershed moment in the modern [[LGBT rights movement|LGBTQ rights movement]], ''[[Queerty]]'' named him one of the ''Pride50'' \"trailblazing individuals who actively ensure society remains moving towards [[LGBT equality|equality]], acceptance and dignity for all [[queer]] people\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.queerty.com/pride50|title=Queerty Pride50 2019 Honorees|website=Queerty|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-18}}</ref>\n\nVaradkar completed a course in professional Irish, and devised an [[Irish language]] form for his surname, Leo de Varad.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/heritage/maith-an-fear-taoiseach-awarded-certificate-for-irish-language-course-1.3214781?mode=amp|title=Maith an fear: Taoiseach awarded certificate for Irish language course|website=www.irishtimes.com|access-date=2019-06-15}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of LGBT heads of government]]\n\n==Notes==\n<references group=\"nb\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commonscat}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*{{Official website|leovaradkar.ie}}\n*[http://www.finegael.ie/our-people/ministers/leo-varadkar/ Leo Varadkar's page on the Fine Gael website]\n\n{{s-start}} \n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[Pat Carey]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Minister for Transport, Tourism and Sport]]\n       |years  = 2011\u20132014}}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[Paschal Donohoe]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before = [[James Reilly (Irish politician)|James Reilly]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Minister for Health (Ireland)|Minister for Health]]\n       |years  = 2014\u20132016}}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[Simon Harris (politician)|Simon Harris]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before = [[Joan Burton]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Minister for Employment Affairs and Social Protection|Minister for Social Protection]]\n       |years  = 2016\u20132017}}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[Regina Doherty]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before = [[Enda Kenny]]|rows = 2}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Taoiseach]]\n       |years  = 2017\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc|rows   = 2}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Minister for Defence (Ireland)|Minister for Defence]]\n       |years  = 2017\u2013present}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[Enda Kenny]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Leader of Fine Gael]]\n       |years  = 2017\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Navboxes|title=Leo Varadkar navigational boxes|list1=\n{{Heads of government of Ireland}}\n{{European Council}}\n{{Current Government of Ireland}}\n{{Current TDs}}\n{{29th Government of Ireland}}\n{{30th Government of Ireland}}\n{{Ministers for Health of Ireland}}\n{{Ministers for Transport of Ireland}}\n{{Ministers for Social Affairs of Ireland}}\n{{Ministers for Defence of Ireland}}\n{{Fine Gael}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Varadkar, Leo}}\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Trinity College Dublin]]\n[[Category:Fine Gael TDs]]\n[[Category:Gay politicians]]\n[[Category:Irish people of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:LGBT conservatism]]\n[[Category:LGBT heads of government]]\n[[Category:LGBT history in Ireland]]\n[[Category:LGBT legislators]]\n[[Category:LGBT politicians from Ireland]]\n[[Category:LGBT rights activists from Ireland]]\n[[Category:Local councillors in Fingal]]\n[[Category:Members of the 30th D\u00e1il]]\n[[Category:Members of the 31st D\u00e1il]]\n[[Category:Members of the 32nd D\u00e1il]]\n[[Category:Members of the 33rd D\u00e1il]]\n[[Category:Ministers for Defence (Ireland)]]\n[[Category:Ministers for Health (Ireland)]]\n[[Category:Ministers for Social Affairs (Ireland)]]\n[[Category:Ministers for Transport (Ireland)]]\n[[Category:People educated at The King's Hospital]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Fingal]]\n[[Category:Politicians of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:Taoisigh]]\n[[Category:21st-century Irish medical doctors]]\n[[Category:Young Fine Gael]]\n", "name_user": "Saharawiki", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly life:Edit for writing quality only -- not content~~~~~", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leo_Varadkar"}
{"title_page": "Donetsk", "text_new": "{{Redirect|Stalino}}\n{{about|the city in eastern Ukraine|other uses}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2014}}\n\n{{Infobox settlement\n|name                   = \n|official_name          = Donetsk\n|native_name            = {{lang|uk|\u0414\u043e\u043d\u0435\u0446\u044c\u043a}}\n|other_name             = {{lang-ru|\u0414\u043e\u043d\u0435\u0446\u043a}}\n|translit_lang1= [[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]] \n|translit_lang1_type1= [[Romanization of Ukrainian|Romanization]] \n|translit_lang1_info1= Donetsk\n|translit_lang1_type2= [[Scientific transliteration of Cyrillic|Scholarly]] \n|translit_lang1_info2= Doneck\n|settlement_type        = [[City of regional significance (Ukraine)|City of regional significance]]\n|image_skyline          = Donetsk montage (2015).png\n|image_caption          = Counter-clockwise: Cathedral Transfiguration of Jesus (big image), [[Donbass Palace]], [[Donetsk National Academic Ukrainian Musical and Drama Theatre|Drama Theatre]], Lenin Square, bridge on Ilicha Prospect, [[Donetsk State Academic Opera and Ballet Theatre named after A. Solovyanenko|Opera Theatre]]\n|image_flag             = Flag of Donetsk.svg\n|image_shield           = Greater Coat of Arms of Donetsk (1995).svg\n|shield_size            = 110px\n|pushpin_map            = Ukraine Donetsk Oblast#Ukraine#Europe\n|pushpin_relief=1\n|coordinates            = {{coord|48|00|10|N|37|48|19|E|region:UA|display= inline,title}}\n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = {{Flag|Ukraine}}\n|subdivision_type1      = [[International recognition of Donetsk and Luhansk|Claimed by]]\n|subdivision_name1      = {{flag|Donetsk People's Republic}}\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Administrative division of Ukraine|Oblast]]\n|subdivision_name2      = {{flag| Donetsk Oblast}}\n|subdivision_type3      = [[City of regional significance (Ukraine)|Municipality]]\n|subdivision_name3      = [[File:Flag of Donetsk.svg|22px|border]] Donetsk City\n|established_title      = Founded\n|established_date       = 1869{{ref|1}}\n|established_title2     = City rights\n|established_date2      = 1917\n|established_title3     = Capital of Donetsk People's Republic\n|established_date3      = 2014\n|parts_type             = [[#Government and administrative divisions|Raions]]\n|parts_style            = list\n|parts                  = List of 9\n|p1                     = [[Budionny Raion]]\n|leader_title           = Mayor (Holova)\n|leader_name            = [[Aleksej Kulezmin]]{{efn|group=1|Due to the [[War in Donbass]], Lukyanchenko was forced to move to Kiev.}}\n|area_total_km2         = 358\n|elevation_m            = 169\n|population_total       = 929063\n|population_as_of       = 1 January 2016\n|population_density_km2 = auto\n|population_metro       = 2,009,700{{ref|2}}\n|postal_code_type       = Postal code\n|postal_code            = 83000 \u2014 83497\n|area_code              = +380 622, 623\n|website                =\n|footnotes              = {{note|1}}Donetsk was founded in 1869 as a workers' settlement ''Yuzovka'' around the metallurgical factory of the Welshman John Hughes. The settlement was established in lands of Yevdokim Shydlovsky, who received them upon destruction of the [[Zaporizhian Sich]] in 1775.<br />{{note|2}}The population of the metropolitan area is from 2004.\n|p2                     = [[Voroshylov Raion]]\n|p3                     = [[Kalinin Raion, Donetsk|Kalinin Raion]]\n|p4                     = [[Kiev Raion]]\n|p5                     = [[Kirov Raion, Donetsk|Kirov Raion]]\n|p6                     = [[Kuibyshev Raion]]\n|p7                     = [[Lenin Raion, Donetsk|Lenin Raion]]\n|p8                     = [[Petrovskyi Raion]]\n|p9                     = [[Proletarian Raion]]\n|timezone               = EET\n|utc_offset             = +2\n|timezone_DST           = EET\n|utc_offset_DST         = +3\n|blank_name             = [[Licence plate]]\n|blank_info             = \u0410\u041d\n|blank1_name            = [[Town twinning|Sister cities]]\n|blank1_info            = <small>[[Bochum]], [[Charleroi]], [[Kutaisi]], [[Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania|Pittsburgh]], [[Sheffield]], [[Taranto]], [[Moscow]], [[Vilnius]]</small>\n|blank2_name            = [[K\u00f6ppen climate classification|Climate]]\n|blank2_info            = [[Cool-summer humid continental climate|Dfb]]\n}}\n'''Donetsk''' ({{IPAc-en|UK|d|\u0252|\u02c8|n|j|\u025b|t|s|k}} {{respell|don|YETSK}},<ref>{{Cite Oxford\u00a0Dictionaries|Donetsk|accessdate=5 September 2019}}</ref> {{IPAc-en|US|d|\u0259|\u02c8|n|(|j|)|\u025b|t|s|k}} {{respell|d\u0259|N(Y)ETSK}};<ref>{{Cite American Heritage Dictionary|Donetsk|accessdate=5 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite Merriam-Webster|Donetsk|accessdate=5 September 2019}}</ref> {{lang-uk|\u0414\u043e\u043d\u0435\u0446\u044c\u043a}} {{IPA-uk|do\u02c8n\u025bts\u02b2k||uk-\u0414\u043e\u043d\u0435\u0446\u044c\u043a.ogg}}; {{lang-ru|\u0414\u043e\u043d\u0435\u0446\u043a}} {{IPA-ru|d\u0250\u02c8n\u02b2etsk|}}), formerly known as '''Aleksandrovka''', '''Hughesovka''', '''Yuzovka''', '''Stalin''' and '''Stalino''' (<small>see also: [[Names of European cities in different languages: C-D#D|cities' alternative names]]</small>), is an industrial city in Eastern [[Ukraine]] and the capital city of the unrecognized [[Donetsk People's Republic]], located on the [[Kalmius]] River. The population was estimated at {{Ua-pop-est2016|929,063}} in the city core, with over 2,000,000 in the [[metropolitan area]] (2011). According to the [[Ukrainian Census (2001)|2001 Ukrainian Census]], Donetsk was the fifth-largest city in Ukraine.<ref name=\"ukrcensus1\">{{cite web |title= Results / General results of the census / Number of cities |work= [[Ukrainian Census (2001)|2001 Ukrainian Census]] |url= http://www.ukrcensus.gov.ua/eng/results/general/city/ |accessdate = 28 August 2006 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20060109012020/http://ukrcensus.gov.ua/eng/results/general/city/ |archivedate= 9 January 2006}}</ref>\n\nAdministratively, Donetsk has been the centre of [[Donetsk Oblast]], while historically, it is the unofficial capital and largest city of the larger economic and cultural [[Donets Basin]] (''Donbass'') region. Donetsk is adjacent to another major city, [[Makiivka]], and along with other surrounding cities forms a major [[urban sprawl]] and [[conurbation]] in the region. Donetsk has been a major economic, industrial and scientific centre of Ukraine with a high concentration of heavy industries and a skilled workforce. The density of heavy industries (predominantly steel production, chemical industry, and coal mining) determined the city's challenging ecological situation. In 2012 a UN report ranked Donetsk among the world's fastest depopulating cities.<ref>[https://www.businessinsider.com/cities-that-are-shrinking-2012-10?r=US&IR=T The 28 Fastest-Shrinking Cities In The World]</ref>\n\nThe original settlement in the south of the European part of the [[Russian Empire]] was first mentioned as '''Aleksandrovka''' in 1779, during the reign of the Empress [[Catherine the Great]]. In 1869 the Welsh businessman [[John Hughes (businessman)|John Hughes]] founded a steel plant and several [[coal mining|coal mines]] in the region, and the town was named '''Hughesovka''' or '''Yuzovka''' (\u042e\u0437\u043e\u0432\u043a\u0430) in recognition of his role (\"Yuz\" being a Russian-language approximation of ''Hughes''). During [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] times, the city's steel industry expanded. In 1924 Yuzovka was renamed '''Stalin'''. In 1929 Stalin was renamed '''Stalino''', and in 1932 the city became the centre of the Donetsk region. Renamed '''Donetsk''' in 1961, the city today remains a centre for [[coal mining]] and for the [[steel industry]].\n\nSince April 2014 Donetsk and its surrounding areas have been one of the major sites of fighting in the ongoing [[War in Donbass|Donbass War]], as pro-Russian separatist forces battle against Ukrainian military forces for control of the city and surrounding areas. Throughout the war, the city of Donetsk has been administered by the pro-Russian separatist forces as the center of the [[Donetsk People's Republic]] (DPR), with outlying territories of the Donetsk region divided between the two sides.<ref>{{cite news |last1= Weaver |first1= Matthew |last2= Luhn |first2= Alec |date= 13 February 2015 |title= Ukraine ceasefire deal agreed at Minsk talks |publisher= The Guardian |url= https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/feb/12/ukraine-crisis-reports-emerge-of-agreement-in-minsk-talks |accessdate= 16 December 2016}}</ref> [[Donetsk International Airport]] became the epicenter of the war with almost a year-long battle leading to massive casualties among civilians and a total ruination of the northeastern neighborhoods of the city.\n\n<!-- On June 27, 2014, the [[List of states with limited recognition| unrecognized nation]] of [[South Ossetia]] officially recognized the independence of the [[Donetsk People's Republic]] (DPR) from Ukraine.<ref>{{cite news |last1= News |first1= Tass |date= 27 June 2014 |title= South Ossetia recognizes independence of Donetsk People's Republic |publisher=TASS |url= http://tass.com/world/738110 |accessdate= 12 December 2017}}</ref>\n -->\n{{As of|2019|September}} the DPR has full control of the city, with Ukrainian and DPR forces still engaging in combat outside of the city.\n\n== History ==\n\n===Foundation===\n[[File:\u0428\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0430 \u0434\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0439 \u0430\u043d\u0433\u043b\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0430\u0434\u043c\u0438\u043d\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438 \u042e\u041c\u0417 004.jpg|thumb|left|This building was formerly an English-speaking school for the British in Yuzovka]]\n[[File:1887. \u041d\u043e\u0432\u044b\u0439 \u0441\u0432\u0435\u0442. \u0411\u0430\u0437\u0430\u0440.jpg|thumb|left|A market on the main street of ''Novyi Svet'' section of Yuzovka. (1887)]]\nThe city was founded in 1869 when the [[Wales|Welsh]] businessman [[John Hughes (businessman)|John Hughes]] built a steel plant and several coal mines at ''Aleksandrovka'', in the south of the European part of [[Russian Empire|Russia]]. It was initially named ''Hughesovka'' ({{lang-ru|\u042e\u0437\u043e\u0432\u043a\u0430}}).<ref>''Yuz'' is a Russian or Ukrainian approximation of Hughes</ref> In its early period, it received immigrants from Wales, especially from the town of [[Merthyr Tydfil]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Evans |first=Martin |date=June 11, 2012 |title=Euro 2012: Donetsk's roots have more in common with Merthyr Tydfil than Moscow |publisher=Telegraph  |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/competitions/euro-2012/9323465/Euro-2012-Donetsks-roots-have-more-in-common-with-Merthyr-Tydfil-than-Moscow.html |accessdate=2014-08-09}}</ref> By the beginning of the 20th century, Yuzovka had approximately 50,000 inhabitants,<ref>The population included mostly migrants from neighbouring Russian territories</ref> and attained the status of a city in 1917.<ref name=\"lukianchenko\">{{cite web |date=31 August 2004 |df=dmy |script-title=ru:\u0418\u0437 \u0438\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0438 \u0433\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0430 |language=Russian |trans-title=From the history of the city |work=Official site of the Head of Donetsk City |url=http://lukyanchenko.dn.ua/today/view.php?cat=7&subcat=7&type=1 |accessdate=7 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070127190501/http://lukyanchenko.dn.ua/today/view.php?cat=7&subcat=7&type=1 |archivedate=27 January 2007}}</ref> The main district of \"Hughezovka\" is named English Colony, and the British origin of the city is reflected in its layout and architecture.\n\n===Soviet Union===\n[[File:\u0414\u0435\u043d\u044c \u041f\u043e\u0431\u0435\u0434\u044b \u0432 \u0414\u043e\u043d\u0435\u0446\u043a\u0435, 2010 036.JPG|thumb|left|A Monument for the Liberators of Donbass, dedicated to the soldier liberating [[Donbass]] from the Nazis during [[Eastern Front (World War II)|World War II]].]]\nAfter the [[Russian Civil War]] broke out, Yuzovka was part of the [[Donets-Krivoy Rog Soviet Republic]] from its declaration of independence on 12 February 1918. The Republic was disbanded at the 2nd All-Ukrainian Congress of Soviets on 20 March 1918 when the independence of the [[Ukrainian Soviet Republic]] was declared. It failed to achieve recognition, either internationally or by the [[Russian SFSR]], and in accordance with the [[Treaty of Brest-Litovsk]] was abolished.\n\nIn 1924, under [[Soviet era|Soviet rule]], the city's name was changed to ''Stalin''. In that year, the city's population totaled 63,708, and in the next year, 80,085. In 1929\u201331 the city's name was changed to ''Stalino''.<ref name=\"alldonetsk.info\">http://alldonetsk.info/en/history-city-donetsk The history of the city of Donetsk</ref> The city did not have a drinking water system until 1931, when a {{convert|55.3|km|1|abbr=on}} system was laid underground. In July 1933, the city became the administrative center of the [[Donetsian Oblast]] of the [[Ukrainian SSR]].<ref name=\"lukianchenko\" /> In 1933, the first {{convert|12|km|0|abbr=on}} sewer system was installed, and next year the first exploitation of gas was conducted within the city. In addition, some sources{{Which|date=March 2012}} state that the city was briefly called Trotsk\u2014after [[Leon Trotsky]]\u2014for a few months in late 1923.\n[[File:Stadtplan Stalino LOC 2012593213.jpg|thumb|A German map of the city in 1943, note that all the streets have been given German names.]]\nAt the beginning of [[World War II]], the population of Stalino consisted of 507,000, and after the war, only 175,000. The [[Nazi Germany|German]] [[Operation Barbarossa|invasion]] during World War II almost completely destroyed the city, which was mostly rebuilt on a large scale at the war's end. It was occupied by German and Italian forces as part of the [[Reichskommissariat Ukraine]] between 16 October 1941 and 5 September 1943.\n\nIn 1945, young men and women aged 17 to 35, from the [[Danube Swabians|Danube Swabian ''(Schwowe)'']] communities of [[Yugoslavia]], [[Hungary]] and [[Romania]] (the [[Batschka]] and [[Banat]]), were forcibly sent to Russia as Allied \"war reparations\", being put to work as slave labour to rebuild Stalino and to work in its mines. The conditions were so poor that many died from disease and malnutrition.<ref>{{cite web |title=Das politische Bewusstsein |url=http://www.hog-kernei.de/PDF/Internierung%20und%20Vertreibung.pdf |accessdate=2013-03-26}}</ref>\n\nDuring [[Nikita Khrushchev]]'s second wave of [[destalinization]] in November 1961, the city was renamed Donetsk, after the [[Seversky Donets]] River, a tributary of the [[Don (Russia)|Don]]<ref name=\"lukianchenko\" /> in order to distance it from the former leader [[Joseph Stalin]].\n\nIn 1965, the Donetsk Academy of Sciences was established as part of the [[National Academy of Science of Ukraine|Academy of Science of the Ukrainian SSR]].\n\n===Independent Ukraine===\nAfter experiencing a tough time in the 1990s, when it was the center of gang wars for control over industrial enterprises, Donetsk modernised quickly, largely under the influence of big companies.\n\nIn 1994 a referendum took place in the [[Donetsk Oblast]] and the [[Luhansk Oblast]], with around 90% supporting the [[Russian language in Ukraine|Russian language]] gaining status of an official language alongside [[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]], and for the [[Russian language]] to be an official language on a regional level; however, the referendum was annulled by the [[Kiev]] government.<ref>{{cite news|last=Morin |first=Yevgenii |url=http://thekievtimes.ua/society/372400-donbass-zabytyj-referendum-1994.html |script-title=ru:\u0414\u043e\u043d\u0431\u0430\u0441\u0441: \u0437\u0430\u0431\u044b\u0442\u044b\u0439 \u0440\u0435\u0444\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043d\u0434\u0443\u043c-1994 |trans-title=Donbass: the forgotten 1994 referendum |language=ru |newspaper=The Kiev Times |date=12 May 2014 |accessdate=14 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nakanune.ru/articles/18807/ |script-title=ru:\u041a\u0438\u0435\u0432 \u0443\u0436\u0435 20 \u043b\u0435\u0442 \u043e\u0431\u043c\u0430\u043d\u044b\u0432\u0430\u0435\u0442 \u0414\u043e\u043d\u0431\u0430\u0441\u0441: \u0414\u043e\u043d\u0435\u0446\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0438 \u041b\u0443\u0433\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u0435\u0449\u0435 \u0432 1994 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0443 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0433\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0441\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043b\u0438 \u0437\u0430 \u0444\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043b\u0438\u0437\u0430\u0446\u0438\u044e, \u0440\u0443\u0441\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u044f\u0437\u044b\u043a \u0438 \u0435\u0432\u0440\u0430\u0437\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0443\u044e \u0438\u043d\u0442\u0435\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u044e |trans-title=Kiev has been cheating Donbass for 20 years: in 1994 the Donetsk and Lugansk regions voted in favour of federalisation, the Russian language, and Eurasian integration |language=ru |publisher=Nakanune.ru |date=26 March 2014 |accessdate=14 December 2016}}</ref>{{Unreliable source?|reason=This is a Russian blog/forum, and is user generated per [[WP:SELFPUBLISH]]. |date=December 2016}}\n\nIn the 1990s and the 2000s coal mine collapses took place in Donetsk and the region, taking the lives of hundreds; those included the [[2008 Ukraine coal mine collapse]], the [[2007 Zasyadko mine disaster]], and the [[2015 Zasyadko mine disaster]]. Ukraine has had a series of mining accidents since the collapse of the Soviet Union in 1991, and one reason being given is the linking of miners' pay to production, which serves as an incentive to ignore safety procedures that would slow production.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/7103086.stm|title=Ukraine's mine death toll rises|newspaper=[[BBC News]]|date=20 November 2007|accessdate=14 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn a summit in [[Moscow]] in 2008, Donetsk was recognised as the best city in the [[Commonwealth of Independent States]] for its implemented development strategies;<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.utro.ua/ru/zhizn/donetsk_priznan_luchshim_gorodom_sng_4a07e7a7c5ef7 |script-title=ru:\u0414\u043e\u043d\u0435\u0446\u043a \u043f\u0440\u0438\u0437\u043d\u0430\u043d \u043b\u0443\u0447\u0448\u0438\u043c \u0433\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043e\u043c \u0421\u041d\u0413 |trans-title=Donetsk named best city of the CIS |language=ru |publisher=Utro.ua |date=8 April 2008 |accessdate=14 December 2016}}</ref> in 2012 and 2013 Donetsk was recognised as the best place for business in [[Ukraine]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://lb.ua/economics/2013/06/27/209344_donetsk_priznali_luchshim_gorodom.html|script-title=ru:\u0414\u043e\u043d\u0435\u0446\u043a \u043f\u0440\u0438\u0437\u043d\u0430\u043b\u0438 \u043b\u0443\u0447\u0448\u0438\u043c \u0433\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043e\u043c \u0434\u043b\u044f \u0432\u0435\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u0431\u0438\u0437\u043d\u0435\u0441\u0430|trans-title=Donetsk recognised as the best city for conducting business|language=ru|publisher=Lb.ua|date=27 June 2013|accessdate=14 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://gazeta.ua/ru/articles/economics/_doneck-vtoroj-god-podryad-priznayut-samym-privlekatelnym-v-ukraine-dlya-biznesa/508042|script-title=ru:\u0414\u043e\u043d\u0435\u0446\u043a \u0432\u0442\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0439 \u0433\u043e\u0434 \u043f\u043e\u0434\u0440\u044f\u0434 \u043f\u0440\u0438\u0437\u043d\u0430\u044e\u0442 \u0441\u0430\u043c\u044b\u043c \u043f\u0440\u0438\u0432\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u043c \u0432 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0438\u043d\u0435 \u0434\u043b\u044f \u0431\u0438\u0437\u043d\u0435\u0441\u0430|trans-title=Donetsk recognised as the most attractive for business in Ukraine for the second consecutive year|language=ru|publisher=Gazeta.ua|date=22 July 2013|accessdate=14 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.epravda.com.ua/rus/news/2013/07/22/386434/|script-title=ru:\u0414\u043e\u043d\u0435\u0446\u043a \u043f\u0440\u0438\u0437\u043d\u0430\u043b\u0438 \u0441\u0430\u043c\u044b\u043c \u043f\u0440\u0438\u0432\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u043c \u0433\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043e\u043c \u0434\u043b\u044f \u0431\u0438\u0437\u043d\u0435\u0441\u0430 - Forbes|trans-title=Donetsk recognised as the most attractive city for business - Forbes |language=ru|publisher=Epravda.com.ua|date=22 July 2013|accessdate=14 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nWhilst getting praise for its business potential, Donetsk also received criticism for the strong mafia connection of its business magnates, and for the increasing poverty rate (alongside a growing number of oligarchs).<ref>{{cite web|first=Natalia|last=Kommodova|url=http://www.ostro.org/donetsk/society/articles/67015/|script-title=ru:'\u0411\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0448\u0438\u0435 \u0441\u0434\u0432\u0438\u0433\u0438' \u0414\u043e\u043d\u0431\u0430\u0441\u0441\u0430, \u0431\u043e\u0433\u0430\u0442\u044b\u0435 \u043b\u0435\u0442\u0447\u0438\u043a\u0438 \u0438 \u0431\u0435\u0434\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u0432\u0443\u043d\u0434\u0435\u0440\u043a\u0438\u043d\u0434\u044b - \u041e\u0431\u0437\u043e\u0440 \u0434\u043e\u043d\u0435\u0446\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0441\u0441\u044b|trans-title='Great shifts' of Donbass, rich high fliers and poor wunderkind - Overview by the Donetsk Press|language=ru|publisher=Ostro.org|date=4 August 2009|accessdate=14 December 2016}}</ref> Some analysts warned of a long-term collapse of the Donetsk economy, and that it could share [[Detroit]]'s gloomy fate, due to its failure to combat crime and poverty<ref>{{cite web|url=http://makeevkainfo.com.ua/content/pochemu-doneck-zhdet-sudba-detroyta|script-title=ru:\u041f\u043e\u0447\u0435\u043c\u0443 \u0414\u043e\u043d\u0435\u0446\u043a \u0436\u0434\u0435\u0442 \u0441\u0443\u0434\u044c\u0431\u0430 \u0414\u0435\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0439\u0442\u0430|trans-title=Why Donetsk awaits the fate of Detroit|language=ru|publisher=Makeevkainfo.com.ua|date=24 June 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140703220200/http://makeevkainfo.com.ua/content/pochemu-doneck-zhdet-sudba-detroyta|archivedate=3 July 2014}}</ref>{{Better source|reason=User generated site, with the author being 'a passer by'. Needs a reliable source.|date=December 2016}}\n\n===Euromaidan, War in Donbass, and Capital of the Donetsk People's Republic (2014-present)===\n[[File:2014-05-11. \u0420\u0435\u0444\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043d\u0434\u0443\u043c \u0432 \u0414\u043e\u043d\u0435\u0446\u043a\u0435 017.jpg|thumb|left|[[2014 Donetsk and Luhansk status referendums|Referendum]] organized by the rebels. A line to enter a polling place, 11 May 2014]]\n[[File:1 \u043c\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0430 2014 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430 \u0432 \u0414\u043e\u043d\u0435\u0446\u043a\u0435. \u0423 \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0441\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0430 \u043f\u043e\u0434\u043d\u0438\u043c\u0430\u044e\u0442 \u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0444\u043b\u0430\u0433.ogv|thumb|left|Russian flag being raised in Donetsk, 1 March 2014]]\nAfter President Yanukovych abandoned Ukraine for Russia, Russian-backed defenders took over the main government building in Donetsk. The police did not offer resistance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gazeta.ua/ru/articles/politics/_v-donecke-neskolko-soten-radikalov-s-krikami-rossiya-shturmuyut-oga/545225 |title=\u0412 \u0414\u043e\u043d\u0435\u0446\u043a\u0435 \u043d\u0435\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043b\u044c\u043a\u043e \u0441\u043e\u0442\u0435\u043d \u0440\u0430\u0434\u0438\u043a\u0430\u043b\u043e\u0432 \u0441 \u043a\u0440\u0438\u043a\u0430\u043c\u0438 \"\u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u044f\" \u0448\u0442\u0443\u0440\u043c\u0443\u044e\u0442 \u041e\u0413\u0410 |publisher=Gazeta.ua |date= |accessdate=3 March 2014}}</ref> Later in the week the authorities of Donetsk denounced a referendum on the status of the region<ref>{{cite web|url=http://novosti.dn.ua/details/219796/ |title=\u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u0414\u043e\u043d\u0431\u0430\u0441\u0441\u0430 :: The authorities of Donetsk region don't want a referendum and they opposed 'foreign scenarios' \u2013 video report |publisher=Novosti.dn.ua |date=9 March 2014|accessdate=9 August 2014}}</ref> and the police retook the Donetsk Oblast administrative building.<ref>{{cite news|first=Lina|last=Kushch|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/03/06/us-ukraine-crisis-donetsk-idUSBREA250CW20140306|title=Ukrainian flag again flies over Donetsk regional HQ|agency=[[Reuters]]|date=6 March 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140307113744/https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/03/06/us-ukraine-crisis-donetsk-idUSBREA250CW20140306|archivedate=7 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Andrew|last=Roth|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/03/08/world/europe/ukrainian-officials-in-east-move-to-blunt-pro-russia-forces.html?hpw&rref=world&_r=0|title=Ukrainian Officials in East Act to Blunt Pro-Russian Forces|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=7 March 2014|accessdate=16 December 2016|url-access=subscription }}</ref> Donetsk became one of the centers of the [[2014 pro-Russian conflict in Ukraine]].\n\nOn 7 April 2014, pro-Russian activists seized control of Donetsk's government building and declared the \"[[Donetsk People's Republic]]\",<ref>{{cite video|title=Russian Roulette: The Invasion of Ukraine (Dispatch Twenty Three) |date=Apr 11, 2014 |publisher=VICE News |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FpdCvuf-ZOk }}</ref> asking for Russian intervention.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/international/world/donetsk-proclaims-independence-from-ukraine/article5883598.ece|title=Donetsk proclaims independence from Ukraine|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|date=7 April 2014|accessdate=7 April 2014|last=Radyuhin|first=Vladimir|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140408214831/http://www.thehindu.com/news/international/world/donetsk-proclaims-independence-from-ukraine/article5883598.ece|archivedate=8 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 May 2014, a Donetsk status referendum, 2014 was held in Donetsk in which voters could choose political independence. It was stated by the head of the self-proclaimed Donetsk People's Republic election commission, Roman Lyagin, that almost 90 percent of those who voted in the Donetsk Region endorsed political independence from [[Kiev|Kyiv]]. Ukraine does not recognize the [[referendum]], while the EU and US stated that the polls were illegal.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-27369500|title = Ukraine crisis: Eastern rebels claim 'self-rule' poll victory|date = 12 May 2014|accessdate = 12 May 2014|website = BBC News|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n\nHeavy [[Shell (projectile)|shelling]] by the [[Ukrainian Ground Forces|Ukrainian Army]] and paramilitary units have caused civilian fatalities in Donetsk.<ref>\"[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-28788945 Ukraine crisis: Shells hit Donetsk amid Russia convoy row]\". [[BBC News]]. August 14, 2014.</ref><ref>\"[http://www.euronews.com/2014/08/12/kyiv-s-troops-surround-separatist-stronghold-donetsk-civilian-casualties-high/  Kyiv's troops surround [[Separatism|separatist]] stronghold Donetsk, civilian casualties high]\". [[Euronews]]. August 12, 2014.</ref><ref>\"[http://rt.com/news/180260-killed-civilians-lugansk-ukraine/ 3 days in Donetsk: 70+ civilians killed, over 100 wounded]\". [[RT (TV network)|RT]]. August 14, 2014.</ref> [[Human Rights Watch]] has called on both warring factions to cease using [[BM-21 Grad]] in populated areas, and has said the use of these weapons systems may be a violation of international humanitarian laws and could constitute war crimes.<ref>\"[https://www.hrw.org/news/2014/07/24/ukraine-unguided-rockets-killing-civilians Ukraine: Unguided Rockets Killing Civilians Stop Use of Grads in Populated Areas]\". [[Human Rights Watch]]. July 24, 2014.</ref>\n\nThe [[2015 IIHF World Championship Division I]], Group A was scheduled for 18 to 24 April 2015 in Donetsk, but Ukraine withdrew as hosts due to the ongoing conflict in the country.<ref>{{cite web |author1=Steven Ellis |title=Ukraine Withdraws as Hosts of 2015 Division IA World Championships |url=http://thehockeyhouse.net/international-hockey/ukraine-withdraws-as-hosts-of-2015-division-ia-world-championships/ |website=The Hockey House |date=15 August 2014 |access-date=23 August 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140819085434/http://thehockeyhouse.net/international-hockey/ukraine-withdraws-as-hosts-of-2015-division-ia-world-championships/ |archive-date=19 August 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Instead of Donetsk, the tournament was organized in [[Krak\u00f3w]], [[Poland]]. Eventually, Ukraine co-organized [[2017 IIHF World Championship Division I]], again Group A, but in its capital, [[Kiev]].\n\n== Geography ==\n[[File:Kalmius 01.jpg|thumb|left|The [[spoil tip]]s near the [[Kalmius]]. In the background is the Chervonohvardiyskyi [[raion]] of [[Makiivka]]]]\n\nDonetsk lies in the [[steppe]] landscape, surrounded by scattered [[wood]]land, hills, [[spoil tip]]s, [[river]]s and [[lake]]s. The northern outskirts are mainly used for agriculture. The [[Kalmius River]] links the city with the [[Sea of Azov]], which is {{convert|95|km|0|abbr=on}} to the south, and a popular recreational area for those living in Donetsk. A wide belt of farmlands surrounds the city.\n\nThe city stretches {{convert|28|km|0|abbr=on}} from north to south and {{convert|55|km|0|abbr=on}} from east to west. There are 2 nearby [[Water reservoir|reservoirs]]: Nyzhnekalmius (60 [[hectares|ha]]), and the \"Donetsk Sea\" (206&nbsp;ha). 5 rivers flow through the city, including the [[Kalmius]], Asmolivka (13&nbsp;km), Cherepashkyna (23&nbsp;km), Skomoroshka and Bakhmutka. The city also contains a total of 125 spoil tips.<ref name=\"Was there a ghetto in Donetsk\">{{cite web |last=Liakh |first=Liudmila |script-title=ru:\u0411\u044b\u043b\u043e \u043b\u0438 \u0433\u0435\u0442\u0442\u043e \u0432 \u0414\u043e\u043d\u0435\u0446\u043a\u0435? |language=Russian |trans-title=Was there a ghetto in Donetsk? |publisher=gorod.donbass.com |url=http://www.gorod.donbass.com/archive/html/1941252001.htm |accessdate=7 May 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070903070923/http://www.gorod.donbass.com/archive/html/1941252001.htm |archivedate=3 September 2007}}</ref>\n\n=== Climate ===\nDonetsk's climate is moderate [[Humid continental climate|warm summer continental]] ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification|K\u00f6ppen]]: ''Dfb'').<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weather-summary.php3?s=91543&cityname=Donetsk,+Donetsk,+Ukraine&units=|title=Donetsk, Ukraine K\u00f6ppen Climate Classification (Weatherbase)|website=Weatherbase|access-date=2018-11-13}}</ref> The average temperatures are{{convert|-4.1|\u00b0C|0|abbr=on}} in January and {{convert|21.6|\u00b0C|0|abbr=on}} in July. The average number of rainfall per year totals 162 days and up to 556 millimetres per year.<ref name=\"rospogoda.ru\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rospogoda.ru/city3_48.html|title=The Weather in Donetsk|website=rospogoda.ru|language=Russian|script-title=ru:\u041f\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430 \u0432 \u0414\u043e\u043d\u0435\u0446\u043a\u0435|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070430133346/http://www.rospogoda.ru/city3_48.html|archivedate=30 April 2007|url-status=dead|accessdate=5 May 2007}}</ref>\n{{Weather box|location = Donetsk 1981\u20132010\n|metric first = Yes\n|single line = Yes\n| Jan record high C = 12.2\n| Feb record high C = 16.0\n| Mar record high C = 21.3\n| Apr record high C = 31.0\n| May record high C = 34.6\n| Jun record high C = 38.0\n| Jul record high C = 37.8\n| Aug record high C = 39.1\n| Sep record high C = 33.9\n| O