ory:City name changes in Ukraine]]\n[[Category:Former Soviet toponymy in Ukraine]]\n[[Category:Oblast centers in Ukraine]]\n[[Category:Bakhmutsky Uyezd]]\n[[Category:De-Stalinization]]\n", "name_user": "80.44.55.50", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eSee also)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Donetsk"}
{"title_page": "Ormond Robbins", "text_new": "{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name          = Ormond Orlea Robbins\n| image         = Ormond_Robbins_-_Dane_Gregory.png\n| imagesize     = 200px\n| alt           =\n| caption       =\n| pseudonym     = Dane Gregory, Breck Tarrant\n| birth_name     = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date|1910|3|14|mf=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Stillwater, Oklahoma|Stillwater]], [[Oklahoma]]\n| death_date     = {{death date and age|1984|7|21|1910|3|14|mf=y}}\n| death_place    = [[Seaside, Oregon|Seaside]], [[Oregon]]\n| occupation    = [[Author]]\n| language      = [[American English]]\n| nationality   = United States\n| ethnicity     = \n| citizenship   = \n| education     = \n| alma_mater    = University of Washington\n| period        = \n| genre         = [[Pulp magazine|Pulp]] [[Detective fiction|Detective]] and [[Horror fiction]]\n| subject       = [[Horror (emotion)|Horror]]\n| movement      = [[Hardboiled]], [[Weird menace]]\n| notableworks  = \n| spouse        = \n| partner       = \n| children      = \n| relatives     = \n| influences    = \n| influenced    = \n| awards        = \n| signature     = \n| signature_alt = \n| website       = \n| portaldisp    = \n}}\n\n'''Ormond Orlea Robbins''' (March 14, 1910&nbsp;\u2013 July 21, 1984) was an American [[author]] of [[hardboiled]] [[detective fiction]] and [[weird fiction]]. His work was primarily published in the [[Popular Publications]] catalog of [[pulp magazine|pulp fiction]]. The most part of his work for Popular Publications was attributed to his pen names ''Dane Gregory'' and, occasionally, ''Breck Tarrant''.\n\nIn ''The Shudder Pulps'', Robert Kenneth Jones places Dane Gregory's detective fiction in the vogue of the \"defective detective\" in the late nineteen-thirties and early forties. Recurring characters in Dane Gregory's fiction included ''Rocky Rhodes'', ex-convict turned private investigator, and ''Satan Jones''.<ref>''The Shudder Pulps'', Robert Kenneth Jones, Fax Collector's Editions Inc., 1975, {{ISBN|0-913960-04-7}}.</ref>\n\nOrmond Robbins' brother [[Wayne Robbins]] also wrote fiction for the pulps. The two brothers even collaborated on a western story, ''Murder Boss Of The Poverty Pool'' that was featured in ''10 Story Western Magazine'' in September 1941.\n\n==Biography==\n[[File:Francis, Wayne, Ormond, and Lorimer Robbins.jpg|thumb|240px|right|alt=Francis, Wayne, Ormond, and Lorimer Robbins|Francis, [[Wayne Robbins|Wayne]], Ormond, and Lorimer Robbins]]\n\nOrmond Robbins was born on March 14, 1910 in [[Stillwater, Oklahoma]] to Charles L. and Clara (Brooks) Robbins. His family moved to [[Sunnyside, Washington]] in 1919, where Ormond completed elementary and high school, class of 1928.\n\nHe began writing short stories, humor, and poetry at about age 12. By the age of 15, he regularly contributed to the pulp magazine ''[[College Humor (magazine)|College Humor]]''.<!--Working on this bibliography--> ''[[The Saturday Evening Post]]'' published a poem in their December 1, 1934 issue, and another in March of the following year. He saw another printed in the June 1935 issue of ''Country Gentleman.'' In 1936, the newly established ''Yakima Independent'' newspaper carried his daily column for about a year.\n\nHe married Jane Eshom on October 8, 1937 in [[Yakima, Washington]]. Their daughter, Alta Jane Robbins, was born on 15 April 1951. After a divorce, he married Wanda M. Falls at Bettles Field, Alaska on September 20, 1957. They had no children.\n\nOrmond was unable to serve in [[World War II]] due to a [[4F (military conscription)|4f classification]], but he and Jane were accepted by the [[FAA|Civil Aeronautics Administration]] (now the FAA) for outpost positions in Alaska. Ormond served as station manager, while Jane was a communications operator.<ref>''CAA Mukluk Telegraph'', July 1947, p. 30, retrieved from [http://www.atchistory.org/History/Pubs/mukluk_telegraph_pubs/pdf_files/1947/mukluk_telegraph_jul_1947.pdf atchistory.org] November 30, 2009.</ref> Their first assignment was [[Nome, Alaska|Nome]], then [[Kotzebue, Alaska|Kotzebue]] in 1945, and then [[List of places in Alaska/B|Bettles Field]] in 1951.<ref>''CAA Mukluk Telegraph'', November 1948, p. 17, retrieved from [http://www.atchistory.org/History/Pubs/mukluk_telegraph_pubs/pdf_files/1948/mukluk_telegraph_1948_nov.pdf atchistory.org] November 30, 2009.</ref> He transferred with Wanda to [[Northway, Alaska|Northway]], and became district manager at [[Kenai, Alaska|Kenai]].<ref>''FAA Telephone Directory - Alaskan Region'', January 1968, p. 9, retrieved from [http://www.atchistory.org/History/Pubs/ak_phone_directory/alaskan_region_telephone_directory_Jan_1968.pdf atchistory.org] November 30, 2009.</ref> In 1969, he transferred to [[Anchorage, Alaska|Anchorage]], where he retired and became city manager at Kenai on January 20, 1970.<ref>''The Job No One Seemed to Want'', Clark Fair, The Redoubt Reporter, May 6, 2009, retrieved from [http://redoubtreporter.wordpress.com/2009/05/06/1-in-a-million-shot-%E2%80%94-persistent-pacific-passenger-sews-up-free-ticket-stock/ redoubtreporter.wordpress.com] November 30, 2009.</ref>\n\nIn 1974, Ormond and Wanda returned to Sunnyside, Washington to be near his father, his mother having died that year. After his father died in 1978, they moved to [[Seaside, Oregon]], where Ormond died in 1984. He had survived both his first wife Jane and his daughter, and left no descendants.\n\n==Bibliography==\n\n===Published Short Stories and Novelettes===\n\n<div style=\"padding: 0em .5em; font-size:0.9em;\">(Attributed to \"Ormond Robbins.\")</div>\n*''Eternal'', Complete Stories - August 1929 #2 (poem)\n*''Detective Novel'', The Saturday Evening Post - December 1, 1934 (poem)\n*''Spirited Plea for a Return to the Old Order'', The Saturday Evening Post - March 30, 1935 (poem)\n*''Unknown Title'', Country Gentleman - June 1935 (poem)\n<div style=\"padding: 