riters]]\n\n==Footnotes==\n<references/>\n\n==References==\n*''The Shudder Pulps'', Robert Kenneth Jones, Fax Collector's Editions Inc., 1975, {{ISBN|0-913960-04-7}}. (Jones' work conflates the brothers Wayne and Ormond Robbins together with Ormond's pen name Dane Gregory, but otherwise provides a solid history of weird menace fiction.)\n*''Selected tales of Grim and Grue from the Horror Pulps'', [[Sheldon Jaffery]], Bowling Green State University Popular Press, 1987, {{ISBN|978-0-87972-391-0}} (hardcover), {{ISBN|978-0-87972-392-7}} (paperback).\n*''The Weirds'', Sheldon Jaffery, Starmont House Inc., 1987, {{ISBN|0-930261-92-5}}.\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Robbins, Ormond}}\n[[Category:20th-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:American male novelists]]\n[[Category:1910 births]]\n[[Category:1984 deaths]]\n[[Category:American crime fiction writers]]\n[[Category:People from Seaside, Oregon]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male writers]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ormond_Robbins"}
{"title_page": "Handroanthus impetiginosus", "text_new": "{{Speciesbox\n| image = Tabebuia_impetiginosa_h\u00e1bito_2.jpeg\n| image_caption = Flowering in Corrientes, [[Argentina]]\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN2.3\n| status_ref = <ref>https://www.iucnredlist.org/species/32024/9675106</ref>\n| display_parents = 2\n| genus = Handroanthus\n| species = impetiginosus\n| authority = ([[Carl Friedrich Philipp von Martius|Mart.]] ex [[Augustin Pyrame de Candolle|DC.]]) [[Jo\u00e1o Rodrigues de Mattos|Mattos]]\n| synonyms = {{Plainlist | style = margin-left: 1em; text-indent: -1em; |\n*''Gelseminum avellanedae'' <small>(Lorentz ex Griseb.) Kuntze</small>\n*''Handroanthus avellanedae'' <small>(Lorentz ex Griseb.) Mattos</small>\n*''Tabebuia avellanedae'' <small>Lorentz ex Griseb.</small>\n*''Tabebuia dugandii'' <small>Standl.</small>\n*''Tabebuia impetiginosa'' <small>(Mart. ex DC.) Standl.</small>\n*''Tabebuia ipe'' <small>var. integra (Sprague) Sandwith</small>\n*''Tabebuia nicaraguensis'' <small>S.F.Blake</small>\n*''Tabebuia palmeri'' <small>Rose</small>\n*''Tabebuia schunkevigoi'' <small>D.R.Simpson</small>\n*''Tecoma adenophylla'' <small>Bureau & K.Schum. in C.F.P.von Martius & auct. suc. (eds.)</small>\n*''Tecoma avellanedae'' <small>(Lorentz ex Griseb.) Speg.</small>\n*''Tecoma avellanedae'' <small>var. alba Lillo</small>\n*''Tecoma impetiginosa'' <small>Mart. ex DC.</small>\n*''Tecoma integra'' <small>(Sprague) Hassl.</small>\n*''Tecoma ipe'' <small>f. leucotricha Hassl.</small>\n*''Tecoma ipe'' <small>var. integra Sprague</small>\n*''Tecoma ipe'' <small>var. integrifolia Hassl.</small>\n   }}\n| synonyms_ref = <ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://apps.kew.org/wcsp/synonomy.do?name_id=317146\n|title=World Checklist of Selected Plant Families\n|accessdate=June 3, 2014}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Handroanthus impetiginosus''''',<ref>{{GRIN | ''Tabebuia impetiginosa'' | 36147 | accessdate = December 21, 2017}}</ref> '''pink ip\u00ea''', '''pink lapacho''', or '''pink trumpet tree''' is a native tree of family [[Bignoniaceae]] of the [[Americas]], distributed from northern [[Mexico]] south to northern [[Argentina]]. Lapacho is the national tree of [[Paraguay]],<ref>[http://homeguides.sfgate.com/lapacho-tree-48569.html]</ref> and it is also a common tree in Argentina's northeastern region, as well as in southeastern [[Bolivia]].  According to ''Native Trees of Trinidad and Tobago'', this tree is not indigenous to Trinidad, it is introduced.\n\nIt is a conspicuous and well-known species with a long history of human use. Consequently, it has a range of local names: ''ip\u00ea-cavat\u00e3, ip\u00ea-comum, ip\u00ea-reto, ip\u00ea-rosa, ip\u00ea-roxo-damata, lapacho negro, pau d'arco-roxo, pe\u00fava'' or ''pi\u00fava''. The [[timber]] is sometimes traded as \"[[Brazilwood]]\", which properly refers to the unrelated Pernambuco tree (''[[Caesalpinia echinata]]'').\n\n==Description==\n[[Image:Tabebuia impetiginosa hojas.jpeg|thumb|left|150px|Foliage]]\n[[Image:Tabebuia impetiginosa inflorescencia.jpeg|thumb|left|150px|[[Inflorescence]]s]]\n[[Image:Tabebuia impetiginosa flower.jpg|thumb|left|150px|A single flower]]\n\nThe pink lapacho is a rather large [[deciduous]] tree, with trunks sometimes reaching 8 dm width and 30 m height. Usually a third of that height is trunk, and two thirds are its longer branches. It has a large, globous, but often sparse [[Canopy (forest)|canopy]]. The tree has a slow growth rate. Leaves are opposite and [[Petiole (botany)|petiolate]], 2 to 3&nbsp;inches long, elliptic and [[lanceolate]], with lightly serrated margins and pinnate [[Leaf#Venation (arrangement of the veins)|venation]]. The leaves are palmately compound with usually 5 leaflets.\n\nIts bark is brownish grey, tough and hard to peel. The wood is of a pleasant yellowish colour, barely knotted and very tough and heavy (0,935&nbsp;kg/dm\u00b3). It's rich in [[tannin]]s and therefore very resistant to weather and sun.<ref name = lopezetal1987>L\u00f3pez ''et al.'' (1987)</ref> It is not very useful for furniture since it is so hard to work by hand. It can be found as beams or fulfilling other structural uses where needed outdoors.\n\nIn the southern hemisphere, pink lapacho flowers between July and September, before the new leaves appear. In the northern hemisphere like [[India]], the flowering season is December to January, after the leaves are shed. The flower is large, tubular shaped, its corolla is often pink or magenta, though exceptionally seen white, about 2&nbsp;inches long. There are four [[stamens]] and a [[staminode]]. The fruit consists of a narrow dehiscent [[Capsule (fruit)|capsule]] containing several winged seeds.\n\nThe flowers are easily accessible to [[pollinator]]s. Some [[hummingbird]]s - e.g. [[black jacobin]] (''Florisuga fusca'') and [[black-throated mango]] (''Anthracothorax nigricollis'') - seem to prefer them over the flowers of other ''[[Handroanthus]]'' species, while for others like the [[stripe-breasted starthroat]] (''Heliomaster squamosus'') it may even be a mainstay food source.<ref>Baza Mendon\u00e7a & dos Anjos (2005)</ref>\n\n==Ecology==\n\nHarvest of wild ''Handroanthus impetiginosus'' for lumber to make flooring and decking (in which case it is referred to as ip\u00ea in much of the timber trade) has become a major cause of [[deforestation of the Amazon rainforest|deforestation in the Amazon]].<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Schulze M, Grogan J, Landis RM, Vidal E | title = How rare is too rare to harvest? Management challenges posted by timber species occurring at low densities in the Brazilian Amazon| journal = [[Forest Ecology and Management]]  | year = 2008 | volume = 256 | pages = 1443\u20131457 | doi=10.1016/j.foreco.2008.02.051}}</ref> Because the trees do not grow in concentrated stands but instead are found scattered throughout the forest, logging roads have to be built long distances to locate and harvest the trees. In most cases, once these trees are logged, the rest of the forest is cleared for agricultural use.<ref name=\"Schulze M, Grogan J, Uhl C, et al. 2008 2071\u20132085\">{{cite journal  |vauthors=Schulze M, Grogan J, Uhl C, etal | title = Evaluating ip\u00ea (''Tabebuia'', Bignoniaceae) logging in Amazonia: Sustainable management or catalyst for forest degradation? | journal = [[Biological Conservation (journal)|Biological Conservation]]  | year = 2008 | volume = 141 | pages = 2071\u20132085 | doi=10.1016/j.biocon.2008.06.003}}</ref> Scientific examination of current logging practices, in which 90% of mature trees can be legally harvested, found that recovery from juvenile populations within 60 years was not likely under any feasible scenario (five were modeled).<ref name=\"Schulze M, Grogan J, Uhl C, et al. 2008 2071\u20132085\"/> The parallel to the overharvesting of [[Swietenia macrophylla]] (big-leaf mahogany), a tree that grows in a similar distribution in the same areas as ip\u00ea, is interesting, yet ip\u00ea continues to be logged at prodigious rates with no sign of a listing in the Convention on Trade in International Species or other drastic actions likely necessary to prevent extinction. [[Swietenia mahagoni]] and [[Swietenia humilis]] (other species yielding mahogany wood) were so thoroughly depleted that by the early 1900s there were essentially none left to harvest in the wild. Unfortunately the current scenario is one in which ''Handroanthus'' is headed for similar unsustainable depletion of wild populations.\n\n==Uses==\n[[Image:Lapacho Teerinde.JPG|thumb|left|[[Lapacho]] tea]]\n''Handroanthus impetiginosus'', as well as other species of this genus, are trees naturally found in the wild of central to South American forests. It is also used as a [[honey plant]], and widely planted as [[ornamental tree]] in landscaping gardens, public squares and boulevards due to its impressive and colorful appearance as it flowers.<ref name=lopezetal1987/> Well-known and popular, it is the [[Floral emblem|national tree]] of Paraguay. It is also planted as a street tree in cities of India, like in Bangalore.\n\nThe inner [[Bark (botany)|bark]] of ''Handroanthus impetiginosus'' is used in [[traditional medicine]].<ref>[http://www.esalq.usp.br/trilhas/medicina/am21.htm?PHPSESSID=82bf340b6b369121eea5b3aeefd6eef5 ''Tabebuia avellanedae''] at [[University of S\u00e3o Paulo]]</ref> It is dried, shredded, and then boiled, making a bitter brownish-colored tea known as [[lapacho]] or taheebo. The unpleasant taste of the extract is lessened when taken in pill form, or as [[tincture]]s. Lapacho bark is typically used during flu and cold season and for easing [[smoker's cough]].{{citation needed|date=March 2013}} It apparently works by promoting the lungs to expectorate and free deeply embedded mucus and contaminants during the first three to ten days of treatment.<ref name = lopezetal1987 />{{medcn|date=March 2013}}\n\nIn [[ethnomedicine]], lapacho plays an important role for several South American indigenous peoples. In the past decades it has been used by [[herbalist]]s as a general [[Pharmaceutical drug|tonic]], [[immunostimulant]],<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Wagner H. |author2=Seitz R. | title = Lapacho (''Tabebuia impetiginosa'') - Portrait of a medicinal plant from the Southamerican rainforest | journal = Zeitschrift f\u00fcr Phytotherapie | year = 1998 | volume = 19 | issue = 4 | pages = 226\u2013238}}</ref> and [[adaptogen]]. It is used in herbal medicine for intestinal [[candidiasis]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.oralchelation.com/taheebo/lapacho1.htm | title = Purple Lapacho: Ancient Herb, Modern Miracle | publisher = oralchelation.com | url-status = dead | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070528182811/http://www.oralchelation.com/taheebo/lapacho1.htm | archive-date = 2007-05-28 | df =  }}</ref>\n\nHowever, the main active compound [[lapachol]] has since turned out to be toxic enough to kill fetuses in pregnant rats and reduce the weight of the seminal vesicle in male rats in doses of 100&nbsp;mg/kg of body weight.<ref>E.g. de C\u00e1ssia da Silveira e S\u00e1 & de Oliveira Guerra (2007)</ref> Still, lapachol has strong [[antibiotic]] and [[disinfectant]] properties, and may be better suited for [[topical]] applications. [[Lapachol]] induces genetic damage, specifically [[clastogenic]] effects, in rats.<ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 20112181 | year = 2010 | last1 = Maistro | first1 = EL | last2 = Fernandes | first2 = DM | last3 = Pereira | first3 = FM | last4 = Andrade | first4 = SF | title = Lapachol induces clastogenic effects in rats | volume = 76 | issue = 9 | pages = 858\u201362 | doi = 10.1055/s-0029-1240816 | journal = [[Planta Medica]]}}</ref> Beta-lapachone has a direct [[cytotoxic]] effect and the loss of [[telomerase]] activity in [[leukemia]] cells ''in vitro''.<ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 20438329 | year = 2010 | last1 = Moon | first1 = DO | last2 = Kang | first2 = CH | last3 = Kim | first3 = MO | last4 = Jeon | first4 = YJ | last5 = Lee | first5 = JD | last6 = Choi | first6 = YH | last7 = Kim | first7 = GY | title = Beta-lapachone (LAPA) decreases cell viability and telomerase activity in leukemia cells: Suppression of telomerase activity by LAPA | volume = 13 | issue = 3 | pages = 481\u20138 | doi = 10.1089/jmf.2008.1219 | journal = [[Journal of Medicinal Food]]}}</ref>\n\nThe ethnomedical use of lapacho and other ''Handroanthus'' teas is usually short-term, to get rid of acute ailments, and not as a general tonic.  Usefulness as a short-term antimicrobial and disinfecting expectorant, e.g. against [[Pneumocystis pneumonia|PCP]] in [[AIDS]] patients, is yet to be scientifically studied. ''Handroanthus impetiginosus'' inner bark seems to have anti-''[[Helicobacter pylori]]'' activity.<ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 16359837 | year = 2006 | last1 = Park | first1 = BS | last2 = Lee | first2 = HK | last3 = Lee | first3 = SE | last4 = Piao | first4 = XL | last5 = Takeoka | first5 = GR | last6 = Wong | first6 = RY | last7 = Ahn | first7 = YJ | last8 = Kim | first8 = JH | title = Antibacterial activity of ''Tabebuia impetiginosa'' Martius ex DC (Taheebo) against Helicobacter pylori | volume = 105 | issue = 1\u20132 | pages = 255\u201362 | doi = 10.1016/j.jep.2005.11.005 | journal = [[Journal of Ethnopharmacology]]| url = https://naldc-legacy.nal.usda.gov/naldc/download.xhtml?id=30016&content=PDF }}</ref> and has some effects on other human intestinal bacteria.<ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 15713033 | year = 2005 | last1 = Park | first1 = BS | last2 = Kim | first2 = JR | last3 = Lee | first3 = SE | last4 = Kim | first4 = KS | last5 = Takeoka | first5 = GR | last6 = Ahn | first6 = YJ | last7 = Kim | first7 = JH | title = Selective growth-inhibiting effects of compounds identified in ''Tabebuia impetiginosa'' inner bark on human intestinal bacteria | volume = 53 | issue = 4 | pages = 1152\u20137 | doi = 10.1021/jf0486038 | journal = [[Journal of Agricultural and Food Chemistry]]}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Tabebuia avellanedae.jpg|Lapacho in the wild\nFile:Tabebuia impetiginosa.jpg|in Bras\u00edlia\nFile:Tabebuia impetiginosa (Pink Trumpet tree) in Hyderabad, AP W IMG 2609.jpg|in [[Hyderabad, India]].\nImage:Tabebuia impetiginosa (Pink Trumpet tree) in Hyderabad, AP W IMG 2608.jpg|trunk\nCastle in bloom (2351687460).jpg|Tabebuia impetiginosa at Disneyland\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Lapacho]]\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* {{aut|Angely, J.A.}} (1965): ''Flora analitica do Parana''.\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Baza Mendon\u00e7a | first1 = Luciana | last2 = dos Anjos | first2 = Luiz | year = 2005 | title = Beija-flores (Aves, Trochilidae) e seus recursos florais em uma \u00e1rea urbana do Sul do Brasil [Hummingbirds (Aves, Trochilidae) and their flowers in an urban area of southern Brazil]. [Portuguese with English abstract] | url = | journal = Revista Brasileira de Zoologia | volume = 22 | issue = 1| pages = 51\u201359 | doi = 10.1590/S0101-81752005000100007 }}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = de | first1 =  | last2 = S\u00e1 | first2 = Rita | last3 = de Oliveira Guerra | first3 = Martha | year = 2007 | title = Reproductive toxicity of lapachol in adult male Wistar rats submitted to short-term treatment | url = | journal = [[Phytotherapy Research|Phytother. Res.]] | volume = 21 | issue = 7| pages = 658\u2013662 | doi = 10.1002/ptr.2141 | pmid = 17421057 }}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = G\u00f3mez-Castellanosa | first1 = J. R. | last2 = Prieto | first2 = J. M. | year = 2009 | title = Red Lapacho Tea (''Tabebuia impetiginosa'') \u2013 a global ethnopharmacological commodity? | url = | journal = Journal of Ethnopharmacology | volume = 121 | issue = | pages = 1\u201313 }}\n* {{aut|L\u00f3pez, J.A.; Little, E.; Ritz, G.; Rombold, J. & Hahn, W.}} (1987): ''\u00c1rboles comunes del Paraguay: \u00d1ande yvyra mata kuera.'' Cuerpo de Paz, Asunci\u00f3n.\n* [[Pradip Krishen]], ''Trees of Delhi a Field Guide'', DK publishers, Page 216, 2006\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.cancer.org/treatment/treatmentsandsideeffects/complementaryandalternativemedicine/herbsvitaminsandminerals/pau-d-arco Pau d'arco], [[American Cancer Society]]\n* http://hort.ifas.ufl.edu/database/documents/pdf/tree_fact_sheets/tabimpa.pdf\n* [http://medicalxpress.com/news/2011-07-class-antiangiogenesis-drugs.html New class of antiangiogenesis (anti-cancer) drugs identified in ''Tabebuia avellanedae'']\n\n{{Commons category|Handroanthus impetiginosus}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q3266951|from2=Q20884077}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Handroanthus impetiginosus}}\n[[Category:Handroanthus|impetiginosus]]\n[[Category:Trees of Mexico]]\n[[Category:Trees of Argentina]]\n[[Category:Trees of Brazil]]\n[[Category:Trees of Bolivia]]\n[[Category:Trees of Paraguay]]\n[[Category:Flora of the Cerrado]]\n[[Category:Medicinal plants of South America]]\n[[Category:Plant dyes]]\n[[Category:Garden plants of North America]]\n[[Category:Garden plants of South America]]\n[[Category:Ornamental trees]]\n[[Category:Trees of Peru]]\n[[Category:Plants described in 1845]]\n", "text_old": "{{Speciesbox\n| image = Tabebuia_impetiginosa_h\u00e1bito_2.jpeg\n| image_caption = Flowering in Corrientes, [[Argentina]]\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN2.3\n| status_ref = <ref>https://www.iucnredlist.org/species/32024/9675106</ref>\n| display_parents = 2\n| genus = Handroanthus\n| species = impetiginosus\n| authority = ([[Carl Friedrich Philipp von Martius|Mart.]] ex [[Augustin Pyrame de Candolle|DC.]]) [[Jo\u00e1o Rodrigues de Mattos|Mattos]]\n| synonyms = {{Plainlist | style = margin-left: 1em; text-indent: -1em; |\n*''Gelseminum avellanedae'' <small>(Lorentz ex Griseb.) Kuntze</small>\n*''Handroanthus avellanedae'' <small>(Lorentz ex Griseb.) Mattos</small>\n*''Tabebuia avellanedae'' <small>Lorentz ex Griseb.</small>\n*''Tabebuia dugandii'' <small>Standl.</small>\n*''Tabebuia impetiginosa'' <small>(Mart. ex DC.) Standl.</small>\n*''Tabebuia ipe'' <small>var. integra (Sprague) Sandwith</small>\n*''Tabebuia nicaraguensis'' <small>S.F.Blake</small>\n*''Tabebuia palmeri'' <small>Rose</small>\n*''Tabebuia schunkevigoi'' <small>D.R.Simpson</small>\n*''Tecoma adenophylla'' <small>Bureau & K.Schum. in C.F.P.von Martius & auct. suc. (eds.)</small>\n*''Tecoma avellanedae'' <small>(Lorentz ex Griseb.) Speg.</small>\n*''Tecoma avellanedae'' <small>var. alba Lillo</small>\n*''Tecoma impetiginosa'' <small>Mart. ex DC.</small>\n*''Tecoma integra'' <small>(Sprague) Hassl.</small>\n*''Tecoma ipe'' <small>f. leucotricha Hassl.</small>\n*''Tecoma ipe'' <small>var. integra Sprague</small>\n*''Tecoma ipe'' <small>var. integrifolia Hassl.</small>\n   }}\n| synonyms_ref = <ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://apps.kew.org/wcsp/synonomy.do?name_id=317146\n|title=World Checklist of Selected Plant Families\n|accessdate=June 3, 2014}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Handroanthus impetiginosus''''',<ref>{{GRIN | ''Tabebuia impetiginosa'' | 36147 | accessdate = December 21, 2017}}</ref> '''pink ip\u00ea''', '''pink lapacho''', or '''pink trumpet tree''' is a native tree of family [[Bignoniaceae]] of the [[Americas]], distributed from northern [[Mexico]] south to northern [[Argentina]]. Lapacho is the national tree of [[Paraguay]],<ref>[http://homeguides.sfgate.com/lapacho-tree-48569.html]</ref> and it is also a common tree in Argentina's northeastern region, as well as in southeastern [[Bolivia]].  According to ''Native Trees of Trinidad and Tobago'', this tree is not indigenous to Trinidad, it is introduced.\n\nIt is a conspicuous and well-known species with a long history of human use. Consequently, it has a range of local names: ''ip\u00ea-cavat\u00e3, ip\u00ea-comum, ip\u00ea-reto, ip\u00ea-rosa, ip\u00ea-roxo-damata, lapacho negro, pau d'arco-roxo, pe\u00fava'' or ''pi\u00fava''. The [[timber]] is sometimes traded as \"[[Brazilwood]]\", which properly refers to the unrelated Pernambuco tree (''[[Caesalpinia echinata]]'').\n\n==Description==\n[[Image:Tabebuia impetiginosa hojas.jpeg|thumb|left|150px|Foliage]]\n[[Image:Tabebuia impetiginosa inflorescencia.jpeg|thumb|left|150px|[[Inflorescence]]s]]\n[[Image:Tabebuia impetiginosa flower.jpg|thumb|left|150px|A single flower]]\n\nThe pink lapacho is a rather large [[deciduous]] tree, with trunks sometimes reaching 8 dm width and 30 m height. Usually a third of that height is trunk, and two thirds are its longer branches. It has a large, globous, but often sparse [[Canopy (forest)|canopy]]. The tree has a slow growth rate. Leaves are opposite and [[Petiole (botany)|petiolate]], 2 to 3&nbsp;inches long, elliptic and [[lanceolate]], with lightly serrated margins and pinnate [[Leaf#Venation (arrangement of the veins)|venation]]. The leaves are palmately compound with usually 5 leaflets.\n\nIts bark is brownish grey, tough and hard to peel. The wood is of a pleasant yellowish colour, barely knotted and very tough and heavy (0,935&nbsp;kg/dm\u00b3). It's rich in [[tannin]]s and therefore very resistant to weather and sun.<ref name = lopezetal1987>L\u00f3pez ''et al.'' (1987)</ref> It is not very useful for furniture since it is so hard to work by hand. It can be found as beams or fulfilling other structural uses where needed outdoors.\n\nIn the southern hemisphere, pink lapacho flowers between July and September, before the new leaves appear. In the northern hemisphere like [[India]], the flowering season is December to January, after the leaves are shed. The flower is large, tubular shaped, its corolla is often pink or magenta, though exceptionally seen white, about 2&nbsp;inches long. There are four [[stamens]] and a [[staminode]]. The fruit consists of a narrow dehiscent [[Capsule (fruit)|capsule]] containing several winged seeds.\n\nThe flowers are easily accessible to [[pollinator]]s. Some [[hummingbird]]s - e.g. [[black jacobin]] (''Florisuga fusca'') and [[black-throated mango]] (''Anthracothorax nigricollis'') - seem to prefer them over the flowers of other ''[[Handroanthus]]'' species, while for others like the [[stripe-breasted starthroat]] (''Heliomaster squamosus'') it may even be a mainstay food source.<ref>Baza Mendon\u00e7a & dos Anjos (2005)</ref>\n\n==Ecology==\n\nHarvest of wild ''Handroanthus impetiginosus'' for lumber to make flooring and decking (in which case it is referred to as ip\u00ea in much of the timber trade) has become a major cause of [[deforestation of the Amazon rainforest|deforestation in the Amazon]].<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Schulze M, Grogan J, Landis RM, Vidal E | title = How rare is too rare to harvest? Management challenges posted by timber species occurring at low densities in the Brazilian Amazon| journal = [[Forest Ecology and Management]]  | year = 2008 | volume = 256 | pages = 1443\u20131457 | doi=10.1016/j.foreco.2008.02.051}}</ref> Because the trees do not grow in concentrated stands but instead are found scattered throughout the forest, logging roads have to be built long distances to locate and harvest the trees. In most cases, once these trees are logged, the rest of the forest is cleared for agricultural use.<ref name=\"Schulze M, Grogan J, Uhl C, et al. 2008 2071\u20132085\">{{cite journal  |vauthors=Schulze M, Grogan J, Uhl C, etal | title = Evaluating ip\u00ea (''Tabebuia'', Bignoniaceae) logging in Amazonia: Sustainable management or catalyst for forest degradation? | journal = [[Biological Conservation (journal)|Biological Conservation]]  | year = 2008 | volume = 141 | pages = 2071\u20132085 | doi=10.1016/j.biocon.2008.06.003}}</ref> Scientific examination of current logging practices, in which 90% of mature trees can be legally harvested, found that recovery from juvenile populations within 60 years was not likely under any feasible scenario (five were modeled).<ref name=\"Schulze M, Grogan J, Uhl C, et al. 2008 2071\u20132085\"/> The parallel to the overharvesting of [[Swietenia macrophylla]] (big-leaf mahogany), a tree that grows in a similar distribution in the same areas as ip\u00ea, is interesting, yet ip\u00ea continues to be logged at prodigious rates with no sign of a listing in the Convention on Trade in International Species or other drastic actions likely necessary to prevent extinction. [[Swietenia mahagoni]] and [[Swietenia humilis]] (other species yielding mahogany wood) were so thoroughly depleted that by the early 1900s there were essentially none left to harvest in the wild. Unfortunately the current scenario is one in which ''Handroanthus'' is headed for similar unsustainable depletion of wild populations.\n\n==Uses==\n[[Image:Lapacho Teerinde.JPG|thumb|left|[[Lapacho]] tea]]\n''Handroanthus impetiginosus'', as well as other species of this genus, are trees naturally found in the wild of central to South American forests. It is also used as a [[honey plant]], and widely planted as [[ornamental tree]] in landscaping gardens, public squares and boulevards due to its impressive and colorful appearance as it flowers.<ref name=lopezetal1987/> Well-known and popular, it is the [[Floral emblem|national tree]] of Paraguay. It is also planted as a street tree in cities of India, like in Bangalore.\n\nThe inner [[Bark (botany)|bark]] of ''Handroanthus impetiginosus'' is used in [[traditional medicine]].<ref>[http://www.esalq.usp.br/trilhas/medicina/am21.htm?PHPSESSID=82bf340b6b369121eea5b3aeefd6eef5 ''Tabebuia avellanedae''] at [[University of S\u00e3o Paulo]]</ref> It is dried, shredded, and then boiled, making a bitter brownish-colored tea known as [[lapacho]] or taheebo. The unpleasant taste of the extract is lessened when taken in pill form, or as [[tincture]]s. Lapacho bark is typically used during flu and cold season and for easing [[smoker's cough]].{{citation needed|date=March 2013}} It apparently works by promoting the lungs to expectorate and free deeply embedded mucus and contaminants during the first three to ten days of treatment.<ref name = lopezetal1987 />{{medcn|date=March 2013}}\n\nIn [[ethnomedicine]], lapacho plays an important role for several South American indigenous peoples. In the past decades it has been used by [[herbalist]]s as a general [[Pharmaceutical drug|tonic]], [[immunostimulant]],<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Wagner H. |author2=Seitz R. | title = Lapacho (''Tabebuia impetiginosa'') - Portrait of a medicinal plant from the Southamerican rainforest | journal = Zeitschrift f\u00fcr Phytotherapie | year = 1998 | volume = 19 | issue = 4 | pages = 226\u2013238}}</ref> and [[adaptogen]]. It is used in herbal medicine for intestinal [[candidiasis]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.oralchelation.com/taheebo/lapacho1.htm | title = Purple Lapacho: Ancient Herb, Modern Miracle | publisher = oralchelation.com | url-status = dead | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070528182811/http://www.oralchelation.com/taheebo/lapacho1.htm | archive-date = 2007-05-28 | df =  }}</ref>\n\nHowever, the main active compound [[lapachol]] has since turned out to be toxic enough to kill fetuses in pregnant rats and reduce the weight of the seminal vesicle in male rats in doses of 100&nbsp;mg/kg of body weight.<ref>E.g. de C\u00e1ssia da Silveira e S\u00e1 & de Oliveira Guerra (2007)</ref> Still, lapachol has strong [[antibiotic]] and [[disinfectant]] properties, and may be better suited for [[topical]] applications. [[Lapachol]] induces genetic damage, specifically [[clastogenic]] effects, in rats.<ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 20112181 | year = 2010 | last1 = Maistro | first1 = EL | last2 = Fernandes | first2 = DM | last3 = Pereira | first3 = FM | last4 = Andrade | first4 = SF | title = Lapachol induces clastogenic effects in rats | volume = 76 | issue = 9 | pages = 858\u201362 | doi = 10.1055/s-0029-1240816 | journal = [[Planta Medica]]}}</ref> Beta-lapachone has a direct [[cytotoxic]] effect and the loss of [[telomerase]] activity in [[leukemia]] cells ''in vitro''.<ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 20438329 | year = 2010 | last1 = Moon | first1 = DO | last2 = Kang | first2 = CH | last3 = Kim | first3 = MO | last4 = Jeon | first4 = YJ | last5 = Lee | first5 = JD | last6 = Choi | first6 = YH | last7 = Kim | first7 = GY | title = Beta-lapachone (LAPA) decreases cell viability and telomerase activity in leukemia cells: Suppression of telomerase activity by LAPA | volume = 13 | issue = 3 | pages = 481\u20138 | doi = 10.1089/jmf.2008.1219 | journal = [[Journal of Medicinal Food]]}}</ref>\n\nThe ethnomedical use of lapacho and other ''Handroanthus'' teas is usually short-term, to get rid of acute ailments, and not as a general tonic.  Usefulness as a short-term antimicrobial and disinfecting expectorant, e.g. against [[Pneumocystis pneumonia|PCP]] in [[AIDS]] patients, is yet to be scientifically studied. ''Handroanthus impetiginosus'' inner bark seems to have anti-''[[Helicobacter pylori]]'' activity.<ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 16359837 | year = 2006 | last1 = Park | first1 = BS | last2 = Lee | first2 = HK | last3 = Lee | first3 = SE | last4 = Piao | first4 = XL | last5 = Takeoka | first5 = GR | last6 = Wong | first6 = RY | last7 = Ahn | first7 = YJ | last8 = Kim | first8 = JH | title = Antibacterial activity of ''Tabebuia impetiginosa'' Martius ex DC (Taheebo) against Helicobacter pylori | volume = 105 | issue = 1\u20132 | pages = 255\u201362 | doi = 10.1016/j.jep.2005.11.005 | journal = [[Journal of Ethnopharmacology]]| url = https://naldc-legacy.nal.usda.gov/naldc/download.xhtml?id=30016&content=PDF }}</ref> and has some effects on other human intestinal bacteria.<ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 15713033 | year = 2005 | last1 = Park | first1 = BS | last2 = Kim | first2 = JR | last3 = Lee | first3 = SE | last4 = Kim | first4 = KS | last5 = Takeoka | first5 = GR | last6 = Ahn | first6 = YJ | last7 = Kim | first7 = JH | title = Selective growth-inhibiting effects of compounds identified in ''Tabebuia impetiginosa'' inner bark on human intestinal bacteria | volume = 53 | issue = 4 | pages = 1152\u20137 | doi = 10.1021/jf0486038 | journal = [[Journal of Agricultural and Food Chemistry]]}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Tabebuia avellanedae.jpg|Lapacho in the wild\nFile:Tabebuia impetiginosa.jpg|in Bras\u00edlia\nFile:Tabebuia impetiginosa (Pink Trumpet tree) in Hyderabad, AP W IMG 2609.jpg|in [[Hyderabad, India]].\nImage:Tabebuia impetiginosa (Pink Trumpet tree) in Hyderabad, AP W IMG 2608.jpg|trunk\nCastle in bloom (2351687460).jpg|Tabebuia impetiginosa at Disneyland\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Lapacho]]\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* {{aut|Angely, J.A.}} (1965): ''Flora analitica do Parana''.\n* {{aut|Baza Mendon\u00e7a, Luciana & dos Anjos,  Luiz}} (2005): Beija-flores (Aves, Trochilidae) e seus recursos florais em uma \u00e1rea urbana do Sul do Brasil  [Hummingbirds (Aves, Trochilidae) and their flowers in an urban area of southern Brazil]. [Portuguese with English abstract] ''Revista Brasileira de Zoologia'' '''22'''(1): 51\u201359. <small>{{doi|10.1590/S0101-81752005000100007}}</small> [http://www.scielo.br/pdf/rbzool/v22n1/a07v22n1.pdf PDF fulltext]\n* {{aut|de C\u00e1ssia da Silveira e S\u00e1, Rita & de Oliveira Guerra, Martha}} (2007): Reproductive toxicity of lapachol in adult male Wistar rats submitted to short-term treatment. ''[[Phytotherapy Research|Phytother. Res.]]'' '''21'''(7): 658-662. <small>{{doi|10.1002/ptr.2141}} {{PMID|17421057}}</small> (HTML abstract)\n* {{aut|G\u00f3mez \u2013 Castellanosa, J. R., J. M. Prieto, and M.Heinrich}}  (2009) Red Lapacho Tea (''Tabebuia impetiginosa'') \u2013 a global ethnopharmacological commodity? Journal of Ethnopharmacology 121: 1- 13.\n* {{aut|L\u00f3pez, J.A.; Little, E.; Ritz, G.; Rombold, J. & Hahn, W.}} (1987): ''\u00c1rboles comunes del Paraguay: \u00d1ande yvyra mata kuera.'' Cuerpo de Paz, Asunci\u00f3n.\n* [[Pradip Krishen]], ''Trees of Delhi a Field Guide'', DK publishers, Page 216, 2006\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.cancer.org/treatment/treatmentsandsideeffects/complementaryandalternativemedicine/herbsvitaminsandminerals/pau-d-arco Pau d'arco], [[American Cancer Society]]\n* http://hort.ifas.ufl.edu/database/documents/pdf/tree_fact_sheets/tabimpa.pdf\n* [http://medicalxpress.com/news/2011-07-class-antiangiogenesis-drugs.html New class of antiangiogenesis (anti-cancer) drugs identified in ''Tabebuia avellanedae'']\n\n{{Commons category|Handroanthus impetiginosus}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q3266951|from2=Q20884077}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Handroanthus impetiginosus}}\n[[Category:Handroanthus|impetiginosus]]\n[[Category:Trees of Mexico]]\n[[Category:Trees of Argentina]]\n[[Category:Trees of Brazil]]\n[[Category:Trees of Bolivia]]\n[[Category:Trees of Paraguay]]\n[[Category:Flora of the Cerrado]]\n[[Category:Medicinal plants of South America]]\n[[Category:Plant dyes]]\n[[Category:Garden plants of North America]]\n[[Category:Garden plants of South America]]\n[[Category:Ornamental trees]]\n[[Category:Trees of Peru]]\n[[Category:Plants described in 1845]]\n", "name_user": "Rjwilmsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:Journal cites:,", 