{"title_page": "Perrin Busbee", "text_new": "{{Infobox college coach\n| name = Perrin Busbee\n| image = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1872|2|10}}\n| birth_place = [[Raleigh, North Carolina]]\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|1935|1|9|1872|2|10}}\n| death_place = [[Raleigh, North Carolina]]\n| alma_mater = \n| coach_sport1 = Football\n| coach_years2 = 1892\n| coach_team2 = [[NC State Wolfpack football|North Carolina A&M]]\n| coach_years3 = 1896\u20131897\n| coach_team3 = [[NC State Wolfpack football|North Carolina A&M]]\n| coach_sport4 = Baseball\n| coach_years5 = 1891\u20131893\n| coach_team5 = [[North Carolina Tar Heels baseball|North Carolina]]\n| overall_record = 3\u20132 (football)<br>9\u20136 (baseball)\n| bowl_record = \n| tournament_record = \n| championships = \n| awards = \n| coaching_records = \n}}\n'''Perrin Busbee''' (February 10, 1872 \u2013 January 9, 1935) was an [[American football]] and [[baseball]] coach.  He served as the head football coach at North Carolina College of Agriculture and Mechanic Arts, now [[North Carolina State University]], in 1892 again from 1896 to 1897, compiling a record of 3\u20132.  Busbee was also the first head baseball coach at the [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill]], coaching from 1891 to 1893 and tallying a mark of 9\u20136.\n\nOn Jan. 9, 1935, he died in Raleigh and is buried in Oakwood Cemetery.<ref>{{cite news|title=University Alumnus Is Dead in Raleigh |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/67775513/?terms=Perrin+Busbee+football|newspaper=The Daily Tar Heel|date=January 11, 1935|page=4|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = July 21, 2014 }} {{Open access}}</ref>\n\n==Head coaching record==\n===Football===\n{{CFB Yearly Record Start | type = coach | team = | conf = | bowl = | poll = no }}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Subhead\n | name      = [[NC State Wolfpack football|North Carolina A&M Aggies]]\n | conf      = Independent\n | startyear = 1892\n | endyear   = single\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = \n | year         = [[1892 college football season|1892]]\n | name         = [[1892 North Carolina A&M Aggies football team|North Carolina A&M]]\n | overall      = 1\u20130\n | conference   = \n | confstanding = \n | bowlname     = \n | bowloutcome  = \n | ranking      = no\n | ranking2     = no\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Subhead\n | name      = [[NC State Wolfpack football|North Carolina A&M Aggies]]\n | conf      = Independent\n | startyear = 1896\n | endyear   = 1897\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = \n | year         = [[1896 college football season|1896]]\n | name         = [[1896 North Carolina A&M Aggies football team|North Carolina A&M]]\n | overall      = 1\u20130\n | conference   = \n | confstanding = \n | bowlname     = \n | bowloutcome  = \n | bcsbowl      = \n | ranking      = no\n | ranking2     = no\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = \n | year         = [[1897 college football season|1897]]\n | name         = [[1897 North Carolina A&M Aggies football team|North Carolina A&M]]\n | overall      = 1\u20132\n | conference   = \n | confstanding = \n | bowlname     = \n | bowloutcome  = \n | bcsbowl      = \n | ranking      = no\n | ranking2     = no\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Subtotal\n | name       = North Carolina A&M\n | overall    = 3\u20132\n | confrecord = \n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record End\n | overall  = 3\u20132\n | bowls    = no\n | poll     = no\n | polltype = \n | legend   = no\n}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of college football head coaches with non-consecutive tenure]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Find a Grave|94007530}}\n\n{{North Carolina Tar Heels baseball coach navbox}}\n{{NC State Wolfpack football coach navbox}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Busbee, Perrin}}\n[[Category:1872 births]]\n[[Category:1935 deaths]]\n[[Category:NC State Wolfpack football coaches]]\n[[Category:North Carolina Tar Heels baseball coaches]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Raleigh, North Carolina]]\n\n{{1890s-collegefootball-coach-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox college coach\n| name = Perrin Busbee\n| image = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1872|2|10}}\n| birth_place = [[Raleigh, North Carolina]]\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|1935|1|9|1872|2|10}}\n| death_place = [[Raleigh, North Carolina]]\n| alma_mater = \n| coach_sport1 = Football\n| coach_years2 = 1892\n| coach_team2 = [[NC State Wolfpack football|North Carolina A&M]]\n| coach_years3 = 1896\u20131897\n| coach_team3 = [[NC State Wolfpack football|North Carolina A&M]]\n| coach_sport4 = Baseball\n| coach_years5 = 1891\u20131893\n| coach_team5 = [[North Carolina Tar Heels baseball|North Carolina]]\n| overall_record = 3\u20132 (football)<br>9\u20136 (baseball)\n| bowl_record = \n| tournament_record = \n| championships = \n| awards = \n| coaching_records = \n}}\n'''Perrin Busbee''' (February 10, 1872 \u2013 January 9, 1935) was an [[American football]] and [[baseball]] coach.  He served as the head football coach at North Carolina College of Agriculture and Mechanic Arts, now [[North Carolina State University]], in 1892 again from 1896 to 1897, compiling a record of 3\u20132.  Busbee was also the first head baseball coach at the [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill]], coaching from 1891 to 1893 and tallying a mark of 9\u20136.\n\nOn Jan. 9, 1935, he died in Raleigh and is buried in Oakwood Cemetery.<ref>{{cite news|title=University Alumnus Is Dead in Raleigh |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/67775513/?terms=Perrin+Busbee+football|newspaper=The Daily Tar Heel|date=January 11, 1935|page=4|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = July 21, 2014 }} {{Open access}}</ref>\n\n==Head coaching record==\n===Football===\n{{CFB Yearly Record Start | type = coach | team = | conf = | bowl = | poll = no }}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Subhead\n | name      = [[NC State Wolfpack football|North Carolina A&M Aggies]]\n | conf      = Independent\n | startyear = 1892\n | endyear   = single\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = \n | year         = [[1892 college football season|1892]]\n | name         = North Carolina A&M\n | overall      = 1\u20130\n | conference   = \n | confstanding = \n | bowlname     = \n | bowloutcome  = \n | ranking      = no\n | ranking2     = no\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Subhead\n | name      = [[NC State Wolfpack football|North Carolina A&M Aggies]]\n | conf      = Independent\n | startyear = 1896\n | endyear   = 1897\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = \n | year         = [[1896 college football season|1896]]\n | name         = North Carolina A&M\n | overall      = 1\u20130\n | conference   = \n | confstanding = \n | bowlname     = \n | bowloutcome  = \n | bcsbowl      = \n | ranking      = no\n | ranking2     = no\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = \n | year         = [[1897 college football season|1897]]\n | name         = North Carolina A&M\n | overall      = 1\u20132\n | conference   = \n | confstanding = \n | bowlname     = \n | bowloutcome  = \n | bcsbowl      = \n | ranking      = no\n | ranking2     = no\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Subtotal\n | name       = North Carolina A&M\n | overall    = 3\u20132\n | confrecord = \n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record End\n | overall  = 3\u20132\n | bowls    = no\n | poll     = no\n | polltype = \n | legend   = no\n}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of college football head coaches with non-consecutive tenure]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Find a Grave|94007530}}\n\n{{North Carolina Tar Heels baseball coach navbox}}\n{{NC State Wolfpack football coach navbox}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Busbee, Perrin}}\n[[Category:1872 births]]\n[[Category:1935 deaths]]\n[[Category:NC State Wolfpack football coaches]]\n[[Category:North Carolina Tar Heels baseball coaches]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Raleigh, North Carolina]]\n\n{{1890s-collegefootball-coach-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Jweiss11", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHead coaching record:add team links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Perrin_Busbee"}
{"title_page": "Mourmelon-le-Grand Airfield", "text_new": "{{Infobox military installation\n| name=Mourmelon-le-Grand<br>{{smaller|Advanced Landing Ground (ALG) A-80}}\n| ensign=Patch9thusaaf.png\n| ensign_size=60px\n| partof = \n| location= Champagne-Ardenne Region, France\n| image= \n| caption= \n| pushpin_map= France\n| pushpin_label= Mourmelon-le-Grand Airfield\n| pushpin_mapsize=300\n| coordinates={{Coord|49|06|45|N|004|22|20|E|type:airport|display=inline,title}}\n| type=Military airfield\n| code= \n| ownership= \n| controlledby=[[United States Army Air Forces]]\n| condition= \n| built= \n| builder= IX Engineering Command\n| used= September 1944 \u2013 July 1945\n| materials= Pierces Steel Planking (PSP)\n| demolished= \n| battles= [[Western Front (World War II)]]<br />Northern France Campaign\n| events= \n| past_commanders= \n| garrison= \n| occupants= \n}}\n\n'''Mourmelon-le-Grand Airfield''' is an abandoned [[World War II]] military airfield in [[France]]. It lies approximately 1 mile (2&nbsp;km) east-southeast of [[Mourmelon-le-Grand]] and 93 miles (150&nbsp;km) northeast of [[Paris]].\n\nThe airfield was a semi-permanent facility built by the USAAF in the Champagne region west of Monte Carnillet which was a fiercely contested region of the [[World War I]] [[Western Front (World War I)|Western Front]]. The 6000' (1830&nbsp;m) [[Pierced Steel Planking]] runway of the airfield supported fighter and transport aircraft from September 1944 through the end of the war in Europe.\n\n==History==\nKnown as [[Advanced Landing Ground]] \"A-80\", the airfield consisted of a single 6000' PSP runway aligned 08/26. Tents were used for billeting and for support facilities; an access road was built to the existing road infrastructure; there was a staging area for supplies, ammunition, and gasoline drums. There were a water-treatment facility and a minimal electrical grid for communications and station lighting.<ref>[http://www.ixengineercommand.com/airfields/physical.php IX Engineer Command ETO Airfields, Airfield Layout]</ref>\n\nCombat units stationed at the airfield were:<ref>Maurer, Maurer. ''Air Force Combat Units of World War II''. Maxwell AFB, Alabama: Office of Air Force History, 1983. {{ISBN|0-89201-092-4}}.</ref>\n* [[406th Fighter Group]], 22 September 1944 \u2013 2 February 1945 ([[P-47 Thunderbolt]])\n* [[358th Fighter Group]], 16 October \u2013 9 November 1944 (P-47)\n* [[434th Troop Carrier Group]], March \u2013 24 July 1945 ([[C-47 Skytrain]])\n\nAfter the war ended the facility was dismantled and the land was turned over to local French authorities. Today the remains of the airfield can be seen in aerial photography as a disturbed area south of Mourmelon-le-Grand.<ref>Johnson, David C. (1988), ''[https://www.afhra.af.mil/Portals/16/documents/Timelines/World%20War%20II/usaaf_european_airfields.pdf?ver=2016-08-30-150750-583 U.S. Army Air Forces Continental Airfields (ETO), D-Day to V-E Day]''; Research Division, USAF Historical Research Center, Maxwell AFB, Alabama.</ref>{{failed verification|date=May 2019}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|World War II}}\n* [[Advanced Landing Ground#A-71 to A-80|Advanced Landing Ground]]\n\n==References==\n{{Air Force Historical Research Agency}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{USAAF 9th Air Force UK}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mourmelon-Le-Grand Airfield}}\n[[Category:World War II airfields in France]]\n[[Category:Airfields of the United States Army Air Forces in France]]\n[[Category:Airports established in 1944]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military installation\n| name=Mourmelon-le-Grand<br>{{smaller|Advanced Landing Ground (ALG) A-80}}\n| ensign=Patch9thusaaf.png\n| ensign_size=60px\n| partof = \n| location= Champagne-Ardenne Region, France\n| image= \n| caption= \n| pushpin_map= France\n| pushpin_label= Mourmelon-le-Grand Airfield\n| pushpin_mapsize=300\n| coordinates={{Coord|49|06|45|N|004|22|20|E|type:airport|display=inline,title}}\n| type=Military airfield\n| code= \n| ownership= \n| controlledby=[[United States Army Air Forces]]\n| condition= \n| built= \n| builder= IX Engineering Command\n| used= September 1944 \u2013 July 1945\n| materials= Pierces Steel Planking (PSP)\n| demolished= \n| battles= [[Western Front (World War II)]]<br />Northern France Campaign\n| events= \n| past_commanders= \n| garrison= \n| occupants= \n}}\n\n'''Mourmelon-le-Grand Airfield''' is an abandoned [[World War II]] military airfield in [[France]]. It lies approximately 1 mile (2&nbsp;km) east-southeast of [[Mourmelon-le-Grand]] and 93 miles (150&nbsp;km) northeast of [[Paris]].\n\nThe airfield was a semi-permanent facility built by the USAAF in the Champagne region west of Monte Carnillet which was a fiercely contested region of the [[World War I]] [[Western Front (World War I)|Western Front]]. The 6000' (1830&nbsp;m) [[Pierced Steel Planking]] runway of the airfield supported fighter and transport aircraft from September 1944 though the end of the war in Europe.\n\n==History==\nKnown as [[Advanced Landing Ground]] \"A-80\", the airfield consisted of a single 6000' PSP runway aligned 08/26. Tents were used for billeting and for support facilities; an access road was built to the existing road infrastructure; there was a staging area for supplies, ammunition, and gasoline drums. There were a water-treatment facility and a minimal electrical grid for communications and station lighting.<ref>[http://www.ixengineercommand.com/airfields/physical.php IX Engineer Command ETO Airfields, Airfield Layout]</ref>\n\nCombat units stationed at the airfield were:<ref>Maurer, Maurer. ''Air Force Combat Units of World War II''. Maxwell AFB, Alabama: Office of Air Force History, 1983. {{ISBN|0-89201-092-4}}.</ref>\n* [[406th Fighter Group]], 22 September 1944 \u2013 2 February 1945 ([[P-47 Thunderbolt]])\n* [[358th Fighter Group]], 16 October \u2013 9 November 1944 (P-47)\n* [[434th Troop Carrier Group]], March \u2013 24 July 1945 ([[C-47 Skytrain]])\n\nAfter the war ended the facility was dismantled and the land was turned over to local French authorities. Today the remains of the airfield can be seen in aerial photography as a disturbed area south of Mourmelon-le-Grand.<ref>Johnson, David C. (1988), ''[https://www.afhra.af.mil/Portals/16/documents/Timelines/World%20War%20II/usaaf_european_airfields.pdf?ver=2016-08-30-150750-583 U.S. Army Air Forces Continental Airfields (ETO), D-Day to V-E Day]''; Research Division, USAF Historical Research Center, Maxwell AFB, Alabama.</ref>{{failed verification|date=May 2019}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|World War II}}\n* [[Advanced Landing Ground#A-71 to A-80|Advanced Landing Ground]]\n\n==References==\n{{Air Force Historical Research Agency}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{USAAF 9th Air Force UK}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mourmelon-Le-Grand Airfield}}\n[[Category:World War II airfields in France]]\n[[Category:Airfields of the United States Army Air Forces in France]]\n[[Category:Airports established in 1944]]\n", "name_user": "LilHelpa", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo: though\u2192through", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mourmelon-le-Grand_Airfield"}
{"title_page": "Lovage", "text_new": "{{For|the band|Lovage (band)}}\n{{speciesbox\n| name = Lovage\n| image = Liebst\u00f6ckel.JPG\n| display_parents = 2\n| genus = Levisticum\n| parent_authority = [[John Hill (author)|Hill]]\n| species = officinale\n| authority = [[Wilhelm Daniel Joseph Koch|W.D.J.Koch]]\n}}\n\n'''Lovage''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|l|\u028c|v|\u1d7b|d\u0292}}), '''''Levisticum officinale''''', is a tall [[perennial plant]], the sole species in the genus '''''Levisticum''''' in the family [[Apiaceae]], subfamily [[Apioideae]].<ref>{{cite book |author1=Pimenov, M. G. |author2=Leonov, M. V.  |lastauthoramp=yes | date = 1993 | title = The Genera of the Umbelliferae | publisher = Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew | isbn = 0-947643-58-3}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | author = Downie, S. R., Plunkett, G. M., Watson, M. F., Spalik, K., Katz-Downie, D. S., Valiejo-Roman, C. M., Terentieva, E. I., Troitsky, A. V., Lee, B.-Y., Lahham, J., and El-Oqlah, A. | date = 2001 | title = Tribes and clades within Apiaceae subfamily Apioideae: the contribution of molecular data | journal = Edinburgh Journal of Botany | volume = 58 | issue = 2 | pages = 301\u2013330 | doi=10.1017/s0960428601000658}}</ref> It has been long cultivated in Europe, the leaves being used as a herb, the roots as a vegetable, and the seeds as a spice, especially in southern European cuisine.\n\n==Description==\n[[File:Levisticum officinale 002.jpg|thumb|upright|Lovage flowers]]\nLovage is an erect, herbaceous, perennial plant growing to {{convert|1.8\u20132.5|m|ft|abbr=on}} tall, with a basal rosette of leaves and stems with further leaves, the flowers being produced in umbels at the top of the stems. The stems and leaves are shiny [[glabrousness|glabrous]] green to yellow-green and smell somewhat similar to celery when crushed. The larger basal leaves are up to {{convert|70|cm|in|abbr=on}} long, tripinnate, with broad triangular to rhomboidal, acutely pointed leaflets with a few marginal teeth; the stem leaves are smaller, and less divided with few leaflets. The flowers are yellow to greenish-yellow, {{convert|2\u20133|mm|in|abbr=on}} diameter, produced in globose umbels up to {{convert|10\u201315|cm|in|abbr=on}} diameter; flowering is in late spring. The fruit is a dry two-parted [[schizocarp]] {{convert|4\u20137|mm|in|abbr=on}} long, mature in autumn.<ref>Interactive Flora of NW Europe: [http://ip30.eti.uva.nl/BIS/flora.php?selected=beschrijving&menuentry=soorten&id=3303 ''Levisticum officinale'' (Lovage)]{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Distribution==\nThe exact native range is disputed; some sources cite it as native to much of [[Europe]] and southwestern [[Asia]],<ref name=\"Virtuella\">Den virtuella floran: [http://linnaeus.nrm.se/flora/di/apia/levis/levioff.html ''Levisticum officinale''] {{in lang|sv}}, with [http://linnaeus.nrm.se/flora/di/apia/levis/levioffv.jpg map]</ref> others from only the eastern Mediterranean region in southeastern Europe and southwestern Asia,<ref name=\"Huxley\">{{cite book | editor = Huxley, A. | date = 1992 | title = New RHS Dictionary of Gardening | isbn = 0-333-47494-5}}</ref> and yet others only to southwestern Asia in [[Iran]] and [[Afghanistan]], citing European populations as [[naturalisation (biology)|naturalised]].<ref name=\"Blamey\">{{cite book |author1=Blamey, M.  |author2=Grey-Wilson, C.  |lastauthoramp=yes | date = 1989 | title = Illustrated Flora of Britain and Northern Europe | isbn = 0-340-40170-2}}</ref><ref>{{GRIN | accessdate = 11 December 2017}}</ref> It has been long cultivated in Europe, the [[leaf|leaves]] being used as an herb, the roots as a vegetable, and the seeds as a spice, especially in southern European cuisine.<ref name=\"Huxley\"/>\n\n==Properties and uses==\nThe [[leaves]] can be used in [[salad]]s, or to make [[soup]] or season broths, and the [[root]]s can be eaten as a [[vegetable]] or grated for use in salads. Its flavor and smell can be described as a mix of [[celery]] and [[parsley]], but with a higher intensity of both of those flavors. The seeds can be used as a spice, similar to [[fennel]] seeds.<ref name=\"Huxley\"/> \n<ul>\n<li>In [[the Netherlands]], lovage leaves are traditionally cooked with white [[asparagus]] and salt; and served with boiled eggs.{{citation needed|date=April 2017}}\n<li>In [[Romania]], the leaves are the preferred seasoning for the various local broths, equally as much as parsley or dill.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://adevarul.ro/locale/arad/In-fel-ciorbe-indicat-folosim-leusteanul-multe-frunze-puternic-aromate-putem-pune-1_58ad5cad5ab6550cb8b4767b/index.html|title=\u00cen ce fel de ciorbe este indicat s\u0103 folosim leu\u015fteanul. C\u00e2t de multe frunze puternic aromate putem pune|date=23 February 2017|website=adevarul.ro|language=en|access-date=2019-03-17}}</ref> \n<li>In the [[UK]], an alcoholic lovage [[Liqueur|cordial]] is traditionally mixed with [[brandy]] in the ratio of 2:1 as a [[winter]] drink.<ref>[http://www.farehamwinecellar.co.uk/0/4c7a5def1b38652380256a73004609dc.html Information on Lovage Cordial] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111006225825/http://www.farehamwinecellar.co.uk/0/4c7a5def1b38652380256a73004609dc.html |date=2011-10-06 }}</ref> \n</ul>\n\nThe roots, which contain a heavy, volatile oil, are used as a mild [[aquaretic]].<ref name=\"EMA1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ema.europa.eu/docs/en_GB/document_library/Herbal_-_Community_herbal_monograph/2012/05/WC500126835.pdf |title= Community herbal monograph on Levisticum officinale Koch, radix | accessdate=2015-07-28 |date=2012-03-27 |format=pdf |publisher=European Medicines Agency}}</ref> Lovage root contains [[furanocoumarins]] which can lead to [[photosensitivity]].<ref name=\"pmid1395606\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Ashwood-Smith MJ, Ceska O, Yeoman A, Kenny PG |title=Photosensitivity from harvesting lovage (Levisticum officinale). |journal=Contact Dermatitis. |volume=26 |issue=5 |pages=356\u20137 | date=May  1993 |pmid=1395606 |doi=10.1111/j.1600-0536.1992.tb00138.x}}</ref>\nIn Romania it is also used dried and with seeds to conserve and to add flavour to pickled cabbage and cucumbers.<ref name=\"adevarul\">{{cite web |title=Cum faci cele mai gustoase mur\u0103turi. |url=https://adevarul.ro/locale/calarasi/cum-faci-cele-mai-gustoase-muraturi-legume-combini-condimente-pastreaza-tari-cata-sare-pune-1_5b8259ebdf52022f75ce6e56/index.html |website=Adevarul newspaper |accessdate=17 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Etymology==\n[[File:Unser Liebst\u00f6ckel.jpg|thumb|upright|A lovage plant beginning to bloom in June, {{cvt|2.78|m|ftin}} tall]]\nThe name \"lovage\" is from \"love-ache\", ''ache'' being a medieval name for [[parsley]]; this is a [[folk etymology|folk-etymological]] corruption of the older French name ''levesche'', from late Latin ''levisticum'', in turn thought to be a corruption of the earlier Latin ''ligusticum'', \"of [[Liguria]]\" (northwest Italy), where the herb was grown extensively.<ref name=\"OED\">{{cite OED|term=lovage|id=110562}}</ref> In modern botanical usage, both Latin forms are now used for different (but closely related) genera, with ''Levisticum'' for (culinary) lovage, and ''[[Ligusticum]]'' for Scots lovage, a similar species from northern Europe, and for related species.<ref name=\"OED\"/> \n\n===Other languages===\n<li>Bulgarian {{lang|bg|\u0434\u0435\u0432\u0435\u0441\u0438\u043b}} (''{{transl|bg|devesil}}'')\n<li>Czech ''{{lang|cs|libe\u010dek}}'' meaning \"love herb\"\n<li>Croatian ''{{lang|hr|ljup\u010dac}}'' or ''{{lang|hr|vegeta}}'' (named after [[Vegeta (condiment)|Vegeta]], a well-known Croatian food seasoning)\n<li>Dutch one of the common names of lovage is ''{{lang|nl|Maggiplant}}'' because the plant's taste is reminiscent of [[Maggi]] soup seasoning<ref>{{cite book | author = Udo Pini | title = Das Gourmet Handbuch | isbn = 978-3-8480-0584-0}}</ref>\n<li>Finnish ''{{lang|fi|liperi}}'' or ''{{lang|fi|lipstikka}}'', the former meaning \"preacher's collar\", because the plant was cultivated in monasteries or in rectories, while the latter is from Swedish, the second language spoken in Finland\n<li>French ''{{lang|fr|liv\u00e8che}}''\n<li>German ''{{lang|de|Liebst\u00f6ckel}}''<ref>Source: http://www.dict.cc/?s=Liebst%C3%B6ckel, see also German Wikipedia article</ref> but one of the common names of lovage is ''{{lang|de|Maggikraut}}'' because the plant's taste is reminiscent of [[Maggi]] soup seasoning<ref>{{cite book | author = Udo Pini | title = Das Gourmet Handbuch | isbn = 978-3-8480-0584-0}}</ref>\n<li>Hungarian ''{{lang|hu|lesty\u00e1n}}''\n<li>Italian ''{{lang|it|levistico}}'' or ''{{lang|it|sedano di monte}}''\n<li>Norwegian ''{{lang|no|l\u00f8pstikke}}''\n<li>Polish ''{{lang|pl|lubczyk}}'' meaning \"love herb\"\n<li>Romanian ''{{lang|ro|leu\u015ftean}}''\n<li>Russian {{lang|ru|\u043b\u044e\u0431\u0438\u0441\u0442\u043e\u043a}} (''{{transl|ru|lyubistok}}'') \n<li>Slovak ''{{lang|sk|ligur\u010dek}}''\n<li>Swedish ''{{lang|sv|libbsticka}}''\n<li>Turkish ''{{lang|tr|yaban kerevizi}}''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Commons category-inline|Levisticum officinale|''Levisticum officinale''}}\n\n{{Herbs & spices}}\n{{Edible Apiaceae}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q27615}}\n\n[[Category:Edible Apiaceae]]\n[[Category:Medicinal plants]]\n[[Category:Perennial plants]]\n[[Category:Plants described in 1824]]\n[[Category:Apioideae]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the band|Lovage (band)}}\n{{speciesbox\n| name = Lovage\n| image = Liebst\u00f6ckel.JPG\n| display_parents = 2\n| genus = Levisticum\n| parent_authority = [[John Hill (author)|Hill]]\n| species = officinale\n| authority = [[Wilhelm Daniel Joseph Koch|W.D.J.Koch]]\n}}\n\n'''Lovage''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|l|\u028c|v|\u1d7b|d\u0292}}), '''''Levisticum officinale''''', is a tall [[perennial plant]], the sole species in the genus '''''Levisticum''''' in the family [[Apiaceae]], subfamily [[Apioideae]].<ref>{{cite book |author1=Pimenov, M. G. |author2=Leonov, M. V.  |lastauthoramp=yes | date = 1993 | title = The Genera of the Umbelliferae | publisher = Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew | isbn = 0-947643-58-3}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | author = Downie, S. R., Plunkett, G. M., Watson, M. F., Spalik, K., Katz-Downie, D. S., Valiejo-Roman, C. M., Terentieva, E. I., Troitsky, A. V., Lee, B.-Y., Lahham, J., and El-Oqlah, A. | date = 2001 | title = Tribes and clades within Apiaceae subfamily Apioideae: the contribution of molecular data | journal = Edinburgh Journal of Botany | volume = 58 | issue = 2 | pages = 301\u2013330 | doi=10.1017/s0960428601000658}}</ref> It has been long cultivated in Europe, the leaves being used as a herb, the roots as a vegetable, and the seeds as a spice, especially in southern European cuisine.\n\n==Description==\n[[File:Levisticum officinale 002.jpg|thumb|upright|Lovage flowers]]\nLovage is an erect, herbaceous, perennial plant growing to {{convert|1.8\u20132.5|m|ft|abbr=on}} tall, with a basal rosette of leaves and stems with further leaves, the flowers being produced in umbels at the top of the stems. The stems and leaves are shiny [[glabrousness|glabrous]] green to yellow-green and smell somewhat similar to celery when crushed. The larger basal leaves are up to {{convert|70|cm|in|abbr=on}} long, tripinnate, with broad triangular to rhomboidal, acutely pointed leaflets with a few marginal teeth; the stem leaves are smaller, and less divided with few leaflets. The flowers are yellow to greenish-yellow, {{convert|2\u20133|mm|in|abbr=on}} diameter, produced in globose umbels up to {{convert|10\u201315|cm|in|abbr=on}} diameter; flowering is in late spring. The fruit is a dry two-parted [[schizocarp]] {{convert|4\u20137|mm|in|abbr=on}} long, mature in autumn.<ref>Interactive Flora of NW Europe: [http://ip30.eti.uva.nl/BIS/flora.php?selected=beschrijving&menuentry=soorten&id=3303 ''Levisticum officinale'' (Lovage)]{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Distribution==\nThe exact native range is disputed; some sources cite it as native to much of [[Europe]] and southwestern [[Asia]],<ref name=\"Virtuella\">Den virtuella floran: [http://linnaeus.nrm.se/flora/di/apia/levis/levioff.html ''Levisticum officinale''] {{in lang|sv}}, with [http://linnaeus.nrm.se/flora/di/apia/levis/levioffv.jpg map]</ref> others from only the eastern Mediterranean region in southeastern Europe and southwestern Asia,<ref name=\"Huxley\">{{cite book | editor = Huxley, A. | date = 1992 | title = New RHS Dictionary of Gardening | isbn = 0-333-47494-5}}</ref> and yet others only to southwestern Asia in [[Iran]] and [[Afghanistan]], citing European populations as [[naturalisation (biology)|naturalised]].<ref name=\"Blamey\">{{cite book |author1=Blamey, M.  |author2=Grey-Wilson, C.  |lastauthoramp=yes | date = 1989 | title = Illustrated Flora of Britain and Northern Europe | isbn = 0-340-40170-2}}</ref><ref>{{GRIN | accessdate = 11 December 2017}}</ref> It has been long cultivated in Europe, the [[leaf|leaves]] being used as an herb, the roots as a vegetable, and the seeds as a spice, especially in southern European cuisine.<ref name=\"Huxley\"/>\n\n==Properties and uses==\nThe [[leaves]] can be used in [[salad]]s, or to make [[soup]] or season broths, and the [[root]]s can be eaten as a [[vegetable]] or grated for use in salads. Its flavor and smell can be described as a mix of [[celery]] and [[parsley]], but with a higher intensity of both of those flavors. The seeds can be used as a spice, similar to [[fennel]] seeds.<ref name=\"Huxley\"/> \n<ul>\n<li>In [[the Netherlands]], lovage leaves are traditionally cooked with white [[asparagus]] and salt; and srved with boiled eggs.{{citation needed|date=April 2017}}\n<li>In [[Romania]], the leaves are the preferred seasoning for the various local broths, equally as much as parsley or dill.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://adevarul.ro/locale/arad/In-fel-ciorbe-indicat-folosim-leusteanul-multe-frunze-puternic-aromate-putem-pune-1_58ad5cad5ab6550cb8b4767b/index.html|title=\u00cen ce fel de ciorbe este indicat s\u0103 folosim leu\u015fteanul. C\u00e2t de multe frunze puternic aromate putem pune|date=23 February 2017|website=adevarul.ro|language=en|access-date=2019-03-17}}</ref> \n<li>In the [[UK]], an alcoholic lovage [[Liqueur|cordial]] is traditionally mixed with [[brandy]] in the ratio of 2:1 as a [[winter]] drink.<ref>[http://www.farehamwinecellar.co.uk/0/4c7a5def1b38652380256a73004609dc.html Information on Lovage Cordial] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111006225825/http://www.farehamwinecellar.co.uk/0/4c7a5def1b38652380256a73004609dc.html |date=2011-10-06 }}</ref> \n</ul>\n\nThe roots, which contain a heavy, volatile oil, are used as a mild [[aquaretic]].<ref name=\"EMA1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ema.europa.eu/docs/en_GB/document_library/Herbal_-_Community_herbal_monograph/2012/05/WC500126835.pdf |title= Community herbal monograph on Levisticum officinale Koch, radix | accessdate=2015-07-28 |date=2012-03-27 |format=pdf |publisher=European Medicines Agency}}</ref> Lovage root contains [[furanocoumarins]] which can lead to [[photosensitivity]].<ref name=\"pmid1395606\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Ashwood-Smith MJ, Ceska O, Yeoman A, Kenny PG |title=Photosensitivity from harvesting lovage (Levisticum officinale). |journal=Contact Dermatitis. |volume=26 |issue=5 |pages=356\u20137 | date=May  1993 |pmid=1395606 |doi=10.1111/j.1600-0536.1992.tb00138.x}}</ref>\nIn Romania it is also used dried and with seeds to conserve and to add flavour to pickled cabbage and cucumbers.<ref name=\"adevarul\">{{cite web |title=Cum faci cele mai gustoase mur\u0103turi. |url=https://adevarul.ro/locale/calarasi/cum-faci-cele-mai-gustoase-muraturi-legume-combini-condimente-pastreaza-tari-cata-sare-pune-1_5b8259ebdf52022f75ce6e56/index.html |website=Adevarul newspaper |accessdate=17 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Etymology==\n[[File:Unser Liebst\u00f6ckel.jpg|thumb|upright|A lovage plant beginning to bloom in June, {{cvt|2.78|m|ftin}} tall]]\nThe name \"lovage\" is from \"love-ache\", ''ache'' being a medieval name for [[parsley]]; this is a [[folk etymology|folk-etymological]] corruption of the older French name ''levesche'', from late Latin ''levisticum'', in turn thought to be a corruption of the earlier Latin ''ligusticum'', \"of [[Liguria]]\" (northwest Italy), where the herb was grown extensively.<ref name=\"OED\">{{cite OED|term=lovage|id=110562}}</ref> In modern botanical usage, both Latin forms are now used for different (but closely related) genera, with ''Levisticum'' for (culinary) lovage, and ''[[Ligusticum]]'' for Scots lovage, a similar species from northern Europe, and for related species.<ref name=\"OED\"/> \n\n===Other languages===\n<li>Bulgarian {{lang|bg|\u0434\u0435\u0432\u0435\u0441\u0438\u043b}} (''{{transl|bg|devesil}}'')\n<li>Czech ''{{lang|cs|libe\u010dek}}'' meaning \"love herb\"\n<li>Croatian ''{{lang|hr|ljup\u010dac}}'' or ''{{lang|hr|vegeta}}'' (named after [[Vegeta (condiment)|Vegeta]], a well-known Croatian food seasoning)\n<li>Dutch one of the common names of lovage is ''{{lang|nl|Maggiplant}}'' because the plant's taste is reminiscent of [[Maggi]] soup seasoning<ref>{{cite book | author = Udo Pini | title = Das Gourmet Handbuch | isbn = 978-3-8480-0584-0}}</ref>\n<li>Finnish ''{{lang|fi|liperi}}'' or ''{{lang|fi|lipstikka}}'', the former meaning \"preacher's collar\", because the plant was cultivated in monasteries or in rectories, while the latter is from Swedish, the second language spoken in Finland\n<li>French ''{{lang|fr|liv\u00e8che}}''\n<li>German ''{{lang|de|Liebst\u00f6ckel}}''<ref>Source: http://www.dict.cc/?s=Liebst%C3%B6ckel, see also German Wikipedia article</ref> but one of the common names of lovage is ''{{lang|de|Maggikraut}}'' because the plant's taste is reminiscent of [[Maggi]] soup seasoning<ref>{{cite book | author = Udo Pini | title = Das Gourmet Handbuch | isbn = 978-3-8480-0584-0}}</ref>\n<li>Hungarian ''{{lang|hu|lesty\u00e1n}}''\n<li>Italian ''{{lang|it|levistico}}'' or ''{{lang|it|sedano di monte}}''\n<li>Norwegian ''{{lang|no|l\u00f8pstikke}}''\n<li>Polish ''{{lang|pl|lubczyk}}'' meaning \"love herb\"\n<li>Romanian ''{{lang|ro|leu\u015ftean}}''\n<li>Russian {{lang|ru|\u043b\u044e\u0431\u0438\u0441\u0442\u043e\u043a}} (''{{transl|ru|lyubistok}}'') \n<li>Slovak ''{{lang|sk|ligur\u010dek}}''\n<li>Swedish ''{{lang|sv|libbsticka}}''\n<li>Turkish ''{{lang|tr|yaban kerevizi}}''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Commons category-inline|Levisticum officinale|''Levisticum officinale''}}\n\n{{Herbs & spices}}\n{{Edible Apiaceae}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q27615}}\n\n[[Category:Edible Apiaceae]]\n[[Category:Medicinal plants]]\n[[Category:Perennial plants]]\n[[Category:Plants described in 1824]]\n[[Category:Apioideae]]\n", "name_user": "Alarichall", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eProperties and uses", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lovage"}
